A sculpture shaped like a fountain. It is made of many clear acrylic rods that curve out from the center and are lit. Nested amongst these lit acrylic rods, there are several hemispheric arrays of small LED lights at varying heights where visitors can speak their feeling of the future. These hemispheres of lights react to your words with different colored patterns.  It has a white tall center shaped like a column, consisting of fins organized radially around the center. It has colored lights diffusing through fabric that displays a colorful combination of all visitors’ feelings.

A horizontal, postcard sized letter written on a typewriter in black ink on yellowing paper. Faded post office stamps in black ink cover some text and indicate where and when it was sent from. The letter reads: 

BOARD OF EDUCATION OF THE CITY OF NEW YORK, N.Y. Thursday. 

Dear Jackie, For the sake of the many School Children of New York, City. Please donot quit baseball They all love you so much. You have a few years left to play. We will be out there rooting for you next summer. 

Money means alot; but it isn’t everything. Please Please Please Signed All the Children

Painting of Jackie Robinson with a yellow background for the top three-quarters of the page and bright green, representing a baseball field, in the bottom. Robinson’s portrait, where he stares intensely into the distance shows him in a navy-blue hat and white jersey with navy blue stripes on the collar. In the foreground, a smaller scene of Robinson sliding into home plate, which is guarded by a catcher.

A white diamond-shaped sign that says “National Postal Museum Baseball America’s Home Run” in blue, red, and white. It has a picture of a baseball left of the bottom corner. The sign is suspended above the Postmaster’s Gallery entrance (the exhibit‘s location) on a grass green arch with pentagon-shaped white bases to represent home plates and large three-dimensional baseballs on top of both posts.
A color photograph of Secretary Lonnie Bunch (left) and Sonya Pankey (right). They are both standing, smiling and wearing formal clothing.
Pink water lily with yellow petals at center. Below it, lily pads in light and dark green and dark water. Sunny day.
Half-length seated illustrated portrait of Mary McLeod Bethune. Her face, with a gentle expression, is rendered in great detail. Her clothing appears in a more loosely sketched style.
Evening painting of the ocean at night, with perhaps three sailboats. The water is dark blue. The sky is lighter blue. Thick gold frame around the painting.

Block of four connected U.S. stamps, all two-cents. Text around stamps says National Parks Centennial and Cape Hatteras National Seashore. Each of the stamps shows part of one beach scene, showcasing driftwood with seagulls, dune plants, people fishing, a lighthouse, and the waves.
Wide painting of a beach scene. The sky, sea, and sand each occupy one third of the space. The water is green-blue with white crests.

Woven tapestry with think stripes of blue, white, black, and one red coming from left to right across the rectangular area. Upper right has thinner lines of white, grey, brown, and blue. It suggests a peaceful body of water or mountains.
Painting with loose, casual brush strokes showing a beach scene with many people in colorful clothing, homes and church in background, ships on the blue sea, and fluffy white clouds above.
Blustery grey-is beach painting with sand that has stripes of yellow-brown seaweed on it, a leafless thin tree trunk, a ship in distance, and a house in distance, and big clouds.
Portable wooden writing desk with a writing surface and storage drawer.
Illustration of American flag on brown pole. Yellow/orange background.

Illustrated portrait of Jose Sarria in a blue dress with white details on shoulders and wrists, long layered necklaces, tiara in an up-do hair style, and scepter. Behind Sarria, a city streetscape and "Black Cafe" text.

2. Organize transportation. Our time is short! We have to get thousands of people to Washington on short notice. Set up your transportation committee at once and have a hardworking and reliable person head it up. Investigate carefully the possibility of bringing your group by train--it is a little more expensive but special rates are available, and the more who come by rail, the less congestion there will be on the roads. If you come by bus make sure that you have a written contract issued in advance and that the bus company has a group insurance policy in effect that covers all members of the group.

Text on cover of brochure: Marsh on Washington For Jobs and Freedom / August 28, 1963 / Organizing Manual No. 1. 

Below the title is a brief introduction explaining that this edition of the manual is to help march delegations start organizing now and that a second edition will be published before the march with final details. 

At the bottom is printed National Office / March on Washington / For Jobs and Freedom / 170 West 130th STREET / NEW YORK 27, NEW YORK / Filmore 8-1900] and in the bottom left is [Cleveland Robinson / Chairman, Administrative Committee] and in the bottom right is Bayard Rustin / Deputy Director.

Draped canvas held to wall at five high points like mountain peaks, with fabric flowing down cowl-like below. Colors range from purple to gold and yellow, some with a marbled effect. In museum gallery setting.

In a museum gallery, draped canvas dangling from string is painted in vivid colors, including purples and reds on top as well as darker reds and blues towards the part of the canvas that is closest to the floor.
Graphic for Smithsonian National Education Summit with yellow and blue geometric shapes in a stair-like pattern. Text: July 27-28, 2022. Online. Washington DC.
Display case in museum gallery with a musical instrument, posters, clothing, and other items.
Museum gallery with text ¡Presente! in gold
Clay tree sculpture with people and butterflies, intricately painted.
Clay sculpture of a tree with rounded branches and small figures and butterflies. On display in museum gallery. Text on wall in background: shaping the nation.

A man with brown skin faces his demise on a dismasted, rudderless fishing boat, sustained by only a few stalks of sugarcane, while threatened by sharks and a distant waterspout. He is oblivious to the schooner on the left horizon
Comic illustration of Richard Nixon, shirtless, in a small boat with a broken mast. It is surrounded by sharks and his face looks dismayed. Inside the boat are opinion polls and tape recordings.

Based on the Great Seal of the United States, this portrait features President Nixon’s photograph collaged on the head of the eagle. The lower portion is split into photographs Henry Kissinger, John N. Mitchell, John Ehrlichman, and H. R. “Bob” Haldeman.

Cartoon-style illustration of seven white men in business suits, President Nixon in center. They are wrapped in electrical cords, recording equipment. The men around Nixon point fingers at each other.

White text: Smithsonian Folklife Festival, June 22–27 and June 30–July 4, National Mall, Washington, D.C. Image underneath the text shows a woman and young girl, each with a falcon perched on her arm, on top of a sand dune.
Four adult women and one young child stand in the desert. There hold falcons. One of the falcons has its wings spread wide.
Wide panoramic photo of soldiers posing, the front row sitting cross legged.

Two elaborate face masks on display in museum case. On left, mask included a woman with brown skin and Afro hair style raising up a sign that says “Stop Killing Us.” Her face masks says BLM. She holds additional signs with text Stop Police Brutality and I Can’t Breathe. The other masks includes a portrait of George Floyd with eyes closed.
Sixteen rectangles in shades of black on left. On right, sixteen rectangles in shades of pink. All arranged in a neat grid.
Black-footed ferret with long neck extended, ears perked, and eyes looking directly into camera. Very alert. It's on a grassy landscape.
Wild bison facing directly towards the viewer. Its beard-area is a bit grey, the rest of it brown and fluffy. Two light brown horns. It's in a grassy landscape with a few trees in background.
Logo with semi-circle painted with a brush in colors of green, blue, yellow. Text: earth optimism x Folklife.
Posed group photo of about 17 adults on the brick steps of a building with white columns.
Eight satellite dishes pointed at the evening sky, where stars are visible. They are located in a desert-like landscape with hills.
Makeshift raft. Stacked styrofoam planks held together with tar carved into the shape of a boat and placed on a wooden frame.
Long sleeve, short dress with vivid floral pattern. On black are large flowers in yellow, blue, and light pink.
White woven shawl on a form, pinned at neck/chest area.
Speaker at podium with large bouquet in foreground, framed by two small trees. Seated on stage, about seven adults. All wear graduation attire.

Painting of a woman in magenta skirt and green striped top with medium brown skin cradling a sleeping baby wrapped in lavender blankets. She sits in a red chair. The wall behind her has a blue section on left and yellow on right.
Graphic with orange donut-like shape of a block hole in space. Text: A special event. The quest to image black holes. Thursday, May 12. 3 p.m. ET. Center for Astrophysics | Harvard & Smithsonian.

Two men stand on the National Mall in front of the Smithsonian Castle. On left, Lonnie Bunch. On right, Kevin Gover. Both smile. Each holds a face mask in hand. It's a cloudy, grey day.

Qur’an, laying open. Framed in red and blue rectangles, each page has an identical medallion, a circle outlined in clue and red with open center. The medallions are decorated with red, blue, and lavender flowers and heart shapes, some of which have wispy vines.

Butterfly signature drawn in pencil with curly wing tips.
Room with large artwork depicting two dramatic gold peacocks on blue background. Gold shelves with blue green walls hold white and blue vases and other glassware.
Person with gardening gloves in a garden with planted rows of vegetables and flowers. Behind her, a golden-brown wall of a museum and blue sky.
Person behind a gallery cart with text Object Project Bicycles = Liberation. She stands in a museum gallery. On cart, objects related to bicycles.
A woman in red shirt mops the floor of the turtle/tortoise enclosure at the National Zoo. In front of her, two very large turtles. One has its long neck extended.
Screenshot of a Zoom featuring 20 participants, all with video on. Each smiling person holds up a sign, many handmade. The signs say "thank you!"

Three people gather around a computer monitor on which is displayed the live video of a volunteer talking about space shuttle Discovery. Behind the screen, the real Discovery tends in the National Air and Space Museum. Above it, other space exploration-related objects.
Five adults pose in front of a museum information desk. Behind them, signage reads African American History and Culture. They wear facemarks.

Museum gallery with many framed photos on wall. All photos are black and white, sepia, or documents. A person stands in front, looking up at the photos. We see her back and purse. There are two 3D objects in the space. One appears to be a textile, the other appears to be a wood-framed glass box or case.
Museum gallery with five cases, dramatically lit with green and blue background. Bust-length figured in each case wear wide hats.
Purple orchid with light yellow center, green leaves. Black background.

Two pandas outdoors. They face each other, gesturing with paws.

Circular pewter plate is engraved with markings for Seder. The plate is of 18th century German origins. “Priest, Levite, Israelite” is inscribed in Hebrew across the center with a crown and Stars of David as decoration.

Pinback button of Jackie Robinson. With the words [I'M ROOTING FOR JACKIE ROBINSON] at the top and [DODGERS] at the bottom. Attached to the bottom of the pin is a small charm in the shape of a baseball. A red, white, and blue striped ribbon is attached to the back of the pin.
Black and white matted photo of Marian Anderson on steps of Lincoln Memorial before microphones. Large crowd visible to her side and part of piano. She wears a fur coat and long dress.
Grey button-up, collarless baseball jersey with blue piping and text Dodgers in blue. On display in exhibit case along with a baseball and a program from a Dodgers game.
Cuatro adultos frente a un museo. Hay palabras en oro. El Museo del Canal Interoceánico de Panamá.
Four adults pose in front of an exterior white wall. On wall in raised gold text: Museo del Canal Interoceano de Panama.
Museum gallery with industrial look, including chainlink fence and cinder block pillars. About seven outfits are displayed on hangers, including an all-red jacket and pant combination.
Museum gallery with long, flat case containing objects and exhibit labels on paper plates. A scrim panel is titled "The People Behind the Plate." A TV monitor is visible in background.

Half-length portrait of Mary McLeod Bethune, seated wearing blazer and button-up collared shirt with brooch at collar. Her clothing is outlined but not colored in, as though incomplete. In contrast, her face, eyes open wide and lips in a smile, is extremely detailed. Her skin is dark brown and her hair, laying flat to her head and pulled back, is black.
Half-length black and white photo of Eleanor Roosevelt wearing hat and jacket. Cheek rests on one fist. Both hands visible, with rings and bracelet. She smiles.
Bust-length portrait of Madeleine Albright wearing a dark navy suit with gold dove pin on shoulder and gold dove earrings. She looks directly into the camera, a sly smile. Background is burgundy red.

Black and white photo of an African American woman wearing glasses and lab coat seated at a microscope in an office/lab environment. In front of her is a glass jar, lamp, papers. Behind her, a typewriter.
Painted portrait of Supreme Court Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg in robe with long white collar.
Pencil portrait of Zora Martin-Felton, with short hair with lots of volume and a big smile showing her teeth. She radiates happiness.
A white, square-shaped shawl made of silk lace and linen, on a mannequin.

Book of hymns by P.P. Bliss and Ira D. Sankey, 112-pages, discolored cover with black printing, text and binding. Text reads "Gospel hymns No. 2, BY PP. BLISS AND IRA D. SANKEY AS USED BY THEM IN GOSPEL MEETINGS."

Two identical posters with blue background, green text, and three stylized portraits of women's faces in white with green lines. Text: Achieve equality of opportunity for women, through recruitment, hiring, training, and promotions.
Ten-cent US postage stamp with text International Women's Year. Symbols include a globe, female symbol, and white dove.

Red poster with a large "M" in center. Inside the M is a stylized white dove with the symbol for "female." The M is outlined in yellow, black, and green. Other text on poster: Mexico 75. Año Internacional de la Mujer. Programs de Mexico. Participe activamente.
More than a dozen bright orange statues of women scientists on display in a garden on a sunny day. In background, Smithsonian Castle.
Orange statue of a woman holding books or notepads in the courtyard of a museum building. Behind her, a light-up art installation.
Orange statue of woman with hands on hips. Behind her, another state holding something in hand. In background, Smithsonian Castle.

Graphic with two portions of a historic document. Typed letterhead: “Headquarters Office Assistant Superintendent 

BUREAU OF REGUEES FREEDMAN AND A. L. 

Salisbury, NC.” Handwritten date: Nov 15 1865. In cursive, text of letter: Mr. Robert Bell You will please settle justly with the colored girl Eliza or appear on Monday the 20 show cause why you have not done so

Photo of quote on gallery wall. “It was a hard thing having to build that school for the white boys when I had no right to educate my son. Then when the war was over and they bought that building for our children, I could hardly believe my eyes—looking at my own little ones carrying their books under their arms, coming from the same school the Lord really raised up for them.” - Ambrose Headen, recalling the establishment of a freedmen’s school in Talladega, Alabama.

Graphic with two portions of a historic, typed form with handwritten responses. Text:  

  

Ed. Form, No. 3. 

TEACHER'S MONTHLY SCHOOL REPORT 

For the Month of August, 1868.  

To contain one entire calendar month, and be forwarded as soon as possible after the close of the month.  

  

Number in Alphabet? 23 

Number who spell, and read easy lessons? 44 

Number in advanced readers? 40 

Number in Geography? 34 

Number in Arithmetic? 34

Museum gallery with panels and graphics that show mostly black-and-white images and documents, with blue overlay in some locations. Big text reads: Make Good the Promises. Reconstruction and Its Legacies.

Seven people stand and pose for a picture, including five women. In center, Lonnie Bunch III holds a yellow orchid in a blue pot. They are in the interior courtyard of a museum. Behind them, a purple sign says "Orchids."

An African American man, Lonnie G. Bunch III, stands in the interior courtyard of a museum. In his hands, a blue pot with "Smithsonian 175" logo and a yellow and orange orchid in bloom with seven flowers on it. He wears a face mask and windbreaker.

Black and white photo of sign on a brick wall. Text: Martin Luther King Co-Op Store. 1101 7th Street S.E. Basement. Manager Mrs. Beatrice Gray. Friendship House Consumer Advisor. Asst. Manager mr. Wm. Graham.

Mural outside the Smithsonian’s Anacostia Community Museum. It shows five hands raised and holding produce. A hand holding a squash with text “squash the system.” One holding a beet has the text “beet hunger.” In center “Food for the the People.” “Turnip for Justice.” “No justice, no peas.”
Two diner-style swivel stools with cushions, one pink and one blue. The back rest and frame of the seat are chrome plated metal.
In museum display, a lunch counter with four stools, two pink, two blue. Above it, photo of African American people doing a sit-in at that very counter.
Orange tailored silk shantung jacket and black velvet skirt worn by Marian Anderson at her Lincoln Memorial Concert in 1939.
Black and white photo. Marian Anderson, in long for coat, stands before a cluster of microphones. Part of a piano visible behind her. Behind her also are columns of Lincoln Memorial.
Lonnie G. Bunch III and John Lewis stand side by side, each with hands clasped in front of them. Lonnie looks down and smiles. John leans towards him. They both wear suits.
Circular metallic button with initials GW in center circle and “long live the President” around the initials. In individual circles, acronyms of 12 US states.

Graphic with Smithsonian National Museum of African Art logo. In red text: Iké Udé: Nollywood Portraits. In white graffiti-style text: African is beautiful Nollywood is beautiful You are beautiful. In center, portrait of woman unglamorous black dress.
A row of four portraits above a photo of a round table covered in various dishes as a group dines around it.
Muhammad Ali jumping rope wearing sweatpants and sneakers. Behind him, American flag. Black and white indoor photo.

A round pinback button featuring a black and white portrait of Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. in the center. Printed above and around in white text on blue background is [POOR PEOPLES CAMPAIGN], directly below in blue text on white background is [FOR POOR POWER]. In the center, divided by the portrait are the words ["I have a dream..."] in blue text. Below the portrait, in white text on blue background is [Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr.], followed by a union printer's symbol.
US quarter featuring portrait of Maya Angelou with arms raised within the silhouette of a bird in flight.
Man in suit signs autographs. Young men and women offer items for him to sign.
Betty White smiles and holds a small bright green frog in her hands in front of an aquarium.

White text on black background reads: 

June 28, 2019 (written on 50th Anniversary of the Stonewall Uprising)

To Whom It May Concern: artists, curators, museum directors, archivists and “rural artists, artists of color, and artists who are LGBTQ or non-binary.” (that’s me.)

(artists who identify in these ways were largely absent from the original project from 1977 and their inclusion is a curatorial priority in this 2019 version.)

Let this letter serve as a placeholder that for “What is Feminist Art?” a project of the Archives of American Art, the Smithsonian American Women’s History Initiative, and a team of outside curators, that artist fees/honorariums were NOT offered to artists and cultural producers asked to participate in the project. Also of note is that the Archives of American Art is requesting that all “documents” received for the project, “What is Feminist Art,” be donated to the permanent collection.

As a queer, gender non-conforming, non-binary person in the arts and

Text reads: 

Nora Naranjo Morse-

I was born in a Tewa matriarch community in northern New Mexico. 

I was raised by women who mud plastered their homes with children on their hips while food simmered in vessels they’d coiled with clay.

Women warriors who move through the portals of creativity believing that building a home and growing food is the same as creating magnificent art. 

Forces of nature who’s ground breaking innovations in clay came from the no nonsense matriarchs who’ve echoed resilience and strength for generations. 

I was born into women who were unaware of western concepts of feminism but who were the standard bearers of the basic concept. 

I was born into a community of women who modeled living an artful life. 

(Tewa-one of six Pueblo villages situated along the Rio Grande in New Mexico. Pueblos are generally distinguished by language groups.)

Rectangular paper with ombre white to pink from top to bottom. On top, handwritten red cursive text reads, "Feminist art is all the stages of a woman giving birth to herself." In between two columns of text, eight icon-like drawings show interpretations of the stages of birth, ranging from biological in nature to a geometric triangle. On left, a vulva-like drawing is larger than the eight icon-sized drawings.

Museum gallery with two cases that contain rectangular artworks/documents. On the wall, title text says: "What is feminist art?" in English and Spanish. A quote on another wall reads: "Feminist art is always emerging."

By William Shulz

This country scene evokes the Brandywine River valley of Smedley’s youth. The woman’s face glows as she banters with her surprise visitor, who leans into the shadowy room from the sun-drenched field beyond. Smedley’s skill in bringing a story to life shows in this image. We can feel the heat of summer, the cool of the interior, and the excitement of the courting couple.

Sagittarius A*, the supermassive black hole at the center of our galaxy, appears as an orange donut-like structure on a black background. Glowing gas orbiting around the black hole reveals a telltale signature: a dark central region (called a “shadow”) surrounded by a bright ring-like structure.

An image of the center of the Milky Way combines data from NASA's three Great Observatories, or space-based telescopes. In this image, X-rays from the Chandra X-ray Observatory are blue and violet, near-infrared emission from the Hubble Space Telescope is yellow, and Spitzer's infrared data are red.

Event graphic. It includes photographs of people in black-and-white and the program title: Smithson to Smithsonian: Expanding our Story. The discussion is at 5 PM ET on August 31 and folks can register at s.si.edu/Expanding-Story

Men woman and children walk near the Independence Avenue entrance of the Arts and Industries Building. It is clear that these visitors were there around the turn of the century by their style of clothing. The men and boys wear suits and hats and the women and girls wear long dresses and skirts. The women are also wearing hats.

Closeup of the portrait of James Smithson from the National Portrait Gallery. He is wearing a blue suit jacket and a white scarf. He has graying hair and gray-blue eyes. He is looking directly at the artist.
An American bison stands in the snow in front of a wooden structure. The bison's head is turned directly toward the camera.
A U.S. ten dollar bill that features an American bison at the center. Portraits of two men are on either side of the buffalo.
Portrait of a young woman with short, wavy hair. She is looking directly at the camera with a slight smile.
A CD from a recent collection with a detailed ink-written label. This information is recorded in the Archives’ Collection Management System (CMS).

Banana-Chocolate Chip Cake recipe. You’ll need 1/2 cup margarine. 1 cup sugar. 2 eggs. 3 med banana m. 2 cups flour. 1 tsp. baking soda. 1/2 tsp. salt. 1 package (6 oz) chocolate chips, 1 tsp. vanilla. Frosting: 1 cup of confectioners sugar. 2 tbs. milk. Directions: cream margarine (or butter) and sugar. Beat in eggs. Add mashed banana. Add flour, baking soda and salt and vanilla. Stir in chocolate chips. Put into [end].
Mann sits in a chair in a field. A tiger cub sits in her lap. She is feeding the cub from a bottle.
Close up of the tiger cub taking a bottle of milk on Mann's lap.
Image of an article in a newsletter, titled "Profile: Not all of the Smithsonian's treasures are in the collections," by Christine Miller Ford.
A man with a bowtie and thick glasses stares directly into the camera.

Two women wearing bathing suits. Their shoulders are exposed and they are wearing short shorts. Both are standing on a rock with one hand on their hips.

A pygmy hippo cools off in a small bath.

View of the Arts and Industries Building with "1876" signage in the archway at the front.

A coffin covered in a striped flag, possibly the American flag, sits in a room in the Castle. Portraits line the walls.

At left, a brown-haired man leafs through a folder of archival correspondence laying on a white work table, while a brown-haired woman takes notes on her laptop, which is perched atop a gray library cart laden with archival storage boxes.
A rusted paperclip leaves a mark on a document. The paperclip is partially lifted to show the damage because we like to be extra dramatic.

A page from the 1991 Smithsonian annual report that includes highlights from the Smithsonian's Anacostia Community Museum. The photograph featured is of people sitting outside of the Museum in front of a "Juneteenth Celebration '91 'Freedom Revisited'" banner. Black, red, and orange figures dance around the text on the banner. The date on the banner reads June 22, [1991].
Names, occupations, and addresses are listed in small font on the pages. The important line here is: "Malone, Fannie E, clk smithsonian, La Fetra's."

This page is typed, but there are annotations. Lines are struck through. Cursive handwriting fills the spaces between lines. The important note here is that at the end of the first paragraph, Mrs. Malone is listed as a clerk.

There is a lot of information on this typed page about the department's accessions that year and how they were numbered. The line that is important for this post is: "...they [specimens] are then delivered to Mrs. Malone, who is charged with the duty of numbering them."
Cover of the booklet includes the text: Smithsonian Festival of American Folklife 1996. It includes a photograph of people biking on a dirt road with a farm in the background.

Thirteen members of the Smithsonian's department of anthropology staff stand in front of the Arts and Industries Building. Eleven men stand in the back. Two women sit in the front. Oh, and a photoshopped photograph of actor Chris Evans with his hands in his pockets is there, too.
View of manuscript boxes on shelves.
View of large bound volumes wrapped in plastic.
Close up shot of reel canisters labeled Smithsonian World.

Screenshot of a short profile about Hall. It includes a photograph of an older Hall on the force. The quote by Hall reads: "When visitors come in, you make them feel at home and tell them what's in the museum, and they like that. You're nice, but you're still firm. You learn how to deal with people. People come in and you treat them with respect, and they'll always respect you."

Because of Her Story Smithsonian Transcription Center intern Madeleine Roberts-Ganim appears in a black, long-sleeved shirt and jeans, she has long, dark hair and is smiling at the camera. Madeleine's quote on her experience as an intern for the National Museum of African American History and Culture and Transcription Center Freedmen's Bureau Transcription Project reads: "This summer, I had the incredible opportunity to explore, transcribe, and share the stories of American women in the Freedmen’s Bureau records. The invaluable primary sources found on Transcription Center make learning about the past exciting and experiential. They provide an intimate window into the daily lives of freedwomen during Reconstruction — essential knowledge that I never could have learned just by reading a textbook." Head to www.transcription.si.edu/freedmensbureau to learn more about the Freedmen's Bureau records.

Because of Her Story Smithsonian Transcription Center intern, Jenna Lugo. Jenna has dark, curly hair, and is smiling at the camera. A quote from Jenna about her experience interning with the National Museum of African American History and Culture and the Transcription Center on the Freedmen's Bureau Transcription Project reads: "Working with the Transcription Center and NMAAHC in the Freedmen’s Bureau records for the Because of Her Story internship has been instrumental in expanding my passion for 19th-century history. Diving into the records while researching women has been both fascinating and inspiring, fostering my interest in giving voice back to everyday individuals in the records." Head to www.transcription.si.edu/freedmensbureau to learn more about the Freedmen's Bureau Records.

Top portion of a Smithsonian Transcription Center 19th Century Cursive Alphabet Chart, created by Jenna Lugo and Madeleine Roberts-Ganim. The chart lists English alphabet characters (included in this top portion are letters A - E), with capitalized and lowercase examples of handwritten, cursive, letters from the Freedmen's Bureau Records. In the background of this graphic is a handwritten letter from the Freedmen's Bureau Records as well.

An 1899 edition, hardcover, octavo book of Poems of Cabin and Field by Paul Laurence Dunbar with black and white photographs by the Hampton Institute Camera Club. Purple graphic with a handwritten Freedmen's Bureau letter on the left, and a typed transcription on the right: ""Raleigh, N.C., April 9, 1868.

Lieutenant, 
Your letter of the 6th inst., asking my assistance in procuring a teacher for Jamesville, was recd yesterday. I know at present no suitable person for the place unless it may be Miss Josephine Cropper, a colored teacher from Philadelphia, who is just now in this city. She has been teaching at Wake Forest (ten miles from here). The colored people there, I am informed, were very much pleased with her...." Find a full transcription here: https://transcription.si.edu/transcribe/34994/NMAAHC-007497958_00714.

Handwritten letter in blue ink on yellowed paper. The page reads: 
Plant
January 6, 1948

Dearest Mama,
Well, your baby is back at the grind again, but she misses her mother and daddy so much.
Everyone was all excited and dead tired. After clearing my room I fell into bed in the wee hours of the morning. I got up at 20 mins of ten this a.m. I'm still a little beat, but I'll get rested soon.

Quote from Dr. Paul Gardullo, Director of the Center for the Study of Global Slavery at the National Museum of African American History and Culture, which reads: ...to know that our transcribers were working to let the words of B.C. Franklin’s unpublished document “The Tulsa Race Riot and Three of Its Victims” live and breathe 100 years after the event was deeply moving and a powerful part of the restorative and reparative process that good history work can do. Connecting with and sharing in those experiences with transcribers helped me to process the sometimes painful part of this work, realize the immense importance of what we do, and recognize the power in our ability to work collectively and collaboratively to tell the truth in hope of making change.

Yellowed page from the 15th-century rare book, "De institutione arithmetica," copied from the original by 6th century Roman philosopher Boethius. Purple graphic featuring a handwritten letter from the Freedmen's Bureau Records (left) and a typed quote from a section of that letter (right). The quote reads: ""...I take the liberty of stating to you what would be agreeable to me as the next best position you can assign to me. 1st. I would like the entire charge of Freedmens affairs in the District of Columbia. reporting to the Assistant Commissioner of this Bureau District. 2d. I desire also to be assigned to the duty from time to time of inspecting and reporting upon the condition of women and children in the several districts of Freedmen." - Josephine S. Griffing to Freedmen's Bureau Commissioner Oliver Otis Howard, May 20, 1865. 

The Transcription Center and NMAAHC Smithsonian logos are underneath the quote. Full document transcription here: https://transcription.si.edu/transcribe/42044/NMAAHC-007675291_00243.

Sepia-toned portrait of African American linguist Lorenzo Dow Turner. He is wearing round glasses, a suit and tie (the tie is striped), and has a small handkerchief in his left breast pocket. Turner's hair is cut short and he is looking into the camera.

Color portrait of African American teacher and researcher Geneva Townes Turner. She is wearing a green top that has a v-neckline, as well as green stud earrings. Her hair is pulled back in a bun on the base of her neck, and is curled against her face at her ear. She is facing slightly away from the camera and has a slight smile on her face.
Sepia-toned portrait of U.S. Airman Helen G. James. James is wearing an Air Force cap and shirt, with a US pin on her left collar. Her hair is cut short and curled, and she is looking at the camer.

Teal graphic with a quote from a Transcription Center Volunteer, Julie, which reads: "I find transcribing historical documents really interesting and  captivating because not only does it provide the opportunity to learn about specific periods in history, but I also gain insight into specific historical accounts and primary source material — learning not solely about certain events in history, but also viewing it through the lens of writers from different sides and perspectives."

Gray graphic featuring a yellowed and worn, bound volume (left) listing names of individuals and dollar amounts paid. The page is dated at the top June 2nd, 1879. A typed transcription of the first part of the bound volume, included on the right, reads: “"June 2nd, 1879," Membership Names and Dues "1 Alexander Albert .25 2 Allens Nancy .75 3 Adams Julia √ 75 4 Bell Minty 5 Bell Mary 6 Brashears Ellen 7 Bowman Leatha..." A citation below the transcription reads: Bladensburg Union Burial Association, Membership Dues Record Book, 1876-1898, Anacostia Community Museum, Smithsonian Transcription Center, https://transcription.si.edu/transcribe/11954/ACM-acma_06-025.7_020. A Smithsonian Transcription Center logo (A brown diary with the Smithsonian yellow and blue sunburst) and a white logo for the Smithsonian Anacostia Community Museum appear at the bottom.

Purple graphic featuring a black and white handwritten letter from the Freedmen’s Bureau in Franklin, North Carolina, dated July 1868 (left). On the right is a typed transcription of a section from the letter which reads: “"...on July 10" one John Allison went to the home of Virgil Bryson. freedman. living near Webster. Jackson Co. and threatened his life if he made any resistance to his proceedings...Also assaulted Bryson with a knife, and threw a rock at him, and threatened to kill him, and to take away his property, and drive him from the place. The freedman was lately a member of the Board of Registration and is a quiet and peaceable citizen." A citation underneath the quote reads: North Carolina Assistant Commissioner, Letters Received, Entered in Register 3, Records of the Bureau of Refugees, Freedmen, and Abandoned Lands, Smithsonian Transcription Center, https://transcription.si.edu/transcribe/12030/NMAAHC-004567398_00638.

Purple graphic featuring a page (left) from “The Freedmen’s Record” journal. Written at the top  is “List of teachers now in service. South Carolina.” The 9th name down, highlighted in purple, is “Harriet Tubman,” noted as teaching in “Hilton Head,” and lists her home as “Auburn, N.Y.” On the right is a carte-de-visite of Harriet Tubman seated in an interior room. Her right hand rests on the back of a wooden chair and her left hand rests in her lap. A boldly patterned carpet covers the floor and the wall behind her is a blank light color. Tubman wears a black bodice that buttons at the center front and has dropped sleeves with heavy ruching and ruffled details on the sleeves. There is a panel of lighter fabric around the yoke, with the upper neck the same dark color as the body of the bodice. A white lace collar with short tails is crossed and pinned at the front of her neck. Her hair is parted at the center and gathered at the nape of her neck. She wears a full skirt.

Scrapbook page belonging to early aviator and balloonist, Lucille Belmont. Glued onto the page are two newspaper clippings - yellowed and faded with age - from the early 20th century, detailing the daring feats of Belmont, and including images of balloons, and a photograph of Belmont in an aviator cap and goggles. The main clipping reads: "Miss Lucille Belmont, The Undisputed World's Champion Aeronaut, Only Lady Making a Triple Parachute Drop."

Black and white photograph of the Harvard College Observatory's "Women Computers" (female astronomers and researchers) studying glass plate negatives of the night sky. Pictured are eight women, dressed in long dresses and with their hair up in buns. Seven women are seated at separate tables and desks looking closely at glass plates with magnifying glasses and taking notes, and one woman is standing above reviewing work. Image is from the early twentieth century.

Yellowed, lined notebook page, listing household items and associated worth (in dollars) from the Obata family. Dated 1942. For a full transcription of this page, see https://transcription.si.edu/view/37107/AAA-AAA_obatchiu_3163996.
Yellowed, lined notebook page with English and Japanese text. For a full transcription see: https://transcription.si.edu/view/37107/AAA-AAA_obatchiu_3164008.

Black and white photograph of Chiura Obata teaching students at his art class at the Tanforan Art School at the Tanforan Assembly Center. Obata is seated with an easel on his lap and a paint brush in his hands. Two children are seated in front of him, also painting, and multiple children are standing in the background.

Black and white portrait of African American signer and actress Joy McLean Bosfield. Bosfield has on pearl earrings and a pearl necklace, her hair is pulled up in a 1940s-era hairstyle, and she is wearing a sweater. A caption on the photograph reads: "To the Dearest Mother! With Joyous love. -Joy"

Black and white portrait of hip-hop artist Jean Grae, 2005. Grae is wearing a t-shirt, and is holding a microphone in her right hand, while her left hand is outstretched. The photograph depicts Grae performing on stage.
Sepia-toned silver and photographic gelatin on photographic paper, c. 1895. A seated portrait of an older Frederick Douglass. Douglass wears a suit with bow tie, jacket and vest.

One-page document with "Principal Office of the Freedmen's Savings and Trust Company" letterhead. Addressed to J. A. J. Creswell, dated July 3, 1874, and signed by the Freedmen's Bank president, Frederick Douglass. See a full transcription of the handwritten letter here: https://transcription.si.edu/project/42143.
Black and white portrait of Dr. Ionia Rollin Whipper. Dr. Whipper has short hair (pinned back) and is wearing an intricately designed dress. Photograph created circa 1920s-1930s.
Bronze sculpture of a woman churning butter with her hand. She is seated, wearing a dress, and working a bowl on her lap.

Black and white photograph of artist Marion Sanford. Sanford is wearing a white button down, collared shirt, and black jacket, with a white handkerchief in the jacket's breast pocket. Her arms are crossed and she is looking away from the camera.

Black and white, handwritten, manuscript page from the Freedmen's Bureau Records. The highlighted section in cursive reads: 
"The Orphan Asylum -
Conducted by Mrs de Mortie is an institution under the control and management of an association of private individuals - and although chiefly supported by the Bureau, I have preferred that it should continue as at present organized, having a hope that it would continue to exist after the military supervision shall have been withdrawn from the State. 
 
Mrs de Mortie has rendered important assistance in taking charge of the helpless that are from time to time thrown upon our hands."

Black and white photograph of Louise de Mortie, date unknown. Louise de Mortie is wearing a dark dress with full skirts, and seated at a high-backed ornate chair. She holds a fan in one hand, and her other hand is placed on a small table to her side.

Yellowed page from the Los Angeles Herald Examiner, dated Sunday, August 10, 1986, featuring a full page story titled: "Firm run by women tries to make a dent in macho profession." Includes a large photograph of architects Margot Siegal, Katherine Diamond, and Norma Merrick Sklarek, co-owners of the architectural firm Siegel-Sklarek-Diamond Architects (SSD).

Black and white contact print photograph of African American architect Norma Merrick Sklarek in the 1980s. Sklarek is seated at a sketch table with a stack of architectural blueprints in front of her. She is wearing a flowered dress and glasses and is smiling at the camera.

One page of a typed document from Welton Beckett Associates Architects and Engineers in Santa Monica, California that lists the accomplishments of African American architect Norma Sklarek (her signature also appears on the bottom of the page).

Digital image of a letter from Christa McAuliffe to Ms. Marcia Holland, dated January 15, 1986. The letter is written on NASA "Teacher in Space Project" letterhead, and reads:

Screenshot of a notebook page from Forman Craton's memoirs, including photographs glued in of his family members - including pictures of "Willie and I" smiling at "Casadaga Outing from Erie, Summer 1926." They are dressed in sweaters and warm clothing, and Willie is wearing a 1920s cloche hat.

Graphic of three pages of a Forman Craton's 1929 letter to his friend, and future wife, Willie Fritschner. The pages are yellowed and include Forman's cursive handwriting. To the right of the pages, is a typed quote from the letter, which reads: "Dearest Willie: Such a New Year's present - the most beautiful gift I ever can receive. Oh, Willie, I am so happy about it....I never dreamed that you had cared for so long, and your Faith and Trust were beautiful...All that matters now is that we love each other...I feel now as though I could conquer the world - solve any problem - do anything, because I love you, and must make good for you. -Forie"

Vertical postcard depicting a drawing of Santa Claus flying in a small biplane and dropping presents (a doll, a toy horse) from the plane to a small, snow-dusted village below. A full Christmas tree is on the front of the plane.

Black and white photograph of painter Dorothea A. Dreier. She is smiling, seated at an easel, with a paintbrush in one hand hand and a canvas in front of her - painted with what appear to be buildings or trees. Dreier is wearing a hat and a high collared shirt and long dress. Circa 1910s.

Sepia toned photograph of Forman Craton, 1938. He is squatting over an outdoor fire on which a grate and cast iron pan have been placed. Forman is holding a metal spatula and is turned, smiling at the camera. He wears a hat, a wool coat, and pants, and tie. There are two people pictured in the background (one on the left and one barely visible on the right). Underneath the picture is handwritten: "Forie," Forman's nickname.

Black and white photograph of artist Emmy Lou Packard, circa 1940s. Packard has her hair pulled up, and is wearing a button down shirt and blazer. She is seated at a sketch desk and is looking over documents and drawings.

Screenshot of a portion of typed notes from an oral history interview with artist Emmy Lou Packard in 1979. The section of text reads: "back from Mexico Nov 1941. Today, without reference to files, I'll type what I remember of the period when I came back from Mexico in November, 1941. I had just spent a year living with Frida and Diego Rivera while I painted for my first one-woman-show. I finished 38 oils and numerous drawings and watercolors that year. My show opened in Los Angeles the same week that the Japanese attacked Pearl Harbor. I was driving back from a breakfast at Mr. and Mrs. Harwell Harris's (architect) when I saw the huge black headlines on the Los Angeles Examiner [Pearl Harbor Bombed]; after that our US world changed rapidly." To read a transcript of the full interview head to https://transcription.si.edu/project/21111.

Color poster issued by the Office of War Information in 1942. The poster is darkly colored with shades of black, brown, red, and gray in the background. A drawing of the upper half of a man - dressed in tattered and torn Navy clothing - is shown on the top part of the poster, he is muscular and has an outstretched fist. Written in red underneath him are the words: "AVENGE December 7." A drawing of a battleship being bombed is included below the words. The poster is signed by the artist, Bernard Perlin, in the lower right corner.

Color propaganda poster issued by the Office of War Information in 1942. Illustrated is a portion of blue sky with clouds with smoke and flames billowing up and covering much of the scene. A flag pole with a tattered and torn American flag is shown in front. White text at the top reads, "...we here highly resolve that these dead shall not have died in vain..." Underneath the flag in red letters is written, "REMEMBER DEC. 7th!" The poster is signed by the artist, Allen Saalburg.

Yellowed, manuscript page from the diary of Alexander Van Valen, dated 1849-1850. This page includes a drawn map of the "Gold Region in California, showing Towns, Ranches, Roads and the point where the first gold was discovered."

First page of a journal belonging to Boston-native, Benjamin S. Buckley, documenting his journey from Boston, Massachusetts to San Francisco, California in 1849. The page is yellowed, and includes cursive handwriting. It begins: "Journal of the Voyage from Boston to San Francisco by B. S. Buckley. Jan 23 1849. At nearly two o clock pm the good ship Capitol, with 200 passengers hauled out from Lewis Wharf into the Channel, preparatory to hoisting Sail for California after giving three hearty Cheers for out friends and the Old Bay State." For a full transcription of all of Buckley's journal, head to the Transcription Center link in tweet.

Sepia toned photograph of Mary Todd Lincoln, which may have been taken in the autumn of 1863. She is wearing a meticulously fashioned black dress, as was customary as she would have been still in mourning for her eleven-year-old son, Willie, who had died of typhoid fever in February 1862. Below her picture is printed text, which reads "Scribner Gift, Entered according to Act of Congress in the Year 1865 by E & H T Anthony in the Clerk's Office of the District Court of hte U.S. for the So District of New York."

A screenshot of the final portion of First Lady Mary Todd Lincoln's letter to President Andrew Johnson. This section reads: "perfect confidence in your hands. I am, My Dear Sir, Yours Truly, (signed) Mary Lincoln. His Excellency A. Johnson &tc." A full transcription of the complete letter can be found by heading to the Smithsonian Transcription Center - link in tweet text.

Black and white photograph from 1978 of Ann Carroll, voice of Smithsonian radio. Carroll, smiling, is wearing a dark-colored turtleneck and is seated at a table with a microphone in front of her.

Front of a postcard from the 1970s featuring a black and white drawing of a two small children (a boy and girl, dressed in overalls and a wide brimmed hat, and a dress and bonnet) tempting a large turkey with seeds.  Written over the turkey is "Wishing You a Happy Thanksgiving."

Cover of a bound notebook belonging to Harvard College Observatory Astronomer Williamina Fleming (brown and red with a tattered edges and peeling) with a label on the front which reads "Henry Draper Memorial

Sepia toned photograph of astronomer Williamina Fleming. She is seated at a desk looking closely at a glass plate negative of the night sky with a magnifying glass. Books, papers, and maps of stars can be seen scattered in the office around her. Circa late 19th century.

Photograph of a two-page open diary. The pages are yellowed, and each page is dated at the top. The left page reads: "Wednesday, November 23, 1932;" and the right page reads: "Thursday, November 24, 1932, Thanksgiving Day." Handwritten, cursive, entries in pencil are included for each date, and include general information on activities and food made. Click the link to read the full diary transcription.
Exterior photograph of the Smithsonian Arts and Industries Building in Washington, DC.

Sepia-toned photograph of Blanche Queen, circa 1940s. Blanche is wearing a dark top with white ruffles on the shoulders and chest. The photograph includes the handwritten caption "Love and Kisses, Blanche."
Sepia toned portrait of Robert Fractious in his WWII military uniform. Fractious wears an army hat, a collared, button-up shirt, and tie.

Color photograph of Earl Shaffer at the end of the Appalachian Trail - standing on Mount Katahdin, Maine, next to a sign identifying the end of the trail. Shaffer is wearing a blue long-sleeved shirt and gray pants, with a camera hanging around his neck.

Image of two pages from Earl Shaffer's 1948 spiral-bound hiking diary from his time on the Appalachian Trail. Black and white photograph of ten attendees at the 1955 National Congress of American Indians convention held in Spokane, Washington. The individuals in the picture are dressed formally, with the men in suits and the women in dresses and heels, all are smiling. From right to left the individuals are holding signs identifying their tribal affiliation: "Otoe, Cherokees of Oklahoma, Chickasaw, Caddo, and Choctaw." In the back of the image two other signs are held up on sticks that read "San Carlos Apache" and "Tulalip."

Manuscript document written by Chief George L. Nelson (Rappahannock) circa 1920. Included alongside the document image is a transcribed quote from the first section of the page. It reads: "The Indians of Virginia for over a Hundred years supposed to be extinct as Recently demonstrated to the people of the State that they are not only still on the map. but that they wish to put their tribal name on the map of glorious State whose History so abounds in Indian Encounters. of the many tribes under the controll of old Powatan in 1620, there are at least five still Represented by decendants, even tho. their names have been almost forgotten we our selves have kept alive the memories of our tribe."

Orange/yellow-colored cover page from the 1946 Booker T. Washington High School in Tulsa, Oklahoma, advertising the annual football game on November 8th between the Booker Washington "Hornets" and the Oklahoma City "Trojans." Included is a sketch of football players and an advertisement for the Casa Loma Ballroom for "after the game!" See a full transcription of the program on the Smithsonian Transcription Center site.

Sepia toned photograph of the "Radical Members of the South Carolina Legislature" during Reconstruction (dated circa 1868). Text written underneath the photograph reads: "These are the photographs of 63 members of the reconstructed South Carolina Legislature, 50 of whom are negroes or mulattoes and 13 white. 22 read and write (8 grammatically), the remainder (41) make their mark with the aid of an amanuensis. Nineteen (19) are tax-payers to an aggregate amount of $146.10. the rest (44) pay no taxes, and the body levies on the white people of the State for $4.000.000."

Location matters. Not all regions display colorful foliage. The best colors are produced when the weather is dry, sunny, and cool. Places that are cloudy, damp, or warm, such as Europe and the tropics, will not see the same degree of changing color.
Darker leaves are caused by a chemical change. Sugars are trapped in leaves produce new pigments that were not part of the leaf during the growing season. These are called anthocyanins.

The earth tilts away from the sun. The seasons change because Earth’s tilt and revolution cause the Northern and Southern Hemispheres to receive different amounts of direct sunlight. The part of Earth that receives less direct sunlight means less daylight and cooler temperatures, slowing down photosynthesis.

The yellow and orange pigments you see in autumn are actually always there. When the days get shorter during the fall season, the chlorophyll in the leaves breaks down and reveals colors like orange or yellow.

Infographic. Left: Methods of Ballast Water Exchange. One: Empty-refill. Ballast water pumped in from the coast is emptied and replaced with open-ocean water. All of the ballast water has to be emptied before refilling. Two: Flow-through. Open-ocean water is pumped into a full ballast tank so that the coastal water flows out of an opening near the top of the ship. Three times the amount of ocean water needs to be pumped in. Right: Onboard Treatment Systems. One: UV Radiation - High intensity UV light destroys the DNA of microorganisms, preventing them from reproducing. This is why we wear sunscreen to protect skin cells from the sun's rays! Two: Electro-chlorination. An electric current is passed through the salt water, creating chlorine compounds and sterilizing the water. Three: Deoxygenation. Oxygenation is removed from the ballast tanks, killing the microorganisms in the process.
Infographic, showing a ship and common invasive species transported: zebra mussels, dinoflagellates, rapa whelks, European green crabs and European green crab larvae

Text over pride flag: "not to seem so superficial, but I felt like there was a combination of—like, there was an admiration I had for gay people just in general. I thought there was a bravery that was built into being out... people who knew how to dress themselves in a way that was maybe going against the grain, or that they were comfortable expressing themselves on the outside... (text continued)

Text over pride flag: "...I felt like all that really was important to me in terms of a sense of believing in the concept of pride. You know, I feel like that early kind of pride was really, really valuable. And it was a really hateful time, you know? And I think that's the other part that's hard to even pick up again, is to remember how reviled this community was..."
Sam Gilliam stands in 3/4 profile towards the camera, his arm extended forward. He is in his studio, surrounded by colorful paintings and equipment.

Text reads, "In the earlier years, color was used rather freely. I could use as much color as I liked. And now, in order to control the work, I mean I like to see a work that contains no more than five colors, sometimes even less, sometimes even one color...in order to establish at least a relationship. So I've begun to use less contrast in order to maintain strength. To increase meaning or dominate them."

color photograph of McLaughlin on a gold course. He holds a club and peers down at the camera while standing next to a large abstract composition of white, yellow, and black.

Photograph of Joyce Pensato painting directly on a wall.

Color photograph of Janine Antoni and Beth Haggard at the opening of The Travel and Leisure Show, March 1, 1992. The women sit in a large blue sandbox with towels and flower crowns on their heads. They are covered in sand up to their necks with sandbox toys surrounding them.
Painted sketch of pink flowers on gold metallic board, signed by Nanae Momiyama.
Painted sketch of a flowering in various shades of gray, coral, magenta, and blue on light gray paper
Four painted sketches of waterlilies in black ink on a single page.

Zarina stands between two men in suits, they are in a gallery with her prints on the walls.
Black and white photograph of Miye Matsukata. She looks up at the camera about to speak as she holds tools in her hand. She is actively working on a piece of jewelry.

Digital image of a jewelry sketch on yellow paper with descriptions of the materials to be used for the piece. Most of the beaded pieces are gold with a blue pendant outlined in gold. Two of the beaded pieces are gold, red, yellow, blue, and black.

Digital image of a jewelry order for the necklace, “Himalaya Range.” Beginning and end dates, materials used, and time spent on labor are noted. The bottom of the page includes a sketch of the necklace which includes blue, green, purple, and gold colors used in the mountain range.

Digital image of a stock card for a jewelry order for the necklace, “Waves.” Beginning and end dates, materials used, and time spent on labor are noted. The bottom of the page includes a sketch of the necklace which includes black, gold, gray, and gold colors used in the design of the necklace.

A collage with two photos. The photo on the right centers Lenore Tawney sitting on the railing of a deck that overlooks the ocean in Truro, Massachusetts. The photo on the left features a woman looking through a camera's viewfinder as it sits atop a tripod.
Ralph Bacerra throwing a pot while seated at a potter's wheel, in a workshop with two large pots behind him.

A black-and-white photograph of Elizabeth Dearing holding five paint brushes in her left hand. She is placing the tip of the paintbrush in her right hand to her painter's palette. Journal and sketchbook pages including a collage with turquoise and green soap packaging.
Journal and sketchbook pages including a photograph of clasped hands featuring iridescent purple and blue nail polish.
Journal and sketchbook pages including train tickets and hand-drawn pencil sketches.
Photograph of Keith Haring sitting on a black leather couch with his arms folded across his chest. One of his signature black and white paintings with figures can be seen behind him on the wall.

Magazine clipping of a Keith Haring painting. In the image two blue figures hold a large yellow dollar bill with the red image of Mickey Mouse in the center. The figures appear to be dancing or moving.
Black and white photo of Miye Matsukata. She holds a large stone and other jewelry in her hand. Miye gestures with one arm raised toward the camera but her eyes are looking away from the camera.
Black and white photograph of Zarina Hashmi. She stands with her arms folded across her chest as she speaks with two other men in the photo.

Black and white photograph of Ray Yoshida. His left leg is perched on a chair, and he leans on his knee with his arms folded. His paintings can be seen behind him, and paints and brushes lay on a table next to him.

1)	A color photograph of Romaine Brooks seated on a wooden bench in what may be her studio surrounded by at least six of her portraits. She is wearing a striped suit jacket and a plain skirt; her hair is short and white and she has a beret on her head. She is looking at the camera. The portraits include, "Self-Portrait," "Dame en Deuil," and "Una, Lady Troubridge."
Color image of various audio recordings, some with handwritten labels.
Painting by Frida Kahlo, a self-portrait of her with a parrot on her shoulder, with a decorative border across the top left corner that says Self Portrait with Bonito 1941, from an artist’s book.
Poem written in response to a painting by Frida Kahlo printed in an artist’s book in reddish-brown ink with a pale border in similar colors.
Cy Twombly’s head is in profile, his left hand curls up to meet his chin; he is wearing a seersucker blazer.

A sepia-toned photograph of Richard Diebenkorn in his Ocean Park Studio with the quote above overlaid on the right side. Diebenkorn is standing with next to a table with his paints, brushed, and other supplies. His hands are in his back pockets. He wears glasses and is smiling.
Color photograph of a city dwelling with a floral mural painted on the side of the building in the foreground. Red and orange blossoms are painted on a blue background with bright green leaves.

Colorful sketch of a memorial with stone pavement surrounded by trees. The memorial is walled off by what appears to be a painted fence. Two bright and colorful rows of flowers lead from the fence to the entrance of the memorial.
A black-and-white photograph portrait of Ellis Wilson's face. The photograph is haveily shadowed. Wilson is half-smiling and looking slightly downward.

Photograph of the dark form of a person standing in front of a large projection of flowers on a wall. The white flowers and designs standout against a red background. The figure appears to be dancing with arms outstretched overhead.

Color photograph of five people painting a mural. Drawings can be seen on the wall with partially painted floral designs in orange, yellow, green, and blue. Some of the people stand painting the wall while others crouch to paint. Cans of paint and brushes can also be seen along the wall.
Arthur Dove standing on a dock wearing a jacket with his hands in his pants pocket.
A black-and-white photograph of Robert Dennis Reid's face, shot in profile.

A note to Reid from Romare Bearden that reads: "Thanks for your kind words. Of course, I'll be more than happy to endorse you for the Guggenheim – I do hope you will get it. I'm writing the book with Harry … naturally, I'd want you in the book. I feel you're a fine talent.
A small blurb describing a few shows, noting that Reid "makes letters fly through the air."
An introductory letter to Barbara Chase-Riboud from Reid. He outlines details of his trip.
A black and white image in which Vincent Smith looks straight ahead. His right hand is resting against the side of his head.

Image depicts Kenneth Noland slouching towards the edge of one of his diamond-shaped canvases. Superimposed is text from a 1987 oral history with Noland: "There are things that happen in painting that don't get talked about as such very often, that I've noticed. Paintings have, color has pulses and those pulses can lead you from one dimension to another dimension to another dimension…"
Page from a Life magazine article featuring a photograph of a man in a suit sitting at a desk working, blowing a large spherical bubble from bubble gum.
A February 6, 1947, handwritten memorandum from advertising executive Douglas Leigh regarding ideas for a soap bubble advertisement.

Yellow cover of The Negro Mother and Other Dramatic Recitations by Langston Hughes with Decorations by Prentiss Taylor. An illustration shows a woman with her left arm raised overhead. A Black figure kneels in the foreground and stairs and a cityscape are in the background.

Partial color illustration shows a woman with her left arm raised overhead. A Black figure kneels in the foreground and stairs and a cityscape are in the background. The poem The Negro Mother appears below the illustration.
Watercolor sketch of purple flowers in a glass.
Sketch of orange and yellow flowers with green stems with black ink.
Drawing of red flowers with green leaves.
Drawing of yellow roses with green leaves.
Pencil drawing of Ann Tobin by Nancy Holt that depicts a woman with shoulder length hair. The drawing is signed, “Ann 1974.”

Photograph of the recently renovated manuscript reading room at the Archives with desks, chairs, and archival material on carts. Elizabeth sits at a desk with a computer in the foreground. Josh, Erin, and Rayna review materials at large desk spaces in the background.
Close-up of George morrow playing bass, Sonny Rollins playing saxophone, and Max Roach, who is smiling, playing drums. All are wearing dark suit jackets.
Handwritten list in black ink on white paper.

Color image of Dizzie Gillespie in black suit playing the trumpet in a live performance next to a large microphone. An unidentified man is in the background and the stage backdrop is red white and dark blue.

Grayscale image of Bruce Mitchell in a shirt and tie painting Johnny St. Cyr wearing a white shirt and dark tie while he plays guitar on a platform. An unidentified man in a suit sits between them on the edge of the platform.

Black and white image of Charles W. White’s lithograph, "Prophet No. 1," that was included in and used for the exhibition announcement for the exhibition, "Twentieth Century Black American Artists," at the San Jose Museum of Art. The lithograph depicts a black man wrapped in cloth looking up at a flower. The flower is in the upper left hand corner and the man is seated in front of a pillar.

A black-and-white photograph of Adrian Dornbush sitting on the back of a painted travel wagon. His legs are crossed at the ankles and he is smoking a cigarette. The wagon is painted with potted plants and a clothesline of shirts and socks. Tassels hanging from the wagon's roof are blowing in the breeze. The wagon has tall wooden wheels. The bottom-right corner of the photograph is torn off.

Composite image of four archival items: a photograph of a woman with her arms and legs crossed over each other, a red document with black text, a document with mineral samples and handwritten notations in ink, and a grayscale image of foil rubbings of a carpet.

Photograph of Catherine Opie dressed in a dark suit and glasses. Opie is gazing over the podium as she speaks to a crowd. A flower is in her lapel and the Archives of American Art medal sits on the podium.

Front cover of the Archives of American Art Journal with a collaged image featuring a woman in profile, whose face is partially covered by a red bandana. The left side of the cover is bright blue with black text which reads, “Spring 2022, 61.1, Archives of American Art Journal.”
The Archives of American Art Journal’s Table of Contents with four images and details about major sections, which include New Research, Art Work, Archives Matters, and New Collections.

Black and white photograph of Worden Day in her studio. The artist wears a smock and sits in a chair as she mixes paints with her palette knife. To her right sits a large glass palette with paint on the edges of the palette, waiting to be mixed.
Worden Day’s sketch of canyons with orange, pink, yellow, and blue watercolors. The artist has added notes in pencil, black ink, and blue ink that describe the coloring of the canyons.
Worden Day’s sketchbook of a rounded, cylindrical structure on a blue background. Handwritten notes surround the sketch, written in blue, orange, and green ink.
A black-and-white photograph of Aline Saarinen standing in front of a heavily patterned background. She is smiling and wearing a sleeveless, floor-length evening dress.

Benny Andrews sits at a table with a microphone, cups, and a pitcher of water with a yellow, green, and blue abstract painting hanging behind him. He is wearing a black button down shirt and raising his hands while talking.

Grayscale image of Lucienne Bloch standing on a scaffold while working on a figurative mural. She is wearing overalls and a striped t-shirt, and there is a bucket and jug next to box holding her brushes. The word FILE is stamped in blue on the front of the photograph.

Text reads, " Well, it's just, to me, the plan is just a basic armature, and I can change the armature, but I'm always interested in the direction it's going. So, I'm an observer in a way. You know, a participant and an observer. Because sometimes there's things that happen that are lucky accidents." By Howardena Pindell, oral history interview, 2012.
Black and white photograph of Robert Hughes sitting on a concrete structure on location in Brasilia. His arms are propped on his bent knees, and he appears to be writing on a small piece of paper.
Black and white photograph of a young man in a black suit and tie, standing in front of a large cubist painting. He looks towards the camera with his hands in his pockets.
Photograph of Robert Smithson standing outdoors in a jacket. Nancy Holt sits in the foreground in a coat with a collar. Clouds can be seen in the sky and trees in the background.

Black and white photograph of Robert Hughes. He stands in the upper left-hand corner of the photo against a hazy backdrop of a city with a white fence behind him. To men stand in the foreground with a large video camera.
Black and white photograph of John Otterbridge and Bob Marley. Both are surround by people and Outterbridge looks at Marley.
Dorothy Liebes in a striped purple and black top with a black skirt sitting on a couch surrounded by a pile of different fabrics.

Typewritten letter with a black ink and watercolor sketch of a sunrise in purple, yellow, orange, and red behind bluish-purple mountains. In the foreground of the sketch are buildings and trucks of an incarceration camp.

Portrait of Barbara Chase holding sunglasses under her chin and gazing to the left side of the camera. Text reads "Plum-lipped sister, sad and wild-eyed with my reflection,  I touch one apricot breast, as you touch one brassy one.  And we gaze into each other's eyes like the criminals that we are."  —Barbara Chase-Riboud reciting from her poem "Why Did We Leave Zanzibar" in her 2019 oral history interview.

The quote "Well yes, everything has its limitations, and certainly fiber does; and certainly techniques, and of course, the loom has many limitations. I love working within limitations. And all I know is when I started weaving the three-dimensional boxes, I would make a little tiny paper model, because I just wanted to see how the folds would go and whether it would work..." over an image of hands working at a loom.

Sam Gilliam stands in 3/4 profile towards the camera, his arm extended forward. He is in his studio, surrounded by colorful paintings and equipment.

Text reads, "In the earlier years, color was used rather freely. I could use as much color as I liked. And now, in order to control the work, I mean I like to see a work that contains no more than five colors, sometimes even less, sometimes even one color...in order to establish at least a relationship. So I've begun to use less contrast in order to maintain strength. To increase meaning or dominate them."
A woman in jeans and a t-shirt lights a miniature wooden house on fire as it sits atop a wheelbarrow in a grassy yard. Handwritten caption reads “ah - that’s quite a flame there – one house is lit -”

"...As long as the work remains figurative, it clings to this kind of popular domain. And I'm okay with that because I think the challenge is to be able to get that work into the position that you want it to get into. Then it will have done something..." — Kerry James Marshall oral history interview, 2008 1/2

"...I think it's much easier to do abstracted and conceptually oriented work and to have it sort of refer to Black culture and the racial thing. It's easy to do that. But it's harder to do it when you've got to have the Black figure in there..." — Kerry James Marshall oral history interview, 2008 2/2

Handwritten black text on graph paper, written in response to the question "What is Feminist Art?" Three paragraphs of text end with the statement, in large capital letters: "FEMINIST ART IS THE FORM BECOMING REAL Dangerous." The page is signed by Harmony Hammond.
The words "STILL DANGEROUS" are scrawled in black capital letters diagonally, from the bottom-left to top-right, across a white page.

White text over a photograph that reads: "That's why people have been accusing me of doing personal painting. And finally it took me five years to realize what 'personal' meant. he cover of Janice Lowry's journal/diary #102 collaged with cut out  illustrations of planets, moons, and stars;  a blindfolded child, a postage stamp; and an illustration of a moth.

White and terracotta brown paper on a black surface, with a color guide device above. The left side of the paper is white and on the right side is a geometric design in terracotta brown with the words “CON SAFO” in the center.

[A quote from Swentzell's oral history interview: "We can step on things. We can cut down forests. We can kill things. We can hurt each other. We can destroy our environment because we're not feeling anymore because if we felt, we couldn't do it. It would hurt too much. So to me, when I make a piece that has a lot of emotion in it, for someone to understand it, they have to connect to their emotions."

Photo of a dark room with a digitization machine in the center, towards the back wall. “So, I read the newspapers, at a very early age. I'd met my father at the streetcar stop, because he'd be carrying the Sun Times, and I'd grab it out of his hand, and we'd race home. First thing I did was read the paper about the war. Kept track of the war. So, if my later political activities had a kind of seed, it probably goes back there.” Irving Petlin interviewed by James McElhinney on September 9, 2016.

“…It had to do with my own expansion of my creative self in terms of bringing the fabric to the surface of the canvas as a symbolic & deeply felt gesture of integrating my entire life. My life of nesting, my life of homemaking, my life of creating in the studio, […] It was an effort to bring all the parts of my life together, as my husband says, into one seamless existence…” —Miriam Schapiro, oral history interview

Slide with white text on a medium blue background, reading: "...I felt two major things, two major thrusts, in my life were, one, where do I belong? And two, how can I make myself ingratiating, how can I be accepted? So the performance aspect was part of not only my daily life, but minute-two-minute life." Quote from Rachel Rosenthal in an oral history interview with the Archives of American Art in 1989.

Sea Sapphires are crustaceans; they are copepods in the family Sapphirinidae. Lots of talk on the internet that they are parasitic...that's not clear from the couple of scientific papers I've seen on them. The males are stunning with their prismatic show of colors. Apparently the color depends on the thickness of their shell and is species specific. Some deeper water species are mainly blue and aqua. Shallower living species can have hot colors added to the mix (reds, yellows, oranges) in their prismatic display and when viewed from above; however, they tend to display more cold colors (blues, violets) when viewed from below.

John Wyeth & Brother of Philadelphia, Pennsylvania began selling pharmaceuticals in 1860. The company was in continuous operation until it was bought by Pfizer in 2008. The Wyeth Brothers compressed these 5 grain (325mg) salicylic acid tablets around 1895. European chemists isolated salicylic acid from willow bark and meadowsweet in the early 19th century. Salicylic acid was a potent analgesic and antipyretic, relieving pain, fever, and inflammation, but tended to be very irritating on the stomach. Acetyl-salicylic acid (aspirin) was developed by Bayer at the end of the 19th century as a less-irritating salicylate medicine.

Nine smiling young people, the grandchildren of artist John Robinson, sit around a table covered with art supplies. Three display their drawings, while others look up from their work or continue without interruption. The realist painting is notable for exacting details, such as the sheen of the polished wood chairs and the patterns on the porcelain in the china closet, as well as for capturing the warmth and intimacy of this gathering. The pride on the children’s faces reflects the artist’s pride in his family

A designed graphic with a quote from Anna Julia Cooper that reads, "Let our girls feel that we expect something more of them than that they merely look pretty and appear well in society. Teach them that there is a race with special needs which they and only they can help; that the world needs and is already asking for their trained, efficient forces." on the left, with a photo of her on the right side.

A designed graphic with a black-and-white image of Jesse Owens and Jack Oakie posing in a runners start, featuring a quote from Owens on the left that reads: "When I came back, after all those stories about Hitler and his snub, I came back to my native country, and I couldn’t ride in the front of the bus. I had to go to the back door. I couldn’t live where I wanted."

This black and white oval photograph depicts a little boy in a suit with short pants. The little boy wears a light colored, double breasted suit jacket with dark pinstripes, and matching knee-length pants. He wears a tie, high dark sock, and dark shoes. Holding a dark hat in his left hand and a stack of books wrapped in a strap in his right, he stands with his left hand on his hip, gazing directly at the viewer. The photograph is mounted on a brown cardboard backing, with a raised decorative groove framing the photograph. Above the photograph on the left side are the words "Off for school" handwritten in pencil, while underneath on the right side are the words "Lucius Harper/ Galveston, Tex."

A school copy book printed by Philip Price in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, and used by Hannah Amelia Lyons. The book has paper covers bound on the proper left side. A length of knotted pink string extends from the top edge of the binding, serving as a bookmark. Several engravings are printed on the front and back covers. On the front cover is a portrait of John Adams entitled "Late President of the United States," above an allegorical scene and space for the owner to sign the book, followed by the printer's name.
A black and white photo of Chuck Brown and the Soul Searchers, a band led by a singer who is called the Godfather of Go go and funk, on stage on the Soul Train television show, 1988.

A 33 1/3 rpm recording titled "GO Ju JU GO” recorded by Experience Unlimited. The album cover is white with blue and black text and a large color photograph of the band at center. The album title is below the color photograph.
Rapper Da Brat (aka Shawntae Harris) appears in a portrait wearing a "Dickies" cap and a bling chain with her name on April 10, 1994 in New York City.
Common performs at the "Blue Note Records: Beyond the Notes" screening during the 2018 Tribeca Film Festival at Spring Studios in New York City.
Black-and-white photograph of President Lyndon B. Johnson moving to shake hands with Martin Luther King, Jr. while others look on after signing the Voting Rights Act.

Grey sweat shirt (.1) and sweat pants (.2) worn by Albert Woodfox while incarcerated at David Wade Correctional Center. The sweat shirt (.1) is made from grey polyester and cotton blend knit fabric.
