It has a ribbed crew neck, full-length sleeves with fitted ribbed cuffs, and the waistband is finished with a ribbed edge. The text "WOODFOX, A / 072148" in stencil lettering is stamped across the back shoulders.

Grey sweat shirt (.1) and sweat pants (.2) worn by Albert Woodfox while incarcerated at David Wade Correctional Center. The sweat shirt (.1) is made from grey polyester and cotton blend knit fabric. It has a ribbed crew neck, full-length sleeves with fitted ribbed cuffs, and the waistband is finished with a ribbed edge. The text "WOODFOX, A / 072148" in stencil lettering is stamped across the back shoulders.

A black and white photo of William Gordon (r), managing editor of the African American newspaper Atlantic Daily World, and pressman Kimber Boddie check a copy of the Memphis World which carries the story of the Supreme Court's May 17th decision to end segregation in public schools.

A black-and-white photograph of the hip hop artist, André 3000, of Outkast. André 3000, pictured center, is posing sideways with his head turned towards the viewer. He is shirtless, wearing a fur hat, a necklace with a pendant, and patterned pants. He is holding his proper left hand to his face, with his thumb resting on his chin and index finger under his eye. Two large tattoos are visible on his proper left bicep.

A black-and-white photograph of the hip hop artist, Big Boi of Outkast. Big Boi, pictured center, is posing facing the viewer. He is wearing a Fila track suit, a necklace with a large pendant, and a baseball cap with a depiction of a Native American on the front panel. Big Boi’s proper left hand is held at his side, while his proper right hand is raised, with his thumb and index fingers pinching the visor of his cap.
A portrait photograph of Barack Obama.

A black-and-white photograph of the rapper Eazy-E, wearing a leather jacket and a black baseball cap that reads [Compton]. He holds a pair of sunglasses in his right hand and wears a diamond pink ring. He is looking away from the camera and leaning against the railing of a subway entrance. Trees and city buildings are visible behind him.

A black and white photograph of Yo-Yo performing on stage at The Ritz in New York City. Yo-Yo is pictured standing in the center of the image, bent slightly at the knees and waist to lean forward, a microphone held to her mouth with her proper right hand. She has long braids and wears a backwards baseball cap and striped shorts.

A stereograph produced by Underwood & Underwood, dated 1899, of an outdoor scene titled: [Girls of the Booker Washington School, Tuskegee, Ala. -- Mrs. McKinley in near carriage / Copyright 1899 by Strohmeyer & Wyman]. The stereograph is rectangular in shape with two identical albumen photographs that are square-shaped with a curved top edge attached to a piece of cardboard.

A designed graphic that has a 1970 quote from James Baldwin written on the left side that reads, "To tell the truth, one sees [things] better from a distance. You can make comparisons, from another place, from another country, which you aren’t able to make in America because there’s nothing to compare America to." and  photo of James Baldwin in a dark shirt on the water of the Golden Horn to the right.

A black-and-white photograph of MC Lyte outside in the Lower East Side of Manhattan. Lyte wears a white tee shirt and dark-colored hat and is leaning with both elbows on a metal railing. She looks away from the

A black and white photograph of DMC and Run reading Rock and Soul Magazine backstage at the UIC Pavilion in Chicago. DMC wears a leather jacket and holds the magazine; Run wears an argyle sweater with his hands in his pockets. Both wear dark-colored fedoras.
Black and white photo of a young Bill Russell in a Boston Celtics T-shirt. He has a welcoming smile on his face with his profile turned to the side. His arm is rested on a bent knee.

An image of Bill Russell and Elgin Baylor playing in 1965. The image features Baylor with the ball going to the net and Russell jumping up to defend him. The two are surrounded by other players on the court. The background of the image shows the stands filled with spectators and the scoreboard hanging from the rafters.

Black and white photograph of African American Astronaut Dr. Mae Jemison with African American actress Nichelle Nichols at the 14th Annual American Black Achievement Awards. Dr. Jemison is wearing a sleeveless dress and is smiling at the camera, standing to the left of Nichols with her arm around her. Nichols is also smiling and looking at the camera, wearing a low-cut dress with a stripped sequins sweater that opens in the front.

The red Starfleet uniform worn by Nichelle Nichols as the character Lt. Uhura on the television show Star Trek. The red mini-dress is made from synthetic velour fabric with gold braid details and a black knit collar. The dress has full-length fitted sleeves, with a band of gold braid sewn around each sleeve. A V-shaped patch with gold lame fabric and black embroidery is sewn with the point facing upward at the proper left front chest.

A designed graphic featuring a photo of Mary Alice holding an Emmy statue in the 90s. She is wearing a long-sleeved dark dress with a shawl draped around her shoulders. The graphic title reads, "Mary Alice" with the caption, "Mary Alice holds her award at the 45th Annual Emmys on September, 19, 1993, where she won in the best supporting actress category for her performance in the acclaimed NBC series, I’ll Fly Away."

A black and white photo of a car on the north side of the 600 block of G Street SW, Washington, D.C. with row houses behind. The 1979 caption states that the tree on the left side of the photograph was still standing and estimated to be 200 years old. Joseph Curtis dates the photo to the 1940s. Curtis photographed this location years later, after the redevelopment of SW.

A black and white photo of East side of the 700 block of 4th Street SW, Washington, D.C. showing shops, restaurants, and other businesses including SandW Restaurant, R. F. Weaver's Radio Barbershop, and Frank's Department Store.

A black and white vintage photo of street and row houses on the east side of the 900 block of Delaware Avenue SW, Washington, D.C. A produce truck painted with 'Charlie Prestopino' is parked in front of the houses and a large 'gas holder' tank is visible behind.

A photo of adults and children walking, socializing and playing on the sidewalk and a stoop of the tree lined east side of the 1200 block of 4th Street SW, Washington, D.C., looking north from N Street.

A black and white photographic print with the caption,  "Silent protest parade in New York City against the East St. Louis riots, 1917". The scene takes place on a NYC street featuring multiple rows of women in all white marching. A man stands in front of the rows of protesters with a large sign.

A black-and-white digital image of people on the beach on Martha's Vineyard. In the foreground is a group of women and men, some of whom are looking towards the camera and smiling. In the background, other groups of men, women and children are lying on towels and walking on the beach. A pier is visible in the background.

A black-and-white digital image of a couple standing along a street outside a large gathering on Martha's Vineyard. The man wears a light colored suit and a hat and stands behind the woman with his hands on her shoulders. The woman wears a dark-colored dress and is smiling.

A flyer for the NMAAHC Hip Hip Block Party. The tagline reads "Featuring live performances, presentations and activities to explore hip-hop music and cultural origins, elements and influences."

Underneath it reads "Learn More: nmaahc.si.edu/hiphopblackparty" On top of the graphic, it reads "Saturday Aug 13 2022". On the side is a vintage black and white photograph of a crowd, with person holding a boombox over their head in the the center. 

On the top of the graphic are the hashtags "#NMAAHCHipHip" and "SmithsonianHipHop".
Cover of  The Negro Motorist Green-Book.
Gelatin silver print of man and woman embracing through an open car window.

A silver and photographic gelatin on photographic paper of three young children in a vintage car.  These students, Michael Willis (now Menelik Fombi), Harry Williams, and Dwania Kyles, were three of the "Memphis 13," the group of thirteen first-graders who integrated four Memphis elementary schools on October 3, 1961. Willis, Williams and Kyles are pictured here on their way to Bruce Elementary School.
A silver and photographic gelatin on acetate film outdoor Photo of Two Women with a Man and Child on the Hood of a Car.
Featured in the EBONY August 1958, Jackie Robinson shares a kiss with wife Rachel Robinson.
Baseball giant Jackie Robinson, is pictured spending some one-on-one time with his three childrenand wife in their home.

A white designed graphic promoting our Summer Workshop that reads, "NMAAHC Summer STEM Workshop: The 3Rs- Inventions for Rest, Refrigeration and Relaxation" and a blurb that reads  "Dive into a 3-day teacher workshop devoted to learning about African American inventions related to rest, refrigeration, and relaxation." On the right side is a photo fo a wooden bed frame artifact from our collection.

Black and white photo of a young Diahann Carroll smiling and looking directly into the camera. She is wearing glamorous makeup with eyeliner and has her hair arranged in a stylish 60s updo. She is wearing a black top with straps and is looking slightly over her shoulders.

Dress worn by Diahann Carroll as the character Julia Baker on the television show "Julia." The pink and cream dress is a full-length, long-sleeved gown with a high neck. A sleeveless bodice and full skirt made from pink taffeta is overlaid with a double layer of pale cream chiffon, with the chiffon covering the entire skirt and forming the upper bodice and sleeves.
A designed graphic featuring a photo of Ida B Wells with her quote "The way to right wrongs is to turn the light of truth upon them."

A sepia black and white photo of  Maggie L. Walker. She is staring off into the distance with a parted updo and is  wearing a black dress with a pearl necklace. She has a pin in the center of her dress of an embellished cross.

This color photograph shows young boys opening a fire hydrant on a summer day in the Brownsville section of Brooklyn, New York, in 1980. One boy opens the hydrant, while the other five stand to the side on the sidewalk.
A sepia photographic panel of the Tulsa skyline after the massacre in 1921.

A photographic print of conjoined women Millie and Christine McCoy. The photograph features the women standing facing the camera. They are wearing a long sleeved dress with a long skirt. The skirt has two layers of additional fabric in tiers that stretch the width of the women. A chair is partially visible in the back right of the photograph. The photograph is mounted on heavier paper that has a scalloped edging and the name of the photography studio printed in gold at the bottom. The back of the photograph has a partial inscription of name.

Black and white photo of Mary McLeod Bethune. She is wearing a long-sleeved, floor length dress  with a long laced collar. She has a moon shaped pendant pin on her throat and a large heart-shaped necklace. Her hair is styled in a neat up-due. Her arm is rested on a surface with a book.

A black and white photograph of poet June Jordan. Jordan sits in a chair with her proper left arm resting against her cheek. An unidentified person sits with their back towards the camera. The back of the photograph has an inscription identifying the photograph’s subject.

Black and white photo of singer-actress Della Reese. She has a beehive updo with a necklace and jeweled earrings. She has a smile on her face, dark lipstick and a v-neck top that exposes her shoulders.
Framed collage-style drawing featuring three images of Della Reese. The drawing is done entirely in black, gray, and white. In each image, she is pictured from the chest up, holding a microphone.

A black and white portrait of Clifford L. Alexander Jr., the first African American to serve as Secretary of the Army. He is sitting with his arms in front of him, wearing a suit and tie with his head slightly tilted, looking directly at the camera.

A black and white photo of Booker T. Washington standing on a stage in Mound Bayou, Mississippi in 1912 holding a piece of paper and is smiling. He is surrounded on all sides by a crowd of men clad in dark coats and suits with bowties and women dressed in dark winter clothes. Many appear to be laughing and smiling.

A stock certificate, number [2469] for nine shares of the Mound Bayou Oil Mill and Manufacturing Company, issued to Frank Daniel on January 18, 1911 for $1.00 per share. The certificate is on cream colored paper surrounded by an elaborate green border.

A black-and-white digital image of men carrying flags. An American flag covers the bottom half of the image. In the center behind, an unidentified man carries a dark colored flag. He is wearing eyeglasses and a beanie and holding one hand to his mouth. The man further back is wearing a white collared t-shirt and carrying an American flag. To the front and left of him, an additional man can be seen wearing a bowler hat and holding a flag.
 A black-and-white digital image of men carrying flags. An American flag covers the bottom half of the image. In the center behind, an unidentified man carries a dark colored flag. He is wearing eyeglasses and a beanie and holding one hand to his mouth. The man further back is wearing a white collared t-shirt and carrying an American flag. To the front and left of him, an additional man can be seen wearing a bowler hat and holding a flag.

A photo of the museum's Freedom & Slavery and Exhibition.  A statue of Thomas Jefferson stands at the center with statues of  notable African American figures placed on each side. All of the statues are standing on a dais that reads "The Paradox of Liberty" with a short description to the right. Behind Jefferson on the dais is a statue of piled bricks with the names of  enslaved people inscribed on each one. On the wall on the top left, a large gold colored engraving reads "The  Founding of America" with a paragraph description below it. Two women are on the left viewing the dais and the exhibition's engravings.

A black-and-white photograph of a large crowd of demonstrators waving American flags. They are standing in front of the Alabama State Capitol building. The print is signed [Charles Moore] on the back in pencil.

Scan of a MAKE GOOD THE PROMISES exhibition note. MAKE GOOD THE PROMISES is typed out and underlined at the top. Underneath the title the visitor hand-wrote, "I promise to be a light in a sea of dark and be a spark to awaken the light in others. We are therefore I am."

Scan of a MAKE GOOD THE PROMISES exhibition note. MAKE GOOD THE PROMISES is typed out and underlined at the top. Underneath the title the visitor hand-wrote, "I promise to never be a bystander and speak out against injustice."

Scan of a MAKE GOOD THE PROMISES exhibition note. MAKE GOOD THE PROMISES is typed out and underlined at the top. Underneath the title the visitor hand-wrote, "Yo eliminariá la discriminación raical para el mundo entero! Todos somos iguales."

A photo of the visitor response section at the end of our Make Good the Promises exhibition. There are quotes displayed on the wall from James Baldwin, Barack Obama and Angela Y. Davis. In between the quote placards is a large, white abstract structure that has various square shaped notes that each read MAKE GOOD THE PROMISES in various  colors. These notes are displayed in 3 rows along the middle of the structure with a few on a round table located to the left of the structure, Each note has unique handwritten responses from our visitors to the question, "How would you reconstruct America and help 'make good the promises of our Constitution?"

Scan of a MAKE GOOD THE PROMISES exhibition note. MAKE GOOD THE PROMISES is typed out and underlined at the top. Underneath the title the visitor hand-wrote, "I will continue to educate and demonstrate that MY Black is bold, my Black is proud, my BLACK is a force, My Black is power, My Black is love, but most of all MY BLACK IS BEAUTIFUL!"

Scan of a MAKE GOOD THE PROMISES exhibition note. MAKE GOOD THE PROMISES is typed out and underlined at the top. Underneath the title the visitor (likely a child based on their handwriting) wrote, "I promise to help people in need"

A black and white photo of Richard Bruce Nugent. He is wearing an open white button up shirt that has a dark pocket square, with a darker button up shirt underneath it. He has long greying hair and thick eyebrows. He is holding  a lighted slim cigarette in a cigarette holder.
A black and white photo of President Lyndon B. Johnson signing the 1964 Civil Rights Act as Martin Luther King, Jr., and a crowd of others look on.

A black-and-white photograph of a group of men at the State Funeral Directors and Embalmers Meeting held in Tulsa, Oklahoma. There are two (2) rows of men standing and sitting in front of an automobile parked underneath a carport.  At the upper right of the photograph is the lower half of the Funeral Home sign: [HOME/ AMBULANCE SERVICE/ DAY AND NIGHT/ PHONE 2-4710].

A designed graphic for NMAAHC's Caregiving Conversation. It reads "ONLINE. Working as a Family Towards Justice — A Book Discussion with Christine Platt and Author, Britt Hawthorne. Thursday, July 7,  7:30pm - 8:30pm" It has an image of Hawthorne's book cover on the right side.

A black and white photograph showing Constance Baker Motley making a victory sign two days after her election as the first African American woman to serve in the New York State Senate. She is wearing a dark dress with pearl necklace and with a flower pinned to the front of her dress.
Twelve African-American men and women posed outside in period clothing.

A black-and-white photograph of the Reverend Dr. Anna Pauline in an office surrounded by a bookshelf filled with law books and a desk covered in stacks of paper and folders. She is sited at a typewriter.

A color photograph of Justice Ketanji Brown Jackson with her hand raised taking an oath. She is smiling and wearing glasses. She is wearing a spotted blouse, a pearl necklace and a blazer. She has shoulder length locs.
A black-and-white photograph of Lena Horne backstage with her eyes downcast while wearing jewelry that sparkles.

A black and white image of a young Carmichael giving an impassioned  speech before an assortment of various microphones. He has a finger pointed at the crowd, eyes set forward, and is wearing a dark long sleeved shirt and jacket.

A paper poster for the Free Huey Rally at De Fremery Park, Oakland, California, 1968. Prominently depicted to the left, stretching the majority of the length of the poster, is Lisa Lyons design of a black panther.
A photograph of James Baldwin sitting and gazing down at a typewriter while  smoking a cigarette. He is wearing a dark short-sleeved striped shirt and a lampshade is positioned in the background.

This is a color photograph of Sam Gilliam seated in the middle of a paint-splattered plastic drop cloth. He is seated in the center of the image wearing navy blue coveralls that are covered in paint down his front. He sits with his legs crossed in front of him pointed towards the right. His clasped hands rest on his knees. Resting on his shins is a rake, also covered in paint splatters. The boots he wears and the rake are slightly camouflaged by the paint splatters that cover the floor in a multitude of colors. The image is bordered in a narrow black line on a large white background. Below the image in the lower left corner are the title, number, and date. Below the image in the lower right corner is the artist's signature. On the back in a repeating pattern is the paper manufacturer [Epson / Professional Paper / EPSON].

A color photographic slide depicting activist Marsha P. Johnson within the crowd at a New York Gay Pride March. Johnson is pictured at the center of the image, from the shoulders up. She has a short, curly hair style, wears rhinestone earrings and matching necklace, and a black sequined top with white and gold beaded collar. She is gazing straight ahead. Behind her are other participants at the march.

A color photographic slide depicting a large gay pride banner flag at a gay rights parade in New York City. The image is captured from the one side of the banner, looking across the banner north on 5th Avenue. The rainbow flag banner takes up the full bottom half of the image, held by seven white-gloved marchers at the three visible sides.

A color photographic slide of marchers in the New York City Gay Pride Parade holding a white banner with the words [SALSA SOUL SISTERS 3RD WORLD WOMEN] printed in black. Just behind them, two women hold a red banner with lavender lettering outlined in yellow reading [THIRD WORLD GAY WOMEN SALSA SOUL]. Behind them, the street is filled with marchers, some of whom carry balloons .
A black-and-white photograph of a man and young boy in swimsuits sitting on the sand and looking at Lake Michigan.

A designed graphic that reads,"Butch Queen Vogue Dramatics Battle at the State-to-State Ball held at the YMCA at 135th Street in Harlem, New York, in 1998" in text at the bottom left. On the right side of the graphic is a black and white photographic print depicting Kevin competing in the battle. The camera is focused on Kevin's face as he and another individual dance and pose on the floor. Kevin is just to the left of center frame, kneeling with his proper left leg bent under him and his other leg extended, his weight supported by leaning with his proper left fingers on the floor. His right arm is bent at the elbow, his right hand is blurred in motion. His face is turned towards his competitor, who faces Kevin while leaning back on his forearms with his right leg extended upright into the air. A crowd of spectators are out of focus around the two competitors, some sitting and standing behind a table in the background and others kneeling and standing on the floor with them.

A color photograph of Fatin Dantzler and Aja Graydon of Kindred The Family Soul preforming during the Nu Soul Revival Tour at Whitney Hall in 2017 in Louisville, Kentucky. Both are singing into microphones standing next to each other. Fatin has on black shades, a hat, a thin chain and a textured vest - and is wearing a t-shirt with a print of Muhammad Ali underneath. Aja is wearing knee high black boots, light colored jeans and a flowy black structured top. She has on glasses and has her hair styled in honey-colored curls.

Black and White photo of of Billy Davis, Jr. and Marilyn McCoo from their 1977 CBS summer replacement television program. Billy is wearing a dark checkered suit with his hands crossed in front of him placed on a ledge. His is smiling and has a short beard with a styled afro. Marilyn is positioned behind him smiling as well in a stripped button down shirt, with one hand rested on his shoulder and the other one caressing his elbow on the same side of his body. Her hair is styled in shoulder length 1970s-era curls.
A color photograph of African American science fiction writer Octavia Butler. She is wearing glasses and looking directly into the camera, standing in front of a bookshelf holding one of her books.

A color photograph of Big Freedia at the National Museum of African American History and Culture. She is holding a microphone in her right hand and posting towards the sky with her left arm bent. Lights from the stage are in the background.

A color photograph of Big Freedia singing with a microphone to her mouth on stage at the National Museum of African American History and Culture. Two African American dancers stand on either side of her, and behind them is a large crowd of people in the museum’s Heritage Hall.

A black and white photo of an older African American woman with glasses and gray hair standing in a yard wearing a short sleeve dress. Her arms are out, her knees are slightly bent and her legs are apart, and she has a hula-hoop around her waist that she is looking down at.
A black-and-white photograph of African American children playing in the water coming from a fire hydrant on a city street.

A designed graphic that holds information about the Juneteenth events happening at our museum this week with the call to "Join Us!” The event listed with details are Monday, June 20, 10am-5pm, “Juneteenth Community Day” with a description of the events, and Tuesday, June 21, 7:00 pm, “Racialize Symbolism and Iconography in Public & Sacred Spaces.”
Outdoor portrait of an African American father smiling and sitting on a chair holding his infant on his lap and a girl standing next to him.
Studio portrait of an African American father and son. The son is standing, and the father is kneeling down beside him with his arms around him, smiling.

A digital scan of ten people and a dog sitting outdoors in Lincoln, Nebraska. Eight of the party are seated at a picnic table, on which bottles, plates, and sandwiches are resting. A man and woman stand at the far end of the table in conversation. A white dog in a black harness sits on the bench as well. The table is on the grass and surrounded by trees. A fence is visible in the background.
Vintage photo of an African-American band at an Emancipation Day celebration, June 19, 1900, held in "East Woods" on East 24th Street in Austin.
Photograph of a formally dressed family of African Americans celebrating Emancipation Day on June 19, 1900 held in "East Woods" on East 24th Street in Austin.
An African American man and two African American women sitting in a one-horse carriage decorated for Juneteenth.

A black and white digital image of a crowd marching. Ralph Abernathy and Mel Thom march with them.  The Washington Monument is in the background. Some of the marchers appear to be chanting or singing in unison.

A color photograph of a large gathering of people outdoors. There are 7 rows of adults and 3 rows of children in the front. A stone building is to the right of the group and 4 picnic tables setup to the left of the group.

A black-and-white photograph of Mary J. Blige at the New York Music Awards after party at China Club in New York City. The image features Blige lowering her sunglasses to peer at the camera while leaning against a wall or column. In the background, a neon sign for the China Club is partially visible above a banner reading "New York Music Awards."

A black-and-white photograph of Etta James singing at a performance in Ft. Lauderdale, FL. She is wearing a black dress, holding the microphone with her left hand, and her right hand is raised above her head.

A designed graphic featuring a photo of the Washington Monument at nighttime with a purple firework display going off in the skyline. Over the photo is large, centered block text that reads: "Smithsonian Folklife Festival, June 22-27 and June 30-July 4 National Mall, Washington, D.C."
Black and white photo of Bessie Coleman in 1923. She is smiling and wearing her aviation cap.

A designed graphic for Juneteenth Community Day events on Monday, June 20. It reads "Registration permits entry to events at the museum throughout the day."  With the event details listed: "11:00 AM Storytime with Rio Cortez, Explore More Gallery", "11:30 AM; 1:30 PM; and 3:30 PM History Alive, Slavery and Freedom Galleries" and "3:00 PM,  Alphonso Horne and the Gotham Kings, Oprah Winfrey Theater/Virtual"

A designed graphic that holds information about three Juneteenth events happening at our museum this week with the call to "Join Us!” The event listed with details are: “Monday, June 13, 7pm: A Taste of Juneteenth: Watermelon and Red Birds—A Conversation with Nicole A. Taylor,” “Wednesday, June 15, 7pm, One Year Later: Juneteenth for All Americans,” and “Friday, June 17, 7pm, Juneteenth and the Color of Care."

A designed white, yellow and black graphic that reads "NMAAHC Hip-Hop Block Party. Stay tuned for more details. Saturday Aug 13 2022. #SmithsonianHipHop." It includes a black and white photo of a crowd, including a man with a white baseball cap as the focus in the center, with a person standing behind him holding a boom box over their heads.

A black-and-white photograph of Tina Turner performing onstage at the World Music Theater, Tinley Park, Illinois, June 28, 1997. She is singing with eyes closed and mouth open into the mic, wearing a sparkling thigh-high dress with spaghetti straps.

A color photograph of Sharon Green, also known as MC Sha-Rock. Sha-Rock wears a green sweatshirt with yellow letters that appears to read "I'm Sha-Rock an I can't be stopped." She is looking away from the camera with her arms held in front of her at waist-level, her hands appear to be mid-snap.
A sepia-toned photograph of a head-and-shoulders portrait of Jack Johnson, an African American boxer. He is wearing a suit, bowtie, and hat, and he’s smiling looking to the right of the camera.

A sepia-toned photographic postcard commemorating the "Fight of the Century" between Jack Johnson, an African American boxer, and James J. Jeffries, a white boxer, c. 1910. The boxers are pictured separately but facing each other, ready to box. Each man's name is written below his feet.

A black, white and red designed graphic featuring the Audible original cover for "Songs That Shook the Planet" with a photo of Chuck D on the right side, and event information on the left side of the graphic.
A close up headshot of Prince with his eyes closed and his head titled downwards.

A tambourine used on-stage during "Baby I'm A Star" at one of seven Wembley Stadium performances during the 1990 Nude Tour. The tambourine has a black frame and head with gold tone rim and the Love symbol in gold painted on the head.

This poster depicts Angela Davis, shown from the chest up. Wearing a shirt with a zig zag pattern, she turns her head to her right. Below the image is black text that reads "FREE ANGELA DAVIS NOW! / New York Committee to free Angela Davis. 29 West 15th ST. 7th Floor/ New York, N.Y. 10011. 929 2010."

An orange button with a black and white image of Angela Davis. She is seen from the neck up and is looking directly at the camera. Around the image of Davis, Black text around the image reads “ANGELA IS FREE / FREE / ALL POLITICAL PRISONERS / T.U.A.D.”
A black-and-white portrait of Ella Fitzgerald. She holds a microphone in her right hand, and her left hand holds her forehead. Her eyes are closed, and she appears to be in the middle of singing.

A color photograph of Doug E. Fresh singing into a microphone. He wears a black t-shirt and is holding the microphone in his left hand up to his mouth, and his right hand is outstretched in front of him. In the background is blue sky and a blurred aerial tower.

A red graphic listing the date, time, and description of next week’s Juneteenth programming at the National Museum of African American History and Culture. Text on the graphic reads, “Juneteenth, Senses of Freedom, June 19, 1865, Join us! Monday, June 6, 6:00 PM, EST, Juneteenth: Dishes to Taste and Savor: Recipes from the Sweet Home Café Cookbook, Virtual, Monday, June 6, 6:00 PM, EST, Tuning in to Juneteenth, Virtual, Saturday, June 11, 12:00-1:30 PM, EST, Texas Freedom Colonies, In Person/Virtual”

A black and white photographic of Octavia St. Laurent and Danielle Revlon, two competitors in the Femme Queen Realness category at the Revlon Ball in Manhattan, NY in 1997. They are leaning on a circular table with one hip and one hand on the table and the other hand on their hips facing the ball's judge, Tony Revlon. A large crowd of spectators are visible sitting and standing in the background.

Three charred pennies from the Tulsa Race Massacre in 1921. The penny on the left and center is brown with charred marks, the penny on the right is black. Lincoln’s profile and the word “Liberty” is somewhat visible on the penny the pennies, the embossing on the front of the penny is hardly visible at all on the penny on the right.

A black-and-white photograph of Eunice Jackson, Owen William and an unidentified woman. Jackson sits on a ladder at the proper-right of the photograph, while the other woman stands at proper left, and Owen William stands in between the two women. Both women are wearing dresses and cloche hats, and William is wearing a dark-colored jacket and light-colored trousers and tie, and he is holding his hat in his clasped hands. There is a large carport structure behind the trio, with two (2) four-door cars parked.

A black-and-white photograph of men walking down the middle of a street with hands raised in surrender during the Tulsa Race Massacre in 1921. In the background, a crowd of people line the street in front of a building. Written into the negative of the photograph is, “Captured negros on way to convention hall during Tulsa Race Riot, June 1st 1921.”

A black-and-white photograph of the Greenwood District of Tulsa, Oklahoma burning during the Tulsa Race Massacre in 1921. The image depicts a building and several people in the foreground watching large plumes of dark smoke rising in the background. The photograph is bent at corners and has loss at top center edge.

A black-and-white photo of two African American women decorating a soldier’s grave on Memorial Day at Arlington National Cemetery in Arlington, Virginia. White grave stones surround the women, with trees dotting the landscape in the background.

This black and white photograph depicts a large mural painted on the side of a two-story building. The mural is broken into six segments, three across the top, and three across the bottom. Each section features various figures engaged in sports, music, and community activism. The mural faces a street with parked cars and a large dumpster in the lower-left corner. A man walks down the street in front of the mural.

A black and white photograph of a graffiti mural memorializing Tupac Shakur on Houston Street in New York City. The mural is spray-painted on a metal security gate inset into a brick wall. in the center is a portrait of Shakur. Above and below him are the words, “Love by the gun die by the gun.” Pedestrians pass by on either side of the image.

A black jacket that is collared with cuffs that are buttoned. On the upper section of both the left and right sleeves, you can see an embroidered dragon in green, red, off-white, and yellow. The back features discolored white embroidery, with an image of a fist wearing a diamond-patterned bracelet with the words “Black Power” in the center. Lettering above and below fist reads “Black Unity, Vietnam, 71 - 72.”

A black jacket with a dark gold zipper with vertical text “Venus” on the pull. There is a circular patch on the proper left breast. The patch is embroidered black, red, and green with an image of two clasped hands in the inner circle. The outer circle contains words in a circle “Black”, “Pride” and “Culture.” An embroidered dragon in green, red, off-white, and yellow is on the upper section of both sleeves.

A chromogenic print depicting a black-and-white image of a crowd of women raising their fists in a Black Power salute. The women are shouting with their right fists rasied in the air. All four women in the front row are wearing floral-printed tops. Many of the women throughout the crowd have afros. A man's face is visible in the bottom left corner.

A color photograph of eleven female rappers posed together on a wooden stage in front of a brick wall. In the back row, standing or crouching (left to right): Sparky D, Sweet Tee, MC Peaches, Yvette Money, Ms. Melodie, Synquis. In the middle is the singer Millie Jackson. Sitting along the bottom row with their legs crossed (left to right): (unidentified), Roxanne Shante, MC Lyte, Finesse.

A black designed graphic that reads "Women Do Dare: Celebrating the Legacy of Shirley Chisholm" in block text stationed at the bottom left. In the top left there is the NMAAHC museum logo, underneath is a red rectangular sticker that reads "ONLINE". On the right side of the graphic is a vintage Shirley Chisholm '72 presidential campaign poster featuring her  catchphrase, "Unbought and Unbossed."

An archival pigment print photograph of collaged images featuring a self-portrait of the artist's grandfather, Willard Thomas. Thomas wears a Korean War-ear military uniform and stands smoking a cigarette and wearing glasses, holding a camera. This image has been cut into the shape of a house and is set into a photograph image of enslaved individuals standing outside plantation slave cabins.

A designed graphic with the NMAAHC Smithsonian logo in purple in the top left corner. Written in block letters at the bottom of the graphic starting from the left and moving all the way to the right it reads "Black Birders Week at NMAAHC" in white, and in smaller sized text underneath it, is a subheading that  reads "Highlighting Black nature enthusiasts and increasing visibility of Black birders", also in white. Above the title to the left it reads, "Sunday, May 29 - Saturday, June 4,  2022" in thinner block text. Taking up most of the graphic, centered towards the right side is an abstract art piece from our collection by Clementine Hunter, 'Untitled' (Miss Cammie with Ducks) depicting an elderly woman outside holding a stick behind two large grazing birds.

A color photo of the inside of the Musical Crossroads exhibition in the National Museum of African American History and Culture. On the right is an exhibition case and panel labeled “Music of a City: Go-Go & Washington, DC.” To the right you can see outside of the museum through a small window, and to the right of the window is another exhibition display case that reads “Funk & Dance.”

A black-and-white photo of two African American men and one African American boy — Reverend Walter Fauntroy stands on the right reviewing redevelopment plans with architect Herbert McDonald (with nine-year-old Cedric Carter standing nearby) for a block destroyed during the 1968 civil disturbances, ca. 1969.
A black-and-white photograph of a group of African American men and women standing outside next to a car in Washington, D.C., with trees and the U.S. Capitol in the background.
Hand tinted photograph of an African American Women's Army Corps soldier wearing a khaki uniform ca. 1945. It is inscribed "to mom love Polly" in the lower right corner on the front.

A yellow designed graphic with the museum's logo in the top left corner. The bottom left side of the graphic reads "Historically Speaking" in large block text with a subheading above that reads "A Conversation with Tracey Michae’l Lewis-Giggetts". On the right side the graphic, Tracey's yellow book cover is pictured with her name followed by the title "Black Joy: Stories of Resistance, Resilience  and Restoration."

A black-and-white photograph of a storefront with a sign indicating that it only serves white patrons. A woman stands to the left of the building, and the rear of a car is visible on the right. The signs above the store read, “Hamilton and Gates,” “Washington,” “Ice Cream,” “Maid,” “Light Lunches Also Dinners,” “Lunch Room,” “Beer,” and the sign directly above the door reads “This Door Whites Only Colored in Rear.” Signs in the windows to the left of the door read “Coca Cola,” “Lunch,” and “Sandwiches.”

A black-and-white photograph of an African American man in a hat, white shirt, and pinstriped pants drinking at a water cooler labeled “Colored" in a streetcar terminal in Oklahoma City, Oklahoma. Signs around the water cooler he drinks at say “white women colored women” on the left and “white men colored men” on the right.

A designed graphic with a black background  that displays the museum's logo in the upper left corner. In the bottom left the text reads in a large heading: "HISTORICALLY SPEAKING." Above it reads the subheading: "A discussion with Sybrina Fulton, mother of Trayvon Martin" and on the right side of the graphic is the cover of Sybrina Fulton's book titled "Trayvon Ten Years Later" with an empty hoodie in the background.

A black and white photograph of Queen Latifah.
She is facing the proper left side of the image and singing into a microphone on a stand held by her proper left hand. She is wearing a light-colored shirt, a patterned, multi-colored woven jacket, and a tall, cylindrical hat in a matching fabric. She is wearing a ring on her proper left hand and she has large drop earrings in a starburst design. The background is out of focus, but a plane of grey is visible against a white wall.

A silver gelatin print depicting a black-and-white image of entertainer Gladys Bentley. Bentley is depicted facing the viewer in bust pose. She is wearing a black top hat, dark bow tie, a white dress shirt, and black tuxedo suit jacket. Her top hat is perched slightly towards her proper right shoulder. The edges of the image are faded into an oval-shaped, white background.

Sepia-toned photograph of 9 of the first 18 African American women to serve in the Army Nurse Corps pictured at Camp Sherman, Ohio, ca.1919. The women are standing on the front steps of a porch all wearing their white uniform dresses with black capes and white camps.

This image depicts a group of individuals erecting a series of temporary shelters in Resurrection City on the National Mall. Thirteen individuals are assisting each other in laying wood floors and constructing wooden supports for the shelters. There are trees in the background, and the Washington Monument can be seen in the distance.

A silver gelatin print depicting a black-and-white image of 5 performing showgirls. Each is depicted in a slightly different dance pose, caught mid-routine. The women are wearing identical costumes with short, medium-toned skirts and white bodices with beaded embellishments. The five women dance in the foreground and mid-ground with musicians behind bandstands & audience members behind the dancers in the background.

A black-and-white photograph of Asia One and Masami performing at the Rock Steady Crew 25th Anniversary, Manhattan Center, 2002. They both have their proper right arms raised and bent in front of their faces and their left arms down by their sides. They are both leaning back. There is a large group of people, mostly men and younger boys, standing behind them as they dance.

A designed graphic that has a black background and reads "Historically Speaking" on the lower end, centered in all caps. Underneath on the left side of the graphic reads the subheading "Advancing African American medical science from Reconstruction - Present". On the right side of the graphic is a light color medical pamphlet titled: "Medical Care And the Plight of the Negro." with publishing details at the bottom.

A digital image of a protest march through Chapel Hill. The image depicts a large group of men, women, and children in the middle of a street. At the front is a banner that reads [FREEDOM NOW! - EAT AT JOE'S - BLACK + WHITE].

An engraved powder horn with stopper. The ox horn is carved with images of a dove carrying a banner reading "LIBERTY," a deer, the sun with a face, and a pine tree. An intricate design featuring eyes encircles the outer edge of the horn. The name Prince Simbo and the date November 17, 1777 are also engraved on the horn.

A sepia-toned image of African American women on the deck of a ship waving American flags. There is a row or two of women seated, and a row behind of women standing, all wearing dresses and some wearing hats. A captain stands in the center of the group. In the background, you can see the side of the ship.

Color photograph of the interior of the National Museum of African American Culture's new exhibition, “Represent: Hip-Hop Photography." A graphic panel with a black-and-white photo of Salt-N-Pepa is at the front on the right, and along the walls are photographs and other photo panels. Brown carpeting and several benches can be seen in the foreground.

Color photograph of the outside of the National Museum of African American Culture's new exhibition, “Represent: Hip-Hop Photography." A colorful graphic panel is to the left of the doorway to the exhibition that reads "Represent," and through the doorway is another colorful graphic panel. Brown carpeting is in the foreground.

Color photograph of the interior of the National Museum of African American Culture's new exhibition, “Represent: Hip-Hop Photography." A colorful graphic panel is at the front on the left, and along the back walls are photographs, and another blue graphic panel on the right. Brown carpeting and several benches can be seen in the foreground.

A designed graphic that reads: "In a conversation with Deesha Philyaw, author Adiba Nelson chronicles her experiences as a new mother of her special needs child" in light text font over the words "HISTORICALLY SPEAKING" in bold in the bottom left corner. On the right side of the graphic is Adiba Nelson's book cover for  "Ain't That a Mother" which features her standing next to an assortment of children's toys.

Designed graphic with the text on the bottom left side that reads: "CYCLE OF BLACK MOTHERHOOD"/"History, Health, Policy, and Justice"/"A conversation with curator Angela Tate, Anna Malaika Tubbs, Christy Turlington Burns, followed by a moderated panel on Black maternal health". On the entire right side of the graphic is William H. Johnson's oil on plywood painting called "Young Mother", ca. 1944-1945. The painting is an abstract, colorful art piece featuring a Black woman seated in a chair holding a swaddled infant. The museum logo is placed at the top left of the graphic.

Large three-sheet broadside promoting "Men of Color" to enlist in the Army in 1863; text printed in relief with carved wood type and cast letterpress/metal type. Text reads "MEN OF COLOR To Arms! To Arms!"

A black designed graphic with event details that reads : "I Have Something to Say....Artist Laurie Anderson and former Guantánamo Bay detainee Mohammed el Gharani collaborated on this monumental video installation, Habeas Corpus', and is projected on a 14-foot sculpture modeled after the Lincoln Memorial. El Gharani will share his recollections of Guantánamo and reflections on unlawful imprisonment."
This blue jacket and Hammer pants were worn by the rapper and dancer MC Hammer in the 1988 music video for his song "They Put Me in the Mix."

Infographic with a photo of Maya Angelou and text that reads, “Caged Bird, The free bird thinks of another breeze, and the trade winds soft through the sighing trees, and the fat worms waiting on a dawn bright lawn, and he names the sky his own. But a caged bird stands on the grave of dreams, his shadow shouts on a nightmare scream, his wings are clipped and his feet are tied, so he opens his throat to sing.”

A black-and-white photograph of Coretta Scott King speaking into a microphone at a podium. She is wearing a large bow on her shoulder, a women to the left of the podium looks toward her, and people sit and stand in bleachers behind her in the bottom right. Text below the photograph reads, “Coretta Scott King speaking at Anti-Vietnam War Rally. Kezar Stadium, San Francisco, CA. 1967”

Black and white photograph of Amiri Bakara. Bakara stands on the right side of the image with his hands clasped behind his back wearing a dark turtleneck shirt and trousers. He stands in front of a paneled background where light ripples in waves on the panels; Bakara's shadow is cast on the wall. The image is bordered in a narrow black line on a white background.

The team of Eastern College All-Stars are shown in their vintage basketball jerseys that read EAST on the top with their numbers underneath. They are arranged in two rows - one row sitting, and one row standing directly behind them. Their coach, an older man has his hands folded in his lap, is seated in the middle wearing a suit. The two men next to him are holding basketballs (Chuck Cooper is to his left).

A designed graphic featuring a background still photo of multiple tall, deep green pine trees in a thick forrest landscape. The large logo in the center reads [Earth Optimism x Folklife] stacked inside of a circular shape that utilizes a paint stroke effect - all in white. At the bottom of the graphic sits neat, white centered text reads: [June 22 - 26 and June 30-July 4, 2022 on the National Mall in Washington, D.C.].

A black-and-white photograph of Charles Mingus playing bass during a performance in New York City. Mingus is photographed head on but from a low angle. He is looking down at the bass he is playing and an out of focus music stand resting his bow on it cuts across the lower portion of the frame.

Designed graphic with a black background that reads [EXPLORING SPACE WITH VICTOR GLOVER] in the bottom left corner in white text. In the top left corner is the museum logo and directly underneath it is a red button that reads [ONLINE]. On the right side of the graphic Victor Glover is pictured staring straight ahead in his space helmet.

Green infographic with a cutout of Langston Hughs on the right, and a black-and-white photo of the Harlem River in 1952 behind him. Text on the graphic reads, “I, Too by Langston Hughs, I, too, sing America. I am the darker brother. They send me to eat in the kitchen, When company comes, But I laugh, And eat well, And grow strong. … Besides, They’ll see how beautiful I am, And be ashamed— I, too, am America."

A first edition of the book Poems on Various Subjects, Religious and Moral, by Phillis Wheatley, while she was enslaved to Mr. John Wheatley of Boston. The book has a brown leather cover, the original morocco spine label, the book is open to the first page with the dedication and title.

A first edition of the book Poems on Various Subjects, Religious and Moral, by Phillis Wheatley, while she was enslaved to Mr. John Wheatley of Boston. The book has a brown leather cover, the original morocco spine label, and a frontispiece featuring a portrait of Wheatley by Scipio Morehead. Along the top of the portrait are the words [PHILLIS WHEATLEY, NEGRO SERVANT TO MR. JOHN WHEATLEY OF BOSTON].

A black-and-white photograph of the National Zoological Park, Lion House Hill on  Easter Monday c. 1900s. Families are scattered about the lawn in formal wear, sitting, standing, and walking. Trees and bushes are scattered about.

Sepia-toned infographic with a sepia-toned photograph of Jackie Robinson in his baseball uniform, jumping over a base and reaching up to catch a ball in his baseball glove. Faded text in the background says "75 Years of 42" and the main text says, "75th Anniversary and Celebration of Jackie Robinson Day, Friday, April 15 7:30 pm - 8:30 pm, Online."

A photograph of the beginning of the "Sports: Leveling the Playing Field” exhibition in the National Museum of African American History and Culture. In the center is a case with one of Jackie Robinson’s baseball jersey. On the left are statues of the Williams sisters holding their tennis rackets, and on the right are statues of Olympic medal winners Peter Norman, and Tommie Smith and John Carlos, who have their fists raised in the air. In the background you can see the word “Sports” and photographs and objects in the exhibition. A larger black-and-white photograph sits above it all, with baseball players lined up in uniform on the field, with a crown behind them.

Sepia-toned infographic with a sepia-toned photograph of Jackie Robinson in his baseball uniform, jumping over a base and reaching up to catch a ball in his baseball glove. Faded text in the background says "75 Years of 42" and the main text says, ‘[Jackie Robinson] was a sit-inner before the sit-ins, a freedom rider before freedom rides.’ Martin Luther King Jr., ‘Hall of Famer’”

A black and white lobby card for the film Lilies of the Field. The lobby card features a scene from the movie of Sidney Poitier holding a record and being shushed by a table of nuns. Along the bottom is a banner of red with [Sidney Poitier AS THE FANTASTIC HOMER IN RALPH NELSON'S Lilies of the Field] in black and white text. Along the bottom edge of the card is a copyright notice.

Sepia-toned infographic with a sepia-toned photograph of Jackie Robinson in his baseball uniform, jumping over a base and reaching up to catch a ball in his baseball glove. Faded text in the background says "75 Years of 42" and the main text says, "75th Anniversary and Celebration of Jackie Robinson Day, Friday, April 15 7:30 pm - 8:30 pm, Online."

A photograph of the beginning of the "Sports: Leveling the Playing Field” exhibition in the National Museum of African American History and Culture. In the center is a case with one of Jackie Robinson’s baseball jersey. On the left are statues of the Williams sisters holding their tennis rackets, and on the right are statues of Olympic medal winners Peter Norman, and Tommie Smith and John Carlos, who have their fists raised in the air. In the background you can see the word “Sports” and photographs and objects in the exhibition. A larger black-and-white photograph sits above it all, with baseball players lined up in uniform on the field, with a crown behind them.

Sepia-toned infographic with a sepia-toned photograph of Jackie Robinson in his baseball uniform, jumping over a base and reaching up to catch a ball in his baseball glove. Faded text in the background says "75 Years of 42" and the main text says, "75th Anniversary and Celebration of Jackie Robinson Day, Friday, April 15 7:30 pm - 8:30 pm, Online."
Black-and-white photo of Frank Robinson in his baseball uniform. He is crouched down on one knee near the dugout with a bat in his hand, facing left wearing his helmet.

Model R161 wood bat with black writing on side. Black type near center of bat reads, [LOUISVILLE SLUGGER® / 125 / HILLERICH & BRADSBY Co / MADE IN U.S.A. / LOUISVILLE, KY. / Powerized]. Type near end opposite of handle reads, [GENUINE / R161 / Frank Robinson / LOUISVILLE SLUGGER]. The bat is cracked one third of the way up from the handle.

A silver gelatin print depicting a black-and-white image of Billie Holiday. Holiday is depicted standing behind a microphone stand. She wears a white blouse, belt, and floral skirt. A band is depicted in the background behind her, on the left side of the image. At the center of the image is a handwritten inscription in black ink.

Green infographic with text that reads, “You will not be able to stay home, brother, You will not be able to plug in, turn on and cop out , You will not be able to lose yourself on skag, And skip out for beer during commercials, because, The revolution will not be televised. Lyrics from “The Revolution Will Not Be Televised” by Gil Scott-Heron” On the right is a black-and-white photograph of Gill Scott-Heron.

A scene titled: "Booker T. Washington, President of the Negro Industrial School, Tuskegee, Alabama"/ Copyright 1899 by Strohmeyer & Wyman", below the image. The photo is rectangular in shape with two identical albumen photographs that is square-shaped with a curved top edge attached to a piece of cardboard. Both images  have Booker T. Washington standing in a dirt paved street with his right hand in his vest pocket.

A black-and-white photograph of of jazz pianist Billy Taylor performing in Florence, AL. Taylor is photographed from a low angle and just behind his right shoulder. His hands are raised to the piano keys and he is wearing a dark suit jacket and glasses.

Black-and-white photo of an audience of Black Muslims: women and some children sitting in chairs, and men in suits standing in a side aisle in the background; possibly a religious service; possibly in the Arena: 119 East Magnolia Street
A black-and-white photograph of a crowd outdoors; an African American woman holds an American flag and in the back an African American man shades himself from the sun under an umbrella.

A black-and-white image of the annual meeting of the Poor People's Corporation Producer Co-ops. The image is in landscape orientation and depicts a large group of people, both men and women, sitting in a large circle around three tables pushed together in a large room.

A black-and-white image of members of a Poor People's Corporation sewing cooperative making patchwork animals. The image is in landscape orientation and depicts a group of women sitting in a building with wooden floors, some are sewing.

A black-and-white photograph depicting a memorial march after the assassination of Dr. King. People march from top right to bottom left carrying signs saying "HONOR KING: END RACISM" and "UNION JUSTICE NOW!"

Simone is photographed in profile from the right. She holds a microphone in her right hand and her left hand is extended in front of her. She wears a light colored dress and large dangling earrings. There is a green graphic of a saxophone in a circle at the bottom right corner of the photo to honor of Jazz Appreciation Month.

Designed graphic featuring the cover of 'Growing Up in the Country' on the right side, and event information towards the left. Includes the text "Join historian and author Kendra T. Field for a discussion on her book and African American migration. Saturday, April 9 12:00 pm - 1:30pm".

Black and white photo of Marvin Gaye sitting at a piano in a recording studio recording "Let's Get It On". He is looking upward with his fingers on the keys. Marvin is wearing a beanie over his head, he has a full beard. He is dressed in an open jacket over a tshirt with a U shape neckline.

A black-and-white photograph of the Preservation Hall Jazz Band of New Orleans, standing in front of Preservation Hall in New Orleans, Louisiana. The photograph depicts six men in suits standing behind bass drum, with the words [PRESERVATION HALL / JAZZ / BAND / of / New Orleans, La.] printed on the drumhead. "Sweet" Emma Barrett, piano player and leader of the band, is seated to the right.

A graphic with a statue on the right of a man seated and turning, looking up, wearing a cloth around his waist. On the left is a green faded background with a close up of the statue faded in the background, with text that reads: National Poetry Month, Golden Shovel Series, Each Thursday in April, April 7, April 14, April 21, April 28, 12:00 pm - 1:00 pm.
Color photograph of Katherine Dunham. She is looking directly at the camera and smiling, with her head tilted and resting on her hand and index finger. The background is a light purple color.

Color photograph of the Katherine Dunham Dance Company. 7 African American men surround an African American woman in a white dress, smiling. The men are posed around her wearing striped pants and shirts and head wraps -- one man on the right is in mid-jump.

Color photograph of the Katherine Dunham Dance Company. 4 African American women posing wearing blue and green dresses. Two in the back face the left in a slight backbend and two in the back face the right, their right hands are arching up over their heads.

Color photograph of the Katherine Dunham Dance Company. 2 African American women in the front are posing in large pink and purple ruffled dresses, their feet bare and their arms outstretched. An African American man poses behind them in a similar fashion, with a large brown shirt and purple pants.

A color digital print photograph of Toni Morrison. Morrison is featured in a close-up angle, with her proper right hand resting on her chin and holding a pencil. The back of the photograph has a Jack Mitchell stamp with the number [5962].

A photo of the National Museum of African American History and Culture in spring, with cherry blossom trees in bloom in front and a blue sky behind. On the right is a purple background with white text that reads, “Welcome you 7 days a week starting Monday, April 4. Free timed-entry passes are required for entry.”

A print depicting a black-and-white image of Pearl Bailey. She is leaning against a large, white, imperial guardian lion statue. She is wearing a light colored, long-sleeved shimmering evening gown, gathered at the waist. Her right hand rests on the statue's foot, while her left hand is on her hip. She looks away, towards the left side. At the top left corner of the image is a handwritten inscription in black ink

Green infographic with a black-and-white cutout of Katherine Dunham on the left and a color photograph of Fatima Robinson on the right. Their names are written in the middle with text at the top that reads "Hidden Herstory." A while line connects the two women.
A black and white photograph of Salt-N-Pepa. Spinderella is on the proper right side.

Black infographic with 5 costumes for the women in The Wiz on Broadway. From left to right: A costume comprised of two (2) pieces, a gown and an accompanying headdress, worn by Dee Dee Bridgewater as the character Glinda; The gown and petticoat worn by Mabel King as Evillene  — a floor-length gown made from a black synthetic fiber and has a bejeweled open-neck bodice, puffed sleeves, decorative eyes covering the bosom, and a very full skirt with a purple and deep rose ruffled trim and a slight train; the jumpsuit worn by Wendy Edmead, made from a diaphanous, coral-colored synthetic fabric; the dress and belt worn by Stephanie Mills as Dorothy — it is a short-sleeved off-white cotton dress that falls just above the knee and has a circle skirt with a flounce, with red ribbon woven into the middle of the lace; The teal and blue floor-length gown and purple petticoat worn by Clarice Taylor as Addaperle.
Black infographic with two pairs of white ankle-length platform boots. White text above the boots read, "Costume boots for the Wizard in The Wiz on Broadway, worn by Carl Hall."
Diana Ross. side 1: I Thought It Took a Little Time (But Today I Fell in Love [mono]; 45 rpm. Accessioned with original printed sleeve. Diana's face shines in the middle of the dark background.
A costume comprised of a teal dress (.1), a light green vest (.2), and a light green hat (.3) worn by Diana Ross as Billie Holiday in the Paramount Pictures produced 1972 film "Lady Sings the Blues".

Photo of Debi Thomas in yellow ice staking leotard gliding over ice with skates on. She is striking a lengthened, graceful pose with her arms lifted in the air. Her hair is pulled back in a bun and her leg facing away from the camera is stretched out behind her.
A black-and-white photograph of Aretha Franklin. She has a slight smile and she stares straight at the camera. Her chin rests on her right index finger. She is wearing a dress, bracelet, and ring.

Designed graphic with event information featuring  Stanley Clarke (photo by Toshi Sakurai), Donald Harrison, Jr. (photo courtesy of Donald Harrison), Billy Hart (photo by Desmond White), and Cassandra Wilson (photo by Mark Seliger).

In color portrait of Dr. Dorothy Height taken in June 2008. She is wearing a stylish church hat with a large flower brooch adorned on her blazer. She is wearing a chunky necklace and large earrings as she looks into the camera.
Ruby Dee during 43rd Annual Emmy Awards at Pasadena Civic Center in Pasadena, California, United States. She is smiling and looking directly at the camera while she holds her Emmy Award.
Button worn by supporters of the Equal Rights Amendment. The button is green with large white text on it that reads, "ERA YES."

Green infographic with the book cover for "Civil Rights Queen" by Tomiko Brown-Nagin on the right, which has a black-and-white photo of Constance Baker Motley giving a peace sign with a slight smile on her face as she looks at the camera. Text on the left reads, "Historically Speaking: A virtual conversation between Michel Martin and Tomiko Brown-Nagin, Tuesday, March 29 7:00pm - 8:00pm, Online."
Black and white sketched portrait of Henry O. Flipper as a cadet. At the bottom of the sketch is his name and ranking written by hand.

Pink infographic with a black-and-white cutout of Ruby Dee on the left and a color photograph of Regina King wearing a white dress and holding an Oscar. Their names are written in the middle with text at the top that reads "Hidden Herstory."
Black-and-white photo of Jackie “Moms” Mabley performing on a stage. She wears a blouse and skirt and has her arms outstretched, and a broad smile on her face.
Black and white photo of Unita Blackwell standing at a podium with a microphone. She is wearing a dark longsleeved dress with a large white bow at the collar. Her hair is trimmed into a curly afro.

Photographic print of Queen Latifah during the filming. " Latifah looks sideways at the camera with lips pursed and her right hand held up in an "L" shape. She wears a multi-colored cylindrical hat and matching jacket in a woven design and large drop earrings in a design. The photo is signed and dated on the front with inscriptions on the back by Bill Adler identifying the photographer, subject, location, and date.

Designed graphic featuring the profile view of an illustrated woman's face with information about the E3 summit in text underneath the NMAAHC logo. On the right side of the graphic there is a button that reads ONLINE and above it a hashtag that says #WomensE3.

Black and White photo from the 60s of a young Myrlie Evers speaking microphone  addressing the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People Freedom Rally at Howard University. At far left is Mrs. Evers' son Darrell seated in a suit. Behind Myrlie are two rows of people sitting in dresses and suits. The sign in front of the podium reads SEGREGATION MUST GO NOW.

Black-and-white photograph on the left of a man wearing a cap and gown and with a light sash and A stereograph of Howard University in the late 19th century on the right on a black background. An orange line joins the photos together, and text on the graphic that reads, “Studio portrait of a man in graduation cap and gown,” “HBCU Legacies,” and “A stereograph of Howard University in the late 19th century.”

Black-and-white photograph on the left of a female cheerleader and a sepia-toned photo on right of 3 men wearing suits, ties, fedoras and overcoats on a black background. An orange line joins the photos together, and text under the photos reads, “Portrait of a Mississippi Vocational College chearleader,” “HBCU Life,” and “Photograph of Waldo C. Falkener, Sr. and two unidentified men at Bennett College.”

A lithographic print of Hiram Revels from Frank Leslie’s Illustrirte Zeitung. The print is bordered by printed German text. The print has been hand colored. Hiram Revels is pictured wearing a blue suit with a red necktie. Underneath the image is “Hiram Revels, farbinger Bundes-Senator von Mississippi.” The top of the image says “Frank Leslie’s Illustrirte Zeitung.”

Black and White headshot of Tammi Terrell with both of her index fingers pointed up and rested next to each corner of her bottom lip. She is wearing 60s era makeup and has her hair in a sleek beehive updo. Her eyes are open wide with a dazed yet calm expression on her face. She is wearing a light colored dress with straps that exposes her shoulders and arms.

Color photograph of a Town Meeting in 2005 focused on where the National Museum of African American History and Culture was to be built. Journalist Renee Poussaint stands on the right at a podium, wearing a red top and speaking in a microphone. A fern sits below the podium, and to the left in the background are three people sitting at a long table on the stage, facing the audience.
A gelatin silver print of Fannie Lou Hamer wearing a floral print top. She is standing on a dirt road. The photograph is mounted to black cardboard.
Designed graphic with written event info in the center. A photo is on the right side of the graphic featuring activists in all black with matching sweatshirts holding their fists up in the air.

Lavender infographic with a black-and-white cutout of Elizabeth Catlett next to a head of one of her sculptures on the left and a color photograph of Bisa Butler wearing a colorful red and blue top on the right. Their names are written in the middle. Their names are written in the middle, with text at the top that reads "Hidden Herstory."

Photo of the Heritage Hall at the entrance of the National Museum of African American History and Culture. Three five-foot-tall bronze sculptures stand spaced out in the center of the photo on the floor. On the left and right are two slightly abstract forms of standing women, and in the center is a slightly abstract form of a seated woman holding a child upon her lap.

Graphic with a purple background and white text on the left that says "Because of Harriet ____" and below text that reads "#HiddenHerstory Learn More at nmaahc.si.edu." On the right, a cut out black-and-white photo of Harriet Tubman is in front of a green circle, with flowers and stems around her. A few flowers are also in the top and bottom left corners.

Black-and-white photo of Harriet Tubman with family and neighbors, circa 1887, at her home in Auburn, NY. Left to right: Harriet Tubman; Gertie Davis {Watson} (adopted daughter born 1874, died ?) behind Tubman; Nelson Davis (husband and 8th USCT veteran); Lee Chaney (neighbor's child); "Pop" John Alexander (elderly boarder in Tubman's home); Walter Green (neighbor's child); Blind "Aunty" Sarah Parker (elderly boarder); Dora Stewart (great-niece and granddaughter of Tubman's brother Robert Ross aka John Stewart).

Matte collodion photograph of Harriet Tubman standing in an interior room setting. The full-length portrait shows Tubman facing the photographer in the middle of the frame with her hands resting on the back of an upholstered chair. Tubman wears a dark bodice with metal buttons at the center front and full-length fitted sleeves. A white ruffled lace collar is tied at her neck. Her ankle length skirt is full with gathers at the waist and a wide decorative fabric band around the skirt near the hem. Her shoes with rounded toes are visible below her skirt. Her hair is parted at the center and pulled back at the nape of her neck. A coat or other article of clothing is draped over the chair and a hat is placed on the chair seat. Behind and to Tubman's right is a table covered in a patterned cloth with a book placed on the table top. The floor is carpeted and a painted drop with details mimicking wainscoting and a fluted column is visible in the background.

A carte-de-visite of Harriet Tubman seated in an interior room. She is positioned slightly turned to the right and gazes off camera. Her right hand rests on the back of a wooden chair and her left hand rests in her lap. A boldly patterned carpet covers the floor and the wall or drop behind her is a blank light color.
Designed graphic with a photo of Maya Rhodan on the right side and the event info on the left hand side. The museum's logo is sitting in the top left corner of the graphic.

The quilt depicts Tubman, in multiple bright-colored fabrics, seated against a dark floral background. Tubman gazes directly at the viewer, her proper right arm on the back of the chair and her proper left hand in her lap. Her face and hands are shown in contrasting shades of blue and purple with rich reds, symbolizing Tubman’s coolness, calmness, and strength as well as her power and force.

Black, white, red and grey designed graphic featuring the Attica movie poster on the right side and event info on the left side. The poster is black and white with illustrated men from the shoulders up standing with their hands behind their heads and one man in the center with his fist raised.

Black and white photo of Phyllis Mae Daley with her class of nurses at their swearing in ceremony. A man in uniform stands at the far left of the photo, and the five nurse inductees are standing adjacent to each other with their right hands raised and left hands at their sides. They are dressed in vintage dresses with tights and coiffed hair styles. Phyllis is the second woman from the right.

A black-and-white photo of prima ballerina Janet Collins. She is dancing in a full-length flowing dress. She is bending backwards slightly, looking down towards the floor, her hands outstretched together in front of her. Her legs are outstretched and her bare feet are pointed slightly away from each other.

Black and white image of Sarah Rector as a child. She is standing and staring into the camera. One of her arms is rested on the top of a chair. Her other hand is hanging to her side. She has dark hair in pigtails and is wearing a long sleeve, button up plaid dress that has a sash fastened around the waist. She is wearing Black tights and the photo cuts off before reaching her shoes.

Cabinet card depicting Sojourner Truth seated, wearing a dark dress and a white shawl and cap. Her right arm is folded at the waist, her left arm is resting on a small table. She holds knitting in her left hand. On the table are a book and a vase of flowers. Beneath her image is a printed caption that reads "I sell the shadow to support the substance/ Sojourner Truth." On the back in the center is a block of printed text that reads "Entered according to act of Congress in the year 1864, by SOJOURNER TRUTH, in the clerk's office, of the U.S. District Court, for the Eastern District of Michigan."

Infographic with a black background, on the left is the photo of a Freedmen’s Bureau document, and on the right is white text that reads, “I have the honor to request that transportation be furnished to Sojourner Truth, to Rochester, N.Y. & return for the purpose of conducting freed people to homes and employment there secured."

Black-and-white photo of African American family in front of a small home with a tree in front. The woman is in the front and the family and children are behind, standing around a wagon pulled by a cow.

Black-and-white image of African American children standing in front of a school, at the top of the school is the text “Freemen’s School.” Two adults stand on either side, trees are in the background.
Black-and-white photograph of an African American family in the late 1800s. They stand in front of a series of small homes with chimneys, with trees in the background.
A black-and-white portrait of Claudette Colvin. She is wearing glasses and staring straight at the camera, lips parted in a half-smile.

Yellow infographic with a black-and-white cutout of Lorraine Hansberry on the left and Issa Rae on the right. Their names are written in the middle. Their names are written in the middle, with text at the top that reads "Hidden Herstory."
Photo of a food on a white plate. Trout fillets are on the right, and next to it on the left is corn with some red peppers and greens.
A large, round iron pot with a brown, orange and red patina. The pot rests on four short legs and has four handles.
Colorful illustrated illustration  of  Kinshasha Holman Conwill & Paul Gardullo smiling from the shoulders up.
No ink on negative. Marian Anderson singing in front of bank of microphones. Crowd is seated behind her. Steps of the Memorial are visible in background. "8" edge imprint.

Photo of Trayvon wearing his flight suit with badges running down the front. His hand opposite to the camera is rested on the propeller of a plane. He is smiling at the camera and standing in front of another student in a flight suit who is obscured. A large plane sits in the right corner of the photo.

A black-and-white digital photograph by Devin Allen of a group of unidentified men and an unidentified child protesting in Baltimore, Maryland. A child wearing a short-sleeved striped polo shirt stands in the left foreground holding a sign with printed text reading "WE ARE / ALL / TRAYVON / MARTIN!"  A photograph of Martin is printed in the upper right corner of the sign.
Color of photo of Rosa Parks doing yoga on the left, on the write is white text on a magenta background that reads, "Self Care, Rosa Parks Practicing Yoga."

A designed graphic with black and grey contrasts that reads DEATH AND THE KING'S HORSEMAN center left with the words "by Wole Soyinka" in smaller letters underneath. The graphic holds details about the program with the date in the bottom left corner. A small red box that reads ONLINE in all caps is in the right hand corner.

Black and white profile portrait of W.E.B Du Bois. Du Bois has short, cropped, receding dark hair and a full mustache with a clipped goatee beard. His eyes are looking downward and he has a calm, pensive expression on his face. He is wearing a dark overcoat with a white button up shirt folded over the collar. The photo is framed in a white frame with various color swatches at the top and bottom of the frame.

An infographic with a teal borderline and a photograph of Dr. Kizzmekia S. Corbett on the right side, and text on the left that reads, "Dr. Kizzmekia S. Corbett, Research fellow and the scientific lead for the Coronavirus Vaccines & Immunopathogenesis Team at the National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases, Vaccine Research Center."

An infographic with a teal borderline and on the left, two vials of the covid-19 vaccine at the top,  and a Covid-19 vaccination record card at the bottom, on the right is text that reads, “Covid-19 Pandemic, Sandra Lindsay, an intensive care nurse with Northwell Health, was the first person known to receive the vaccine in the U.S.”

Infographic with a teal borderline and a black background, with pieces of paper in the center about Black Aid-work during the 1793 Pandemic on the left. On the right is text that reads, “Smallpox and Yellow Fever Pandemics, Narrative of Black Aid-work during the 1793 Pandemic by Absolom Jones and Richard Allen.”

Released in the Netherlands by Philips Records in 1965, an orange Nina Simone record cover that features a black and white image of Simone singing at a piano against an orange background with large white text reading [NINA / SIMONE] at the top and smaller white text reading [I LOVES YOU, PORGY / MISSISSIPPI GODDAM / DON'T LET ME BE / MISUNDERSTOOD / I PUT A SPELL ON YOU]  across the piano.

An image of the  back of the Nina Simone album cover has black printed text over a white background and has the song and credit info as well as advertisements for four other Philips Records releases across the bottom. At the very bottom left is [Cover photo: Frits van Swoll] and at bottom right is [Printed in Holland]. The vinyl record has a blue label with silver text on each side.

Black and white photograph that depicts the 19 members of the Tuskegee Airmen class SE-43-D. The men are in two rows. The front row of men are kneeling or squatting down in front of the back row. All of the men are wearing training uniforms, aviator helmets and goggles. The last name of every person is handwritten next to them in ink. Also handwritten in black ink at the bottom of the photograph is: [Class SE 43-D].
A black and white photograph of Audre Lorde. She is featured standing, facing the camera with her hands in her pockets.

Infographic with a red line around the boarder on an off-white background. In the center are two mixed media portraits, each of a man with a pigeon emerging from the top of his head, framed within a red frame in the shape of a birdcage. The man on the right has his head cast down with his hand over his face.

Infographic with a red line around the boarder on a off-white background. On the left is a mixed media portrait of a man with a pigeon emerging from the top of his head, framed within a red frame in the shape of a birdcage. On the right is black text that reads, "Psychological Redlining (13 studies), Portrait by Rashaun Rucker."
