Designed graphic that reads "Historically Speaking: An Evening with Secretary Bunch and Ras Baraka" over lighter colored blocks towards the right hand side of the graphic. On the left side of the graphic is a photo of Mayor Baraka smiling and leaning forward with "Audible Original" and "The Book of Baraka" written over the photo.

Designed graphic that reads "Historically Speaking: A Conversation with Timothy Todd" with the subtitle "Tuesday, February 22, 2022 7:00pm - 8:00pm". Underneath that caption is a button that reads ONLINE. There is also a graphic of the cover of 'A Great Moral and Social Force' book. The book has a black and white photo of three African American men on the cover.

An infographic with a handwritten diary on the left on a black background, encased in a red leather cover with "Diary / 1865" embossed in gold lettering at top center surrounded by an ornate wreath. White text on the right reads “Diaries and Letters by African American Soldiers, Diary of Lieutenant John Freeman Shorter.”
Wedding Portrait of the Bride and Groom Eating the Wedding Cake

This is a "Wedding Memories" scrapbook made by Lollaretta Pemberton for her wedding to Grover Allen on July 10, 1939. These pages include her notes under the page titled “Our Wedding Journey” and a page titled “Our Honeymoon” with newspaper clippings under it.

Black-and-white portrait photograph of bride Lollaretta Pemberton in her wedding dress and her groom Grover Allen in a white suit, with dark tie, lapel pin and pocket square standing in front of a painted back drop. The ivory colored lace and tulle wedding dress has short puffed sleeves, a bodice with center ruching, and alternating narrow panels of lace and tulle, running vertically up the skirt.

Infographic promoting the a new digital initiative, the North Star. Text on the graphc reads, "North Star, A Digital Journey of African American History, Online Resources for students in grades 6-12 and educators, Explore our new educational webpage and learning activities designed to share African American history using the museum’s collection."

Black-and-white photograph of young men and women sitting at a long banquet table inside a restaurant. They are all looking towards the camera and are dressed formally with the men wearing suits with boutonnieres and the women wearing dresses and hats. There is a sign on the wall behind them for Burts Ice Creams. A printed label below the image says “N. A. A. C. P. Youth Council 1940.”

Black and White vintage photo taken from a distance of a crowd of African American men, each holding a sign that reads 'I AM A MAN' in bold lettering on the front. The men are wearing distinct combinations of suits, button ups, hats and trousers etc. -- however, their collective signs create a striking cascade wave-like effect filling the middle of the photo with I AM A MAN signs.

Infographic promoting a new podcast series with white text on the left that reads, "into america presents Reconstructed: A Black History Series." The MSNBC logo is on the bottom left, the infographic red with sections of photographs and paintings on the right, and a black-and-white photograph cutout of the host.

Black-and-white photograph of Betty Davis. She is posing close down to the floor with one hand on her hip and her other resting on her leg, cradling her face. Her head is upturned mid-laugh, looking directly at the camera.

Infographic with a painting of Henrietta Lacks on the left, and on the right is a purple background with white text that reads: "Henrietta Lacks (HeLa): The Mother of Modern Medicine, Portrait by Kadir Nelson."
Black-and-white photo of 3 African American men in a band. They all wear suits and bowties, the men on the right and left play guitar, and the man in the middle plays the bass.

Engraved portrait of James James McCune Smith c. 1850. He wears a bow tie and suit jacket in the engraving, looking off-camera. The background is a yellow-ish color, and a green line borders the portrait. Text inside reads: “James McCune Smith, America’s first university-trained African American physician.”
A photographic postcard of Lawrence McVey in uniform posing at attention. The word [HERO] is inscribed in pencil on the top right corner.

Black and white vintage photo of Hank Aaron swinging a baseball bat in the direction of the camera at a unique angle where his body appears smaller than the bat in the frame. He is wearing a baseball cap with a brim and his Atlanta Braves uniform.

A photo of Hank Aaron's Atlanta Braves jersey. Set against a dark background, the jersey is short-sleeved and a light color with seven buttons going up the center. Over the chest area, the jersey reads "Braves" in cursive. There are badges on the right sleeve and in the bottom right corner. Over the badges in the bottom corner, there is a fading Hank Aaron signature.

A black and white profile photo of Rosa Parks in her older age staring out a window with a slight smile. Her body is turned to one side of the camera and her hand is raised to the window's curtains. Sunlight is streaming into the room over her face's profile. Her hair is lightened with age, and in an updo with a braid over the crown of her head. She's wearing a dark jacket with a light blouse underneath.

Black and white image of Martha Sapp holding a baby, both lying in bed. Sapp lays in a bed, covered in blankets and sheets, smiling, open-mouthed. Her proper right hand holds the proper left hand of her child. Her head rest on a pillow. She and the baby take up most of the image, diagonally, from the upper left to the lower right. the baby lays eyes closed and hands raised to its face.

A designed graphic featuring a cutout photo of Chef Ramin Coles smiling a broad smile with his arms crossed over his chest that reads "New Executive Chef" in bold lettering to his right.  There are assorted graphics of  healthy greens and vegetables underneath him in a darker colored banner. Behind Chef Coles are graphic outlines of pots and pans.

Dark graphic featuring the cover of 'Make Good the Promises' book  cover. The text on the graphic sites the event details (Wednesday, February 9, 2022 7:00pm - 8:00pm) and the museum logo in the top left corner.

Black and white signed patent of Alfred L. Cralle's original ice cream scooper. On the top of the document it reads "A. L. Cralle Ice Cream Mold and Disher." There is a space underneath that headline and then the  text continues, "No. 576,395" and "Patented Feb. 2, 1987." There are two sketches rendering the original ice cream scooper device from both  side and top views labeled Fig. 1 and Fig 2.

Black and White photo of an African American woman buying ice-cream for children from a truck, June 1940. The woman has her right hand leaned against the side of the  wooden rails of the truck with her other hand on her hip. Two small children are standing in front of her to the left, one eating an ice cream cone. Several men are standing or squatting in the bed of the truck, dishing out ice cream cones.

White infographic with purple border and a photo on the right of a black and white image of several rows of women seated, all wearing midwife uniforms. Text on the right reads: "Midwives, untitled (midwives in class)” with an image credit underneath.

White infographic with purple border and a photo on the right of a black and white image of a midwife and expectant mother arranging items on a bed. Text on the right reads: "Midwives, untitled (preparing for birth)" with an image credit underneith.
A black and white image of four women and a baby seated on a bench. All women are seated in front of a white brick walls. In the upper left corner are dark bricks on the wall behind the seated women.
Black-and-white photograph of an African America family in the late 1800s, standing in front of several small houses, with trees overhead.
Color photograph of Jackie Robinson. He stands on the field of a baseball stadium wearing his Dodgers uniform, ready to swing the baseball bat in his hands.
A black-and-white head-and-shoulders portrait of Coretta Scott King. She is smiling and looking facing away from the camera with her head slightly upturned.
Photo of the National Museum of African American History and Culture with blue skies above and snow on the ground.
Photograph from a magazine of Matthew Henson. He is has a mustache and is wearing a large fur-lined hood and fur coat. He is looking just beyond the camera.
A pocket watch belonging to Matthew Henson. The watch is silver in color, and has a white face with black hands and roman numerals.

A white poster with black lettering used by Arthur J. Schmidt during the 1968 Memphis March. The poster reads "I / AM / A MAN." There is a small Allied Printing Trades Council union bug in black ink at bottom center. The back of the poster is blank.
A circular pinback button featuring a sepia portrait of the aviator Bessie Coleman. The portrait is the one used on her aviation license issued by the Federation Aeronautique Internationale.
A black-and-white photograph of Robert L. Johnson sitting behind a desk. He is adjusting a television knob with his right hand. He is looking directly at the camera.

A black-and-white photo of Arturo Alfonso Schomburg. He is seated in an ornate chair, wearing a suit and bowite. One hand rests on the arm of the chair, another on his crossed knee. He is looking off-camera.
Black-and-white photo of Sam Cooke. He is seated with his hands clasped around his crossed knee, looking back over his shoulder at the camera.

This full-length studio portrait photograph features early African American pilot Willa B. Brown, posed in her flying suit photograph. The photograph was taken somewhere between 1925 and 1935 in Chicago, Illinois.

A color photograph of a group of men and women. The first row has two young women and two women sitting. The second row has two men on either side of a woman standing. They are wearing various outfits. The group is standing in front of a white wall with a light switch visible to the right.

A color photograph of a group of women, men and children outside on the grass. Trees are visible in the background. There are two rows. The first row has five people sitting on chairs and one man kneeling. Two children stand in front of the second row of 13 men and women standing. They are wearing various outfits.

Infographic advertising the museum's virtual program A Seat at the Table, with 4 photos of students and 3 red, green, and yellow circles behind them. Text on the graphic reads: "A Seat at the Table, Discovering the triumphs and challenges of Black education. Join us on February 4 for food and conversation.
Photo of the National Museum of African American History and Culture lit up at twilight with snow in the foreground.
A portrait of André Leon Talley. He is staring directly at the camera, wearing a gray button down, necklace, and wrapped in a colorful cloth.

Infographic on a magenta background with a sepia-toned photograph of Idea B. Wells on the right, and a quote on the left that reads, "The South resented giving the Afro-American his freedom, the ballot box and the Civil Rights Law."
Infographic on a magenta background with 4 photos of Black women suffragists, including Sojourner Truth, Mary Church Terrell, Nannie Helen Burroughs, and Charlotte Forten Grimke.
Infographic on a magenta background with a sepia-toned photograph of Thomas Mundy Peterson on the right and text on the left that reads, "First African American man to cast a vote in an election."

An image of Muhammad Ali fighting Floyd Patterson in 1965 in Las Vegas, Nevada. The image shows Ali landing a left handed punch, while Patterson has both arms up to block the hit. Ali stands to the left of the photograph, Patterson to the right. The two are at the center of the ring and the referee, Harold Krause, looks on from near the ropes. The ring is surrounded by photographers and spectators.

A photograph of a case and exhibition in the museum featuring Martin Luther King, Jr. The case on the left shows 3 pieces of paper, which is Martin Luther King Jr.’s original speech from the 1963 March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom. On the right is an exhibit case with a black-and-white photograph of Martin Luther King Jr. at the March on Washington.

Two images. 
On left: Black and white photograph of hundreds of people sitting in chairs along steps leading up to a giant building with five, big stone columns. A banner hanging across the columns reads” “Join the celebration! Postal Service Day. July 1, 1971.” 

On right: Black and white photograph with 8 postal service employees (three women on the left, then five men) posing in a row on steps outside of a large door, ornate door of a large, stone building. The women are dressed in matching, short dresses and wear sashes reading “Miss U.S.P.S.” The men are dressed in security guard attire: matching trousers with belt, short sleeved white button-down shirt, matching neckties, and police-style caps.

Her hand is placed on her neck. 

On right: Black and white photograph of Lean Horne posing, seated, with one hand placed on her hip and the other on her neck. Her head is cocked slightly upwards and to the left. She is dressed in attire with a ruffled collar and sleeves; one dangly earring is visible.

In 2020, converging crises have forced us to think about public health from a virological standpoint while we stand in the debilitating mental crisis of racial trauma." by Marc Bamuthi Joseph

We will continue to release online resources to offer sustained engagements with xenophobia in U.S. history across a range of different formats and media on our website. We will also share materials by leading artists, scholars, educators, curators, archivists, and community organizers to support self-education and self-care. The cumulative references are meant to generate understanding and self-reflexivity so that we might overcome fear and find empowerment, motivation, and solace even in these difficult times.

We will continue to release online resources to offer sustained engagements with xenophobia in U.S. history across a range of different formats and media on our website. We will also share materials by leading artists, scholars, educators, curators, archivists, and community organizers to support self-education and self-care. The cumulative references are meant to generate understanding and self-reflexivity so that we might overcome fear and find empowerment, motivation, and solace even in these difficult times.

We also reject responses that perpetuate discrimination and divisions between communities of color, understanding that these divisions do not solve the root issues that plague us. We renew our recognition that Black lives and Black communities matter, that Asian Americans and Pacific Islanders have a complex history of conflict and coalition with Black communities, and AAPI communities must continue to confront anti-Blackness and stand against systemic racism and unjust treatment of Black people throughout the United States and the world.

At the Smithsonian Asian Pacific American Center, we stand with communities, locally and globally, to build awareness of our interconnected experiences—especially in times of social turmoil. Even as we witness these moments - which sadden, horrify, and anger us - the Center also seeks to build bridges across difference, by bringing awareness to issues which undermine our shared humanity, and by fostering a sense of belonging and solidarity across communities. This includes addressing not only the hatred and violence that is targeting people of Asian descent, but also the xenophobia that plagues our society during times of national crisis.

This type of “othering” divides communities by dehumanizing groups of people when anxiety is manipulated and misdirected to place blame in a time of crisis. This diverts attention away from the core issue, away from knowledge and understanding, and away from beneficial solutions.

The world has undergone tremendous change as COVID-19 reshapes our lives and increases our fears. The spread of the virus has occasioned the rise of anti-Asian racism and xenophobia throughout the U.S., taking the forms of vandalism, student bullying, online hate speech, and more recently, violent attacks against elders. This type of “othering” divides communities by dehumanizing groups of people when anxiety is manipulated and misdirected to place blame in a time of crisis. This diverts attention away from the core issue, away from knowledge and understanding, and away from beneficial solutions.

Colorful graphic listing statistics: (1) Between 2000 and 2015, the Asian Pacific American population grew 72% – the fastest growth rate of any major racial or ethnic group. (2) Less than 2% of teachers identify as Asian American or Pacific Islander.

Did you know? Today, more than 20 million people of Asian or Pacific Islander descent live in the United States. In less than 50 years, nearly one of every 10 people in the nation will trace their heritage to Asia and the Pacific.

Tablet computer with large screen showing app icons in rows.
Several rows of tiny, bright white squares printed on black paper create a thick, wavy border around a gray and white print of a lattice chair.

A costume design depicting a seated figure in left profile wearing a red shirt, a black cloak, a black helmet, grey tights and sleeves, holding a red rook chess piece in their right, black gloved hand.

A stage design composed of vertical stripes in blue, yellow, orange, red and black, with four large triangles in white, red, black and green in the center. The triangles are overlaid with groups of colored diagonal lines.
Install image of Kauffer exhibition featuring two costumes on two mannequins.

The words [An American In Paris] take the shape of the Eiffel Tower, in red on one side of the tower and black on another to give a sense of depth. A wavy version of the same text appears behind in a light and dark blue to suggest a shadow.
Wallpaper pattern of willow leaves spreading across the paper. The background is a teal color, with the leaves and branches a darker shade.
Wallpaper pattern of willow leaves spreading across the paper. The background is an orange color, with the leaves and branches a darker shade.
Wallpaper pattern of willow leaves spreading across the paper. The background is an olive green color, with the leaves and branches a darker shade.
Wallpaper pattern of willow leaves spreading across the paper. The background is a turquoise color, with the leaves and branches a darker shade.

One folded newspaper and one unfolded newspaper on a light brown desk with a black pencil. The newspaper title reads “We Built This: How Women Innovators Shaped the World” and has teal, yellow, pink, and red graphics and icons. The USA TODAY and Smithsonian logos also appear on the cover.
A book cover with collage of graphical elements. Book title [ART / NOW] printed on a diagonal and horizontal line.
Poster featuring small black and white photograph of person on motorcycle on black and yellow road with orange, yellow, blue text: "WELL DONE! "; "11 WORLD RECORDS "; "VILLIERS".
Bold, graphic Harper’s Bazaar magazine cover in blue, orange-red, black, and white, featuring [1940] in large colorblock, overlaid with a black and white photograph of an elegantly dressed woman.

Poster with photo-illustration in yellow and turquoise of the classical sculpture known as Winged Victory of Samothrace dominating the poster. Text in black and turquoise in the upper center [AMERICAN AIRLINES], [PARIS] in the center right in black, turquoise and red.
Print of a map of the Chicago Metropolitan Area which shows data in different colors
Simple drawing of a woman holding a dog in her lap. The outline of the dog intermingles with the outline of the woman's face, so the woman's eye can also be read as part of the dog's face.
Printed length of silk showing light purple irises with green leaves on a deep purple ground. Bluebirds fly between the flower clusters.

Poster of many photographs of doors arranged in columns and rows. At the bottom read, in Celtic-style font reads [the doors of dublin], then beneath that in block font reads [AER LINGUS / IRISH AIRLINES].

Graphic of olive green patterned background with a black and white photograph of Duro Olowu, a dark-skinned man wearing a blazer and patterned shirt, at right. Next to it on the left is a block of text in an olive green square that reads [NEW EXHIBITION / DURO OLOWU SELECTS: / WORKS FROM / THE PERMANENT / COLLECTION / OPENS FRIDAY, MARCH 18, 2022]
Clear vase-shaped glass carafe painted with green leaves and white and gold flowers

Drawing of a light-skinned, red-haired woman in a black dress holding an open book. Beside her are two tall black torches with gold flames. Green scrolled vines wrap around the torches. At top reads the words [OCCUPATIONS OF WOMEN AND THEIR COMPENSATION].
Book cover with green swirling vines, blue flowers with an empty gold box at center.
Drawing for book cover with tall symmetrical arrangement of red carnations with green stems.
Telephone made of white plastic, the handset is cradled at the top above a clear plastic rotary dial. On the left a white coiled cord connects the handset to the body

Purple wallpaper with a large yellowish tree growing up the right side of the design with a large bird perched on a branch. A golden cobweb suspends from its branches, with a yellow and white butterfly beside it in flight.
A sepia-toned photograph of a young light-skinned girl with long dark hair standing on a balcony wearing a dress with white puffy sleeves and a white ribbon in her hair.
A sepia-toned portrait photograph of a young, light-skinned girl with long fair hair dressed in a thick dark velvet dress with a lace collar and trimmings.
Sepia-toned photo of a light-skinned young woman dressed in formal clothing looking directly at the viewer.
Sepia-toned photograph of a young lady with light skin in a long dress sitting in a chair surrounded by other pieces of furniture.

Bundles of black cotton heaped together to make a sculptural form, wider at the bottom and narrower at the top. The black cotton is bound in the middle with different colored cotton that is russet, blue, or gold.

A hanging, almost square, with small tassels at top and bottom. It is off-white with an irregular diagonal line moving from the lower left to upper right corner, with branching horizontal lines, in shades of black, purple, green and undyed natural linen.

A hanging made of grey-green linen. It is Embroidered with yarns, cords and couched tape, in white and shades of yellow, green and orange, that form a collection of squares in the center of the linen.

A square embroidered hanging depicting a family, with a seated woman and infant at the center, a young boy behind them, a man on the right side and a woman on the left. Behind them is a large tree in the upper left and a cityscape in the upper right corner, with small animals in the foreground. In browns, oranges, pinks, and neutrals on a natural linen ground.
Painting of five purple thistles with green stems on black paper.
Beige silk printed textile with repeating thistle design in light red and olive green.
Black and white photograph of a room in a museum with casts of sculptures on display.
Black and white photograph of women at a drawing class.
Black and white photograph of a gallery at Cooper Union, a classical sculpture is at the foreground and the woman paints at an easel at left.
Black and white photograph of a grand, four-story building with horses and carriages, foliage, and pedestrians milling about nearby.
wallpaper of stylized poppy flowers and foliage meandering back and forth across the width of the design, creating a vibrant pattern. Printed in three shades of orange-red on a white ground.
Black and white photograph of plush hotel dining room.
Black and white photograph of Lucille Ball, standing in a confident pose with hands on hips and one foot tucked behind that other. She looks away from the camera.
Plaid fabric in a rainbow of colors. From left to right the textile changes color in stripes from orange and red, through pink and purple, to green and yellow.
Black and white photograph of Dorothy Liebes standing at a rack of hanging fabrics. Her body is faced away from the camera but her head is turned to look at the lens.

Set of wooden square and rectangular building blocks painted in stripes of white, blue, and orange. Two orange conical shapes sit atop stacks of blocks to look like chimneys of a factory. Three toy cars are placed around the blocks.
Pale brown textile with two white cranes flying towards one another, wings outstretched, against a backdrop of pale teal, salmon red, ochre, cream and black swirling clouds.

White textile woven with blue cross-stitch giving checkerboard effect, lime, emerald and forest green stems and foliage swirl across the surface extending into peach, yellow, blue, white and maroon flowers and buds.
Cream textile with printed pattern of maroon flowers and foliage outlined in lime green, and lime green cheetahs and birds with maroon spots.
Stainless steel cylindrical ice bucket with a pair of tongs beside it.

Scarf with red and blue border and ribbon-script lettering that reads "America and France United Forever, George Washington 1783". At center are two heads in profile, wearing different styled helmets to represent France and the US.
Cream colored L shaped plastic stand with calendar dates displayed individually on white plastic with black font, shown fanned out.
Same calendar as previous image, this time showing the date 1 JAN SUN
Pocket-sized pager with rectangular gray body with rounded corners. A rectangular digital screen takes up the top half of the face of the device, a QWERTY button keyboard is below.
Colorful poster of elevated view of stylized sailboats  on water waterfront with small figures and text: "NOW PROCEEDING/ SUMMER/ SALE AT/ Derry / & TOMS / KENSINGTON W. 8"
Black cotton face mask with the name [BREONNA TAYLOR] printed in a handwritten style typeface in white
Heart shaped necklace with wings made of many gold-plated steel layers resembling clockwork cogs.
A lithograph print of an owl with big eyes looking forward, standing among a group of sunflowers
Section of a strip of printed dress silk with a repeating design of a cartoonish jazz orchestra, in dark blue on white ground.
Silk printed textile with light purple poppies on dark purple background.
Painted studies of three red poppies and green stems, on grey paper.

Black and white poster featuring a photograph of a nude, muscular Black man wearing a baseball mitt on one hand. His hands meet in front of him so that the mitt covers his genital area. Beneath the photograph in bold text are the words "NO GLOVE, NO LOVE! RUBBERS – EVERY TIME!"
A block print in light yellow on a darker yellow background featuring intricate imagery of a wave and various sea creatures.
A bright red portable radio made of molded plastic shaped like a donut, but in this image we see it opened up at its joint at the base.
A bright red portable radio made of molded plastic shaped like a donut.

Banner of images separated into three sections. The first has two sepia toned photographic portraits of the Hewitt Sisters, dressed in 19th-century clothing. The second section is a textile design of purple flowers with green stems and leaves on a purple background. The last section is a photo of a silver tea caddy, ornately decorated with flowers, shells and lions, among other things.
Book jacket for James Joyce’s ULYSSES. Background color is black; uppercase letters spell out title; lettering is grey, white, turquoise, and yellow
Screenshot of a website containing images and text.
A bronze sculpture of a prone yawning tiger with outstretched front paws.
Medical illustration of the COVID-19 virus.
A New York City sidewalk with figures, some carrying umbrellas, walking in the driving snow.  At right, a long row of stoops, similar in design, all covered with snow.
Wallpaper with pattern of large acanthus leaves, tulips, and wiry scrolls intertwine with large perching peacocks whose tails hang downward.
Children's radio cassette player made of molded plastic in bright primary colors
An oval-shaped box with flat bottom and top, decorated around it's sides with a pair of squirrels eating nuts beneath a tree.

Cocktail shaker in the form of a standing penguin with flat wings at sides and a flat base in the form of feet. The lid is in the form of penguin's head and shoulders, with a hinged beak as the spout.
Wallpaper with the image of a life-size cow’s head repeating as a pattern. The Cow is brown on a blue ground.

Poster design encouraging travel to Europe via American Airlines. Stylized eagle, shown in profile facing right, composed from flat, geometric planes of blue and navy. Text in red, white, and blue, across poster on a diagonal: AMERICAN AIRLINES / TO / EUROPE. Superimposed on a blue stripe at bottom, center: [American Airlines logo in white and red]

Poster design encouraging travel to California via American Airlines. Photograph of a woman in a bathing suit montaged into an illustrated beach scene including sand and ocean waves, where she appears to toss a large colorful beach ball into the air. Text in blue, upper center: AMERICAN / AIRLINES; in orange, center: TO CALIFORNIA [American Airlines logo].

Poster for American Airlines advertising New York. Stylized white skyscrapers in foreground, against blue sky with clouds. American flag hangs from building facade, lower center. Text in light blue and white, upper center: AMERICAN / AIRLINES; in blue, lower left: [American Airlines logo in black] TO NEW YORK.
Six gnomes with long grey beards and appropriate outfits are gathered around a barrel of beer in a wood—they are merrymaking, each with a cup of beer in their hands.
An eye-catching poster of a cartoon-like worker holding a bin of tomatoes and the words [WORKERS FIRST] printed in bubble font repeating vertically in wavy lines filling the background.
Wallpaper with large pale green poppy flowers interlocking over a blanket of green and bluish leaves and yellow pimpernel blossoms.
Written in white capital letters the words [CLIMATE CHANGE] repeat in a column on a black background. With each repeat of the words the typeface thins until the bottom iteration is barely legible.

Centered stylized black arm swoops forward with extended fist from black round circle, geometric red structure in background of upper right corner.  Black, blue, red text reads [POWER / THE / NERVE CENTRE / OF LONDON'S / UNDERGROUND].
Photograph of iPhone from 2007. Rectangular in shape, with curved corners, the phone is flat with black and chrome edges. The screen shows several rows of apps.

Poster depicting a series of mixers and sliders that categorize the albums of David Bowie between a set of extremes.  Featuring seven columns for each album released between 1976-84, with "DAVID/ BOWIE" printed in silver ink at the bottom of the poster in custom typography.
Textile design drawing of a pattern of multiple tigers overlapping in different directions across the page.
A young woman with a kerchief over her head and a long brown dress shovels snow away from the garden path. Behind her a fountain with frozen water. Upper right in a box is the word [JANVIER]
Dark gray rectangular electronic personal assistant with antenna on right side, and hinged at the top. The lid lifts to reveal a rectangular screen showing icons for various functions.
Screenshot of operating system for Motorola Envoy showing icons for inbox, outbox, clock, etc.
Photograph of multiple trophies on a black background. The trophies are translucent and in the shape of an eight-pointed star.
Photograph of exhibition at Cooper Hewitt in which a variety of objects are on display, including a kimono.
Photograph of exhibition at Cooper Hewitt. Three posters are on display in an ornate room of the Carnegie Mansion.
Photograph of exhibition at Cooper Hewitt in which a variety of objects are on display.
Plate with various botanical illustrations printed on toned paper.
Personal computer made of translucent blue colored plastic in an egg shape. In front of the monitor is a keyboard and mouse.
Poster for the film Metropolis depicting formations of stooped workers beneath high rise buildings and giant machine wheels.

A greeting card with an illustration of a Chinese blue and white vase with a rose and two peacock feathers in it. To its right are the words [A HAPPY NEW YEAR] written in a stylized art nouveau style font.
Print of a woman in frilly dress and plumed hat holding an enormous bottle of champagne that has burst open with the cork hurtling towards some cherubs in the top right corner of the image.

Watercolor and ink textile design on white paper, with a mix of large white shells finely outlined in black against a seafoam green background swirling with currents of various pale blue tropical fishes
On a blue background, a repeating pattern of stylized trees spread across the image. Above the trees is a band of clouds and beneath is a repeating patter of bluebells.
Three collapsible cube-shaped ornaments printed with geometric decoration. Two cubes are shown flattened towards the front of the photograph, behind them is an ornament assembled into its cube shape.
Wallpaper with all-over pattern of medium size flowers alternating with small flowers. The flowers are printed in two shades of blue and black on a white ground.
Textile design of vertical stripes of repeating diagonal blue bars, on a white background.

Poster of spiral of gray-blue, beige, dark gray splatter-like dots set on top of a large white circle, black background, and silhouettes of figures in dresses falling or dancing. Text above reads [WINTER SALES] and below image states [ARE/ BEST REACHED BY THE/ UNDERGROUND].
Stencil of maple leaves in a variety of sizes. The large leaves have veins running throughout. Some have jagged edges, while others are smooth and crisp.
Stencil of maple leaves shown in a variety of forms are on a striped background.
Stencil of plum blossoms and their budding branches surround two enlarged maple leaves.
A stencil of branches of maple leaves that are surrounded by tiny hole punches.
Photograph of the Washington Monument enclosed by a white open air dome.
Textile design of zodiac symbols on a red background.
Install image of E. McKnight Kauffer exhibition at Cooper Hewitt.
Textile design of repeating pattern of birds stealing strawberries. The pattern is ornate, in an arts and crafts style, and on a blue background.

Textile design with a repeating pattern of white puppies with orange-yellow circles over one of their eyes, some with their tongues sticking out, shown both upside-down and the right-way-up against a black ground with white dots

Textile design with five white pumas, some the right-way-up and others upside-down, a row of four lilies runs down the center, the design is overlaid with yellow and orange spots and set against a black and white pin-striped ground

Textile design with nine brown bears, some upside-down, some the right-way-up and several curled up, floating on a white ground dotted with tiny black flowers, black and yellow spots, white daisies, and large pale pink circles

Two images merged together. On the left is a drawing of a sepia-toned plague doctor in profile dressed in a long overcoat, a bird-like mask with a curved beak and a round, glass-shield eye, a wide-brimmed hat, thick gloves and heeled boots. On the right is a photograph of a light-skinned individual dressed in bright colors adjusting a pink and purple face mask with a clear mouth panel, standing against a sun-dappled leafy green backdrop.

Textile design with grey and yellow curved segments interweaving like seaweed across it, and the black outline of five angel-type fish, with rounded bodies, thick lips, and speckled fins swimming through
Textile design with five zebras, shown both upright and upside-down, floating on a grey and white striped background interspersed with bright yellow daisy-like flowers with black centers

Watercolor textile design with a repeating pattern of large, white daisies, their petals outlined in pale grey and their centers speckled canary yellow, overlapping one another set against a black background

Black and white textile design with a lion crouching, mane curling outwards and yellow eyes gleaming, in the top center, surrounded by upside-down cheetahs cut by the edges and yellow lilies giving pops of color
Box shaped camera covered in brown leatherette. The faceplate is enameled with a tan and brown geometric design.
On silver patterned paper, a seven-branched blue menorah features in the middle of an orange circle with wreath of yellow leaves framing circle.

Curtain panel woven in off-white silk with gold metallic wefts which form open vertical stripes. Squares of yellow, pink, orange and purple are applied across the design, but are more dense at the top.
Photo of a light-skinned woman wearing a blue and white scrub set and white sneakers.

A black and white headshot photograph of the textile designer Marion Dorn, who appears facing the viewer with her head tilted to the left and her chin resting in her left hand. She is posed before a backdrop of one of her textile designs, a repeating motif of shells descending in stripes.

Repeating pattern of abstract doves in a textile design. The ground is green, the doves are white and their wings alternate between blue and green in the pattern, outlined with blue and white stitching.
Young children busy crafting at a table.
A poster featuring a naked male doll, like a Ken doll, on a white background. Underneath him the words [Unless You're Built Like This You Should Be Using Condoms.] are written in a black font.
Two teenagers, one female with medium-toned skin and the other male with dark-toned skin, sit at a desk covered in post-it notes, engaged in conversation.
Textile in a stepped design of rectangles printed in black, royal blue and yellow on a white ground.
Bent birch plywood seat in a ribbon-like curve.
Chair frame consisting of intersecting bent tubular steel. Orange canvas panels stretched over frame form the back, seat, and arm rests.
Chair with horizontal plywood sheets as back and seat-both with red cushions.
A silver cocktail shaker in the shape of an airship.
A silver cocktail shaker disassembled into its parts, which contains silver cups, spoons, tumblers and more.
Oval sauceboat with the handle in form of serpent/dragon, head rising over sauceboat, with delicately molded scales, teeth, tongue, and ears.
Oval sauce boat with a curved concave handle off the side; a curved ladle rests over handle to form a tube. Both are made of polished silver plate.
Marshmallow pattern, consisting of large-scale yellow flowers with green foliage, printed on white ground. This is the marshmallow plant, not the candy.
Spherical red television with convex screen at front and control knobs and hanging/carrying chain in indentation at top. A chrome-plated telescoping antenna sticks out the top.

On a beige background, a thick rose vine twines through a light grey square trellis. Red roses bloom amid green foliage; the stout vine is patterned with red thorns, and green beetles crawl in some roses. Blue birds perch on the trellis and fly upwards. The trellis and roses have heavy, dark outlines, but the blue birds are rendered with more delicate linework. In the background, small stylized brown butterflies. At the edges, outside the picture plane, various colored printing marks. "MORRIS & Co." along the right edge.
Dust jacket for [THE WEEK-END BOOK], printed in bold white, red, black, and orange, with a graphic geometric design
Dust cover of a stylized island and sea scene with bright colors, whimsical animals and title and author text.
Printed dust cover with a minimal blue and teal illustration and text. Features geometric shapes reminiscent of a book and bold, square title and author font.
Photo of the inside of a 3D printed adobe house. The words MUD FRONTIER ARCHITECTURE AT THE BORDERLAND are in the center.
Textile consisting of yellow and orange striped flowers with honey-colored centers, and yellow and orange spotted cheetahs against a yellow background with terracotta orange spots.
Kimono-style coat made from 17 sweaters. The coat has a patchwork style and each patch is a block color. The colors are blues and grays.
White and grey lilies and red and pink waterlilies with yellow centers with large green leaves and metallic silver water on a dark green ground.

Flexible silver chainmail armature covered by overlapping rows of hammered, flattened feather-like blue-black steel nails; row of small, gold pod forms along inner edge; large clasp covered by roughly square panel of pale rose mother-of-pearl with gold fasteners.

A vertical gouache painting of a herd of bovines at the base of a hill meeting the viewer's gaze. Cowboys on horses are watching from behind the herd on a rust colored plain. Green hills and blue mountains rise in the distance.
Printed advertisement based on the preceeding original artwork.

Poster design featuring a pair of worn and dirty sneakers, the one of the left has a beautiful red rose stuck into it. Text to the right of the rose reads L'EGGS MINI MARATHON, 10,000 METERS SATURDAY, JUNE 2, 1979, CENTRAL PARK, N.Y.C, 11:00AM
A simplified chair design made using vertical and horizontal planes. The back of the chair is colored red and the seat is blue. It is made of pine and steel.
Flat, circular vase with short neck and slightly spouted lip; thick cased glass body, clear, over deep blue, over amethyst-colored glass.
Color poster of a view of the countryside with  quarry, train, and silhouette of buildings in foreground.
A cream poster depicting a hilly landscape with fields and trees in greens and browns enclosed in a black, rectangular frame, with text below.
Photograph of the Smithsonian activity guide, a pamphlet sized book that has a colorful, abstract graphic design cover.
Print of a medieval looking cat catching a mouse in its paws. The cat has stripes across its back and down its tail. It is done in a gothic style and is not realistic.
A drawing of a cat done in ink and graphite. It is a cartoonish cat with a huge body and tiny legs. It's face has got human qualities, with big eyes and a big nose.
Area rug, jute and wool; different colors and sizes of overlapping horizontal rectangles; three each long slim rectangles near top left and bottom right; designer’s initials at bottom right.

Install photograph of Underground Modernist: E. McKnight Kauffer at Cooper Hewitt, featuring the carpet designed by Kauffer and the Alvar Aalto chair. The arm chair is made of bent birch plywood. A one-piece curved bent birch plywood scroll-shaped seat is suspended in its own frame composed of ribbon-like, curved, laminated bent birch elements which form sinuous legs/arms in a trapezium shape.
Drawing of pumpkin flowers, with beautiful yellow/orange blooms and green leaves and vines spreading across the page.
A young woman in a yellow dress rakes leaves in an autumnal garden.

Illustration for October from a calendar. A child stands in an autumnal field in front of a pumpkin placed on top of a barrel. The child has a knife in their hand and is standing back to see how their carving looks. The pumpkin has been carved to have a jagged smile, triangular nose, and wide eyes.
Illustration of skeletons and flames dancing about the end pages of a book.

Frontispiece from The Wood Beyond The World. On the left hand page is an illustration of a woman walking through a wood with vines of leaves encircling her waist, above her long and billowing dress. The right hand page contains text in a medieval style font. Surrounding both the text and the illustration of a woman is illustrations of leaves creating a border.
Install shot of Willi Smith: Street Couture at Cooper Hewitt. We see a portrait of the man himself around which is hung several items of clothing he designed.

Install shot of Willi Smith: Street Couture. This part of the exhibition has about a dozen t-shirts hung on a wall, all of which feature designs by prominent artists from the 80s, including Keith Haring, Jenny Holzer, Barbara Kruger, and Robert Rauschenburg.

Install shot of Willi Smith: Street Couture. This part of the exhibition shows full outfits designed by Smith. They are loose fitting and in pastel colors. The mannequins they are on are displayed on different levels so all can be seen.
Winnie-the-Pooh and friends stand around a sign in a landscape of green, rolling, hills. The sky is blue with the hint of sunlight where the sky meets the ground at the lower right hand corner.
A pen and ink drawing of Cooper Hewitt amid a swirling torrent of water.

A photograph of the exhibition Underground Modernist: E. McKnight Kauffer on display at Cooper Hewitt. Two women wearing masks are looking at a graphic representation of Kauffer’s face on a wall. Surrounding his image are lines to images of people and bodies of text about them, all of whom connect to Kauffer and his work.
Graphite drawing of E. McKnight's face shown in profile.

A stylized painting of a naked man riding a white horse. The man looks behind him as he holds onto the mane of the horse, bounding through a stylized hilly landscape. The sky behind them is yellow and full of circular, billowing clouds.
Animals outlined with thick black line. Farm and domestic animals, including dogs, chickens, rabbits, bird and chipmunk or squirrel. Printed in colors on a green ground.
Children's frieze, containing various animals, including dog, sheep, goat, pelican, rhinoceros and leopard. Printed in colors on a tan ground.
A stylized black flock of birds in flight soar towards the upper left corner on a horizontally oriented cream background.
Irregular bowl form with lacquer surface to interior and top rim, the exterior with raised felt incorporated into the side and foot.
Drawing of ears of corn on a blue background.
Drawing of cabbages, done in greens and purples.

In the center are two abstract blue, white and black seated figures, one on the other's lap set against a blue abstracted background. One holds a sphere on our right, the other has blue text across the chest.
Black and white photography of E. McKnight Kauffer and T. S. Eliot standing in a doorway. Both are dressed in 1930s suits, with Kauffer also wearing a coat and hat.

Book cover design for T.S. Eliot's poem Marina with light blue paper and black ink, all text in serif font. Center image of abstract design with geometric and realistic forms. Realistic eye is most prominent in center, surrounded by simple yet stylized architectural elements.
Design of a costume party with people in fantastic clothing held in a massive hall or temple. In red on off white.
Image of Willi Smith sitting at desk, talking on the phone in all-white office designed by SITE; white bricks are piled around office as part of design.
A poster depicting a colorful hilly and wooded landscape in bright greens, yellows and oranges.

Rectangular panel of cream-colored cotton printed in red. The design shows various shadow figures made with the hands. In a large central oval frame, a pair of hands making the shadow of a rabbit, titled below "Bunny." In the four corners are hands and shadows forming "The Camel," "The Dog," "The Goose," and "The Goat." To the left and right of the central oval, the crest of the Prince of Wales – three plumes in a crown – and the legend "Ich Dien" ("I Serve").

An old man, identified as the legendary Flavio Amalfitano, seated at his desk using a compass and reading a book; tools, books, and instruments are arranged around the richly furnished room; a dog is at his feet. A model of a ship hangs above and in front of him.
Poster with a large black rooster with red, green and blue tail feathers in the center standing on rolling hills against a rising yellow sun and pale background advertising Eno's Fruit Salts.

A photo-illustration in yellow and turquoise of the Winged Victory of Samothrace dominates the poster. Text in black and turquoise in the upper center [AMERICAN AIRLINES], [PARIS] in the center right in black, turquoise and red.
Book jacket for James Joyce’s ULYSSES. Background color is black; uppercase letters spell out title; lettering is grey, white, turquoise, and yellow.

Centered stylized black arm swoops forward with extended fist from black round circle, geometric red structure in background of upper right corner. Black, blue, red text reads [POWER / THE / NERVE CENTRE / OF LONDON'S / UNDERGROUND].
A bright yellow poster advertising the Daily Herald, with a stylized black, white and grey flock of birds in flight in the top right corner and black text below.

Beach scene with female figure in blue bikini reclining on the sand at center left. A palm tree near the shoreline and the ocean beyond. The rest of the scene populated with art-making tools: the sun over the ocean is an artist's palette, and other art -making objects protrude from the sand, including scissors, an easel and canvas with a painting of a beach scene, T-squares, a tube of paint, paintbrushes, a pen, pencil, charcoal pencil, camera, and razor blade.
Laurel Nakadate stands in a wide field and salutes the camera. She wears a Junior Girl Scout uniform with her sash covered in patches
Villagers in driving wind and rain on a steep hillside.
Watercolor-style map of New York City.
Watercolor style map of Stockholm
Watercolor style map of Honolulu
Etching of the interior of an antique shop, with a man wearing a hat and overcoat examining objects in the back.

Purple and white graphic with text: Our Shared Future Forum. August 26. 7 p.m. ET. Logos for Smithsonian and Bank of America, with text Founding Sponsor. Our Shared Future. Reckoning With Our Racial Past

Poster with central image in black of a woman in profile, walking to the left, with abstract swirls in black, violet, blue and green radiating off her head and back, reminiscent of smoke. What appears to be the train of a dress takes the form of stairs or waves underneath these swirls. Below, text in large black letters: THE WIZ / [in smaller letters:] a new musical version of “The Wonderful Wizard of Oz”/ AT THE WINTER GARDEN / Broadway and 50th Street, N.Y.C.
A print done in drypoint in dark brown ink on paper shows a street corner seen from above in the rain. A single figure and three groups of two are seen with umbrellas raised.

A bobblehead depicting Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg wearing a black judicial robe with references to her opinions on United States v. Virginia and Ledbetter v. Goodyear Tire & Rubber Co.

Justice Ginsburg received this beaded collar as a gift from her law clerks in 2006. She would often wear it when delivering the majority opinion at the Court. The collar includes many small yellow beads surrounding a gold necklace chain.

One of the most unusual tributes to Justice Ginsburg was sent by a fan who shared a photo of a tattoo they had seen. The image demonstrates the late Justice’s pop-culture status, as well as her sense of humor, as she hung this artwork in her chamber’s powder room. The tattoo shows Ginsburg in a black judicial robe with the word "SUPREME."

Quote from Why We Can't Wait: In Connor’s Birmingham, the silent password was fear. It was a fear not only on the part of the black oppressed, but also in the hearts of the white oppressors. . . Certainly Birmingham had its decent white citizens who privately deplored the maltreatment of Negroes. But they remained publicly silent. It was a silence born of fear—fear of social, political and economic reprisals. The ultimate tragedy of Birmingham was not the brutality of the bad people, but the silence of the good people.

Pallas’ cats have the same thick, long fur, flat faces and stocky builds of domestic Persian cats. Their round ears are set low on their heads, so they can peer over rocks while keeping their ears hidden. Their coats range in color from tan to gray to an almost orange-red, sometimes changing with the seasons to help them blend into the landscape. They can have dark stripes, especially on their tails. Many of their hairs have white tips, giving their coats an almost frosted look.

Two Pallas's cats. Pallas’s cats have the same thick, long fur, flat faces and stocky builds of domestic Persian cats. Their round ears are set low on their heads, so they can peer over rocks while keeping their ears hidden. Their coats range in color from tan to gray to an almost orange-red, sometimes changing with the seasons to help them blend into the landscape. They can have dark stripes, especially on their tails. Many of their hairs have white tips, giving their coats an almost frosted look.

The image is shows the Southern Ring Nebula with a black background speckled with tiny bright stars and distant galaxies. The planetary nebula is a misshapen oval that is slightly angled from top left to bottom right and takes up the majority of each image. It shows a bright white star at the center with long diffraction spikes. Large, transparent teal and orange ovals, which are shells ejected by the unseen central star, surround it.

This Hubble image clearly shows two stars near the center of the nebula, a bright white one and an adjacent, fainter companion to its upper right. A third, unrelated star lies near the edge of the nebula. The flood of ultraviolet radiation from the faint star’s surface makes the surrounding gases, radiating out from the stars in an oval, glow through fluorescence. The colors were chosen to represent the temperature of the gases. Blue represents the hottest gas, which is confined to the inner region of the nebula. Red represents the coolest gas, at the outer edge. Also revealed is a host of filaments, including one long one that resembles a waistband, made out of dust particles which have condensed out of the expanding gases.

To gain crucial insight into the black hole's properties and help interpret the EHT image, scientists coordinated observations with 19 of the world's most powerful telescopes on the ground and in space, collecting light from across the spectrum. This is the largest simultaneous observing campaign ever undertaken on a supermassive black hole with jets.

This composite image features the ringed planet Uranus set against the blackness of space. The planet is depicted in blues and pinks, encircled by a near vertical white ring. The blue and white colors represent optical data obtained by the Keck-1 Telescope, and the pink represents X-ray data gathered by NASA's Chandra X-ray Observatory. The blues, which appear as blended, near vertical stripes, range from midnight blue at our right, to teal and even neon sky blue at our left. Across the right half of the planet is a teardrop-shaped patch of neon pink which is more solid near the bottom and somewhat less defined near the top. Several pale blue dots mark the surface of the planet, though none appear in the hot pink patch. The near vertical ring, which is slightly tipped toward our upper-right, is quite thin. It appears white when set against the black background, and pink when it passes in front of the planet's pink patch.
