A semicircle of red and orange clouds frames a pool of less dense clouds in shades of blues and aquas. Jutting outward from the right-hand side of the semicircle is an area of very dense, reddish and orange clouds that resemble the trunk of an elephant. The entire image is bespeckled with stars.

An optical light image of the galaxy which appears similar to a huge splatter of wet, red paint. In the core of the galaxy is a concentration of bright stars of different sizes. These stars light up the red paint structures closest to them in shades of pink, the soft glow resembling pink cotton candy. Below the core of the galaxy are several clouds, also in shades of red, that appear to swoop down in arcs.

This X-ray and infrared light image features a tiny, glowing purple-pink dot in a sea of luminous stars. Untold thousands of points of light, ranging from tiny to minuscule, fill the blackness of space surrounding the purple dot. While most of these stars glow white, some glow red, and others glow golden yellow. A few specks appear to flare with bright white light, giving them a classic star shape. But only the magnetar in the center appears purple. When magnified, its purple color is revealed to be a pale pink circle with an outer ring of darker neon violet light.

This view also features several interstellar clouds, misty shapes of various amounts of transparency. Along the bottom third of the image is a golden cloud that is thicker and more mottled at our lower right. It overlaps a dusty red cloud with a pale pink core. From this perspective, the dusty red cloud sits to the right of the magnetar, extending above the mottled golden cloud. An arrow points to the magnetar, which is lab

This is an optical and infrared image of galaxy N G C 7252 from Hubble. This spiral galaxy appears face-on. The core of the galaxy is a bright, pale yellow, surrounded by spiral arms in lilac shades. Surrounding that region are dark dust lanes that appear to swirl around the central portion of the galaxy. Hazy material extends way beyond the galaxy's round shape in various directions.

This is a composite image containing X-rays detected by Chandra (blue) and radio emission (pink), overlaid on a visible light image from the Digitized Sky Survey of the field of view. Both X-ray and radio emission are present streaming below and to the right of the object. An outflow of material, which is present in X-ray only, streams out from about the 1 o'clock position from the pulsar.

This is an optical view of the Whale Galaxy from Hubble. The core of the galaxy, on the left side of the image, tapers off to the right toward the outer regions where there are fewer stars and less dust, but pockets of star formation are still present. The core is bright with stars that light up the dusty spiral arms in shades of brown, both from behind and within. The tapered outer reaches of the galaxy are mostly blue and white.

This image is an X-ray and optical image of I C 418. The nebula resembles a geode, a rock which reveals concentric layers of colorful crystals when cut open. At I C 418's core is a small bright dot surrounded by a sky-blue glow. Encircling the glow is a thick ring of purple, marbled with faint orange lines. Around that is a ring of bright orange with a fine red outer edge. Many people find this image aesthetically pleasing.

This Hubble image of the nebula is shaped somewhat like a puffy bow tie, with rounded lobes on both sides. Within the nebula, the complex structure suggests that there have been periodic oppositely directed outflows from the central star in different directions during each episode. The nebula is also rich in clouds of dust, some of which form long, dark streaks pointing away from the central star. Blue and blue-green color is concentrated in the center of the nebula, with the nebula's outer sections mostly in shades of red. The colors in the image correspond to material expelled by the star: blue is helium, blue-green is oxygen, and red is nitrogen and hydrogen.

This composite image shows the central regions of the nearby Circinus galaxy. Data from NASA's Chandra X-ray Observatory is shown in blue and data from the Hubble Space telescope is shown in yellow, red, cyan and light blue. The galaxy appears as though it's made of puffy clouds of fire. Blue X-ray emission is concentrated near the center of the galaxy and appears as splotches in various locations in the image.

In this composite image, an arching red shockwave resembling ribbons of red light pushes away from an electric blue star, surrounded by a ghostly green cloud of gas. The star is located at the center of the image. Electric blue color represents the bubble of X-ray emission around the star. 

The shockwave is left of the star, with a curve like an archer's bow, likely formed by matter blowing away from the star's surface and slamming into gas in its path, as the star moves from right to left. Here, infrared data from NASA Spitzer depicts the shockwave as ribbons of light resembling trails made with a fast-moving flashlight on a dark night. The ribbons are streaked red and white near the center, but appear green and white near the tips at the top and bottom.

The same greenish color can be found in the ghostly clouds that streak the entire image. These faint clouds represent the gas in the path of the star's shockwave. In the background, blue and white specks dot the blackness of space.

This is an optical and infrared image of the nebula from Hubble. The nebula is made of thick gray clouds in a shape similar to a mountain. A bright line of light outlines what would be the peak of this mountain shape. White and gold stars are present embedded in the nebula, as well as in the foreground and background of the image.

This is an optical image of the Little Gem Nebula, also known as N G C 6818, taken by the Hubble Space Telescope. The nebula resembles a round opal, in shades of blues, pinks, reds, and aquas. The different shells in the nebula give the appearance of facets, like those that would be present in a cut stone. A tiny white, glowing dot appears in the center of the nebula. This dot is the nebula's central star.

This is a composite image of pulsar I G R J11014 and the surrounding region. A large area of diffuse X-rays, shown in pinkish purple was produced when a massive star exploded as a supernova, leaving behind a debris field, or supernova remnant. Below and to the right of the remnant is a pulsar, displayed as a white dot and a green pulsar wind nebula. To the right of the pulsar is a long trail of material in pinkish purple and green. The pulsar wind nebula, that is, a "wind" of high-energy particles produced by the pulsar, has been swept behind a bow shock created by the pulsar's high speed.
This is a labeled version of the first image in the post. A label showing the pulsar's name and a green arrow pointing to pulsar itself are superimposed on the original image.

This is an image of N49 in X-ray, infrared, and radio light. This remnant looks similar to a drop of water in motion in very bright shades of pink and purple. Filaments running throughout the remnant bring to mind flames raging in a roaring fire.

This X-ray and optical image of the nebula shows a thick ring of dust around a central star in purple and two S-shaped jets, in shades of yellow and red, with a series of knots emerging from the pole regions of the central star.

This is a multiwavelength image of M 106, a spiral galaxy that has two more arms than most spirals. The image is primarily in shades of red, white and blue. X-rays from Chandra X-ray Observatory are blue, radio data from the NSF's Karl Jansky Very Large Array are purple, optical data from Hubble Space Telescope are yellow and blue, and infrared data from Spitzer Space Telescope are red.

This is a composite image of a glowing dot in a blue haze; a quasar powered by a supermassive black hole. The bright glowing quasar, H 1821 +643, is presented as the white dot at the center of the image. The dot is backed by a vertical hot pink stripe, and sits in the middle of a hazy blue cloud. This cloud is a disk of gas spinning around the quasar, observed by NASA's Chandra X-ray Observatory. The quasar and its gas cloud are surrounded by the blackness of space, which houses other glowing white dots, and is speckled with blue, yellow, red and purple. The red represents radio data from N S F's Karl G. Jansky Very Large Array. The white and yellow specks were captured by the PanSTARRS optical telescope on Hawaii. The blue specks represent X-ray data collected by Chandra.

This Hubble image of M91 combines ultraviolet, visible, and infrared wavelengths. Classified as a barred spiral galaxy, the galaxy's bar is quite prominent. The galaxy's spiral arms, which are slightly elongated, are emanating from the ends of the bar and are specked with star clusters in blue and banded with dark dust lanes in shades of brown.

This composite image in X-ray and infrared light features a star-forming region of the Milky Way known as RCW 120. A glowing cloud dominates the image and it resembles an electric-blue smoke ring with a wispy break near our upper right. Throughout this structure, and across this region of space, are thousands of tiny stars in white, pale blue, gold, and hot pink. The pink stars are part of the Chandra X-ray Observatory dataset and are mostly young stars emitting powerful flares, or outbursts. The brightest pink stars have white cores.

This is an image of the Engraved Hourglass Nebula from Hubble's Wide Field and Planetary Camera 2. The nebula has delicate rings that overlap each other in the shape of an hourglass from top to bottom with an intricate pattern of "etchings" in the object's walls. At the very center of the nebula there is a structure that strongly resembles an eyeball, complete with a greenish-blue iris.

This is an X-ray and optical image of galaxy E S O 137-001 from Chandra and Hubble. The galaxy is zooming toward the upper left of this image, in between other galaxies in the Norma cluster. Tattered threads of gas, similar to blue jellyfish-tendrils stream outward behind the galaxy, toward the lower right. These tendrils are gas that has been torn away from the galaxy in a process astronomers call ram pressure stripping. The image is also decorated with hundreds of stars from within the Milky Way. Though not connected in the slightest to the galaxy shown, these stars contribute to a vibrant celestial vista.

This is a composite image of N G C 4051 in optical and ultraviolet light by Hubble Space Telescope. The galaxy's center is mostly white and yellow, bright with light due to a high concentration of stars. Surrounding the bulge in the center are spiral dust lanes in shades of browns and golds. The outer spiral arms are dotted with knots of star formation in shades of pinks and lilacs.

This is an X-ray and optical image of supernova remnant G292.0+1.8. The remnant resembles a ball of swirling, red, purple and blue clouds veined with bright white light. Inside the remnant, near our lower left, is a white dot; a fast-moving pulsar. This pulsar, J1124-5916, is enlarged in an inset found at the lower left hand corner of the main image. In the enlarged inset, a near-horizontal oblong aura surrounding the dot becomes clear.

This is an optical image of the Lobster Nebula by Dean Carr. Detailed clouds in oranges and reds are present throughout the image. Toward the center of the image, blue-green star-forming regions exist inside bubbles and cavities that were created by radiation and material blowing away from the surfaces of massive stars, as well as supernova explosions. The blue-green glow results from the emission of ionized hydrogen gas.

Hundreds to thousands of galaxies are present in this image of the cluster. The galaxies are of many different shapes and sizes. Many of the galaxies are distorted due to gravitational lensing. X-ray light appears as pink or red and is concentrated in the middle of the image from upper left to lower right. Optical light in the image is red, blue, and green.

This Chandra X-ray image of Kepler's Remnant looks like a colorful ball of dryer lint, complete with knots and wads of material. Different colors in the image, ranging from lower to higher energies, are red, yellow, green, blue and purple. The bulk of the central area of the remnant is mostly red and yellow. Greens, blues, and purples appear to outline the edges of the remnant all around, with a concentration toward the left side of the object.

This is a composite image of one galaxy cluster plowing through another, resembling a white ball barreling through misty purple clouds. Together, these galaxy clusters are known as Abell 2146. Both clusters are dotted with bright red and white specks.  

Cluster number one is a vaguely shaped purple cloud slightly above and to our right of center. Cluster number two is positioned slightly down and to our left of center. The second cluster is in the process of plowing through its misty neighbor, therefore the two clouds appear blended. 

Although these hot gas clouds are quite misty, they feature curiously clean edges in some spots. At our lower left, in front of the barreling core, and at our upper right, far behind the core, the edges of the clouds are notably sharper.

This is an optical and infrared image of NGC 5189 from Hubble Space Telescope in shades of mostly blues, golds, reds, and light creams. Most of the nebula is knotty and filamentary in its structure. As a result of the mass-loss process, the planetary nebula has been created with two nested structures, tilted with respect to each other, that expand away from the center in different directions. A bright golden ring twists and tilts through the nebula and is made up of many radial filaments and cometary knots.

A Periodic Table showing the origins of different chemical elements, many of which come from stellar objects and events. There is also an illustration of a human body to the right of the table showing an estimated percent breakdown of the origin of elemental material in people. 73% of which comes from exploding massive stars.

This is a Hubble Space Telescope image of M 74 in of shades of mostly grays, blues, and browns. The galaxy is seen face-on, similar to looking at the eating surface on a dinner plate. The galaxy's spiral arms appear very symmetrical, and they emanate from a central, bright nucleus.

This near-infrared image from the Gemini South telescope shows a lightly clouded region, slightly off-center and to the right in the image, in shades of red, cream, and purple. A still somewhat obscured protostar is the primary light source in the center of the clouded region. The region somewhat resembles the shape of a butterfly with its wings in flight. Other stars and splotches of nebulas speckle the scene.

This is a Hubble image of galaxy E S O 243-49 shown edge-on, similar to looking at the side of a dinner plate. The galaxy's disk is oriented from bottom left to upper right. The galaxy's galactic bulge is roughly centered and has a dark brown line running through it. The line is the galaxy's dark dust lanes viewed from the side. The black hole being discussed is about 1/3 of the way out from the center of the galaxy and about halfway above the top portion of the galactic bulge. It is marked with a green arrow and labeled as black hole E S O 243-49 H L X-1.

An X-ray image of the supernova remnant in shades of mostly red, purple, and white. The remnant is somewhat round in shape with the exception of an area toward the bottom of the image where material extends outside of the circular shape. The intricate shapes within the remnant almost make it look like a plasma ball filled with electrical current. A long white line runs from left to right across the center of the remnant. This is called an equatorial belt.

This image of N G C 3081 shows a nearly face-on galaxy in a combination of ultraviolet, optical, and infrared light. The center of the galaxy has a well-defined oval shape with a prominent bar. Moving outward there is an area of mostly dust lanes which are surrounded still, farther out, by a ring thick with stars.

This is a close-up, optical image of N G C 2903 from Hubble in shades of mostly brown and beige. A bright bar of light extends outward in opposite directions from the bright orb of light at the center of the galaxy. Spiral arms and dark dust lanes extending from the bright orb give a sense of motion that the galaxy is rotating counter-clockwise. Purple knots of stars are scattered throughout the image, with a higher concentration of these knots toward the outer edges of the image.

This image of supernova remnant N 103 B and the surrounding region is a combination of X-ray light from Chandra and optical light from Hubble. The majority of the remnant is toward the left side of the image and it resembles a cloud ball in colors of mostly pinks, greens, and reds. On the right side of the image, matter is present that resembles ribbons made of reddish smoke. There are stars of different sizes all over the image.

An image of Sagittarius A star captured by the Event Horizon Telescope. It features a bright, orange ring with three golden yellow spots and a red aura, set against a black background. The ring is created by light bending in the intense gravity around the black hole at the center, which has a mass some 4 million times greater than that of our Sun. Superimposed is promotional information about today's Twitter Q and A from 2pm to 3pm eastern time.

A composite image of the supermassive black hole at the center of our Milky Way galaxy. Pointing to the middle of the main image is an inset image of the region around the "event horizon," the boundary of the black hole from which nothing can escape. 

In the main image, golden orange specks of light and tendrils of neon purple and blue clouds are set against a black background. The oranges and purples were captured in infrared light by NASA's Hubble Space Telescope. The blues represent data from NASA's Chandra X-ray Observatory. At the heart of the main image are several bright white dots, including one that contains the supermassive black hole at the center of our galaxy, known as Sagittarius A*. 

Emerging from this bright white dot is an inset image, housed at our upper right. This image is from the Event Horizon Telescope. It shows a bright, orange ring with three golden yellow spots and a red aura... More at: https://chandra.si.edu/photo/2022/sgra/

This is an infrared image of W 40, or Westerhout 40, from NASA's Spitzer Space Telescope. The nebula resembles the shape of a butterfly rotated on its side in shades of reds and pinks. Slightly off center toward the top of the image is where the body of the butterfly would be. This is where about 500 stars are clustered together. It is also the lightest and brightest part of the image. The entire image is dotted with stars that are farther apart than those in the cluster.
A screen shot of the sonification playlist on Chandra's YouTube Channel. The playlist contains 55 videos.

The top half of this image is a NASA image of Earth from space. The bottom half of this image shows a several marbles. A single marble in the center is more in focus than the others and is somewhat separate from the group. Lines extend from the sides of the single marble to the sides of image of Earth.

This is an image of Cygnus A in X-ray, optical, and radio light. A giant blue, elliptical bubble of gas (X-rays) surrounds a bright white X-ray source. Jets shooting outward from both the left and right of the bubble are seen in radio (red) and they extend more than 300,000 light years in each direction.

This Chandra X-ray image shows the center of 3C58, which contains a rapidly spinning neutron star, a pulsar, surrounded by a thick ring, or torus, of X-ray emission. The pulsar appears as a bright white object in the center, and the loops and swirls nearby, in hues of blues and reds, resemble an octopus and its arms.

This is an infrared and visible-light image of M96 from Hubble. The spiral galaxy is face-on in the image. The galaxy's dust and gas is unevenly spread throughout weak spiral arms, and its core is not quite in the center of the galaxy.

This is an optical image from E S O's Very Large Telescope. The center of the nebula looks like a marquise cut diamond in shape with a bright point of light in the middle. Surrounding the center of the nebula are several clouds of material in colors of greens, muted pinks, and browns. A red jet extends outward from both the upper left and lower right of the nebula.

An image of a section of the Lagoon Nebula in optical light from Hubble. Complex, highly detailed clouds of material are present throughout the image, mostly in shades of red, orange, aqua, and yellow. A large, somewhat hidden, ball of white light lurks behind the cloud-like structures in the middle of the image. This is the giant star Herschel 36. Other, much smaller stars pepper the image, and are present as white dots.

This image is an illustration of Chandra's orbit around Earth from "NASA's Eyes" solar system interactive. On the left side of the image, various Earth statistics are given, such as length of year, distance from Sun, and number of moons. Visit NASA's Eyes for more at: https://eyes.nasa.gov/

This image shows four images, arranged in a grid pattern, of star-packed galaxies N G C 1385, 1566, 3344, and 6503. All four composite images contain X-ray data from Chandra, and optical images from NASA's Hubble Space Telescope. They each feature scores of tiny glowing specks, and clouds of gas and dust in faint blues and purples. And all four galaxies have a swirling, spiraling quality.

This image is a combination of X-ray light from Chandra and optical light from Hubble. Hundreds to thousands of galaxies of different shapes and sizes are present over the entire image. X-ray light, appearing as a mist-like blue light in the image, is concentrated in the middle and toward the upper right. This coincides with the more densely concentrated regions of galaxies in the image.

This aesthetically pleasing X-ray and optical image of N G C 281 contains a dense cluster of pink stars in the center. The entire image is thick with stars in shades of pinks and greens. Large columns of gas and dust are present on the left side of the image. Wispy gas pervades the image, also in shades of pinks and greens.

This optical image from Hubble shows a large spiral galaxy, N G C 7753, and a much smaller galaxy, N G C 7752, as the main focus of the image. One of the large galaxy's spiral arms is stretched downward, touching the smaller galaxy. This is a hallmark of gravitational interaction. Many other galaxies and stars, which appear much smaller than N G C 7752, are present in the image.

This infrared image shows nebula D G 129 on the left and the star system Pi Scorpii on the right. The shape of the nebula is similar to a bouquet of flowers in wispy shades of greens, aquas, and pinks. Pi Scorpii is a white area that is surrounded by a thin layer of pink. A greenish haze then surrounds the pink.

This X-ray and optical image shows the star, B P  P s c, as a bright point in roughly the center of the image. A jet, resembling green smoke, extends outward from the star in opposite directions. Other X-ray sources present in the image are shown as pink. The entire image is speckled throughout with stars that appear as white dots.

An optical and infrared photo of spiral galaxy M90. In this image, the galaxy's disk is shown at an angle from upper left to lower right. The center of the galaxy has a bright galactic bulge. There are dark dust lanes that accent the galaxy's spiral arms. The outer reaches of the galaxy resemble gray smoke in a similar spiral pattern.

This is an optical image from E S O's La Silla Observatory. A cloud in shades of reds and pinks is present on the left side of the image. This cloud has many finger-like structures inside of it. Wisps of dark dust are in front of the nebula, dividing it roughly into thirds. A little to the right, the cloud becomes more diffuse, in shades of blues and grays. A couple of foreground stars are shown in the image, including a very bright one at lower right. A starfield pervades the entire image.
A photo of an entire baseball field in a stadium. The photo was taken from the stands behind home base.
A mostly blacked-out photo showing a small sliver of a baseball field.

A multiwavelength image showing the Centaurus A galaxy and the surrounding area. A prominent X-ray jet extending for 13,000 light years points to the upper left in the image, with a shorter "counterjet" aimed in the opposite direction. Knot-like features in the jets detected in the Chandra image show where the acceleration of particles to high energies is currently occurring. The inner part of the X-ray jet close to the black hole is dominated by these knots of X-ray emission, which probably come from shock waves (akin to sonic booms) caused by the jet. Farther from the black hole there is more diffuse X-ray emission in the jet. Hundreds of point-like sources are also seen in the Chandra image. Many of these are X-ray binaries that contain a stellar-mass black hole and a companion star in orbit around one another.

An X-ray and optical image of supernova remnant R C W 103. The remnant shows a mixture of colors in shades of mostly blues, reds, and greens. The remnant is not quite spherical. The texture of the remnant looks a bit like lumpy mashed potatoes. In the center of the remnant is a very pronounced white-blue dot. This dot is the neutron star. A dense star field is present throughout the image.
The same image as the first image from this post without the inset. 14 yellow circles dot the image. These circles label the 14 supermassive black holes found by Chandra.

A composite image of specks of light in the blackness of space, as well as a separate enlarged inset. This is a protocluster, a collection of galaxies and gas that will eventually evolve into a galaxy cluster.

The specks of light are evenly distributed across the main image. Some are tiny pinpricks, while others register as large dots with glowing auras. These specks and dots, galaxies and black holes, glow in a variety of colors. Red, green, and white specks appear courtesy of the Subaru optical telescope in Hawaii. Purple specks were captured by NASA's Chandra X-ray Observatory.

In the center of the image is a mid-sized, light purple dot surrounded by a hazy purple cloud. This is the center of the protocluster enlarged in the accompanying inset. In the enlargement, it becomes evident that the primary purple dot is accompanied by a slightly smaller purple dot, above and to our right. At the center of the smaller purple dot is a golden light resembling a wire filament in a light bulb

This optical light image shows a wispy nebula in shades of blue and red. The nebula extends from the lower left toward the upper right of the image. Just above, but attached to the pencil-shaped structure is a less dense section of nebula. The filaments of this part of the nebula are filled with voids, somewhat resembling tripe. There are stars of different sizes across the entire image.

An optical image of spiral galaxy NGC 4790 is on the left, labeled with a small square near the center of the image. The square pulls out to two optical images on the right. The top image shows the region in 2001 without an object. The bottom image shows the region in 2013. The image has a bright dot, showing a supernova present in the center.

This is a composite image of Abell 1689, combining X-ray light from Chandra and optical light from Hubble. Thousands and thousands of galaxies are present in the image in tones of yellows and golds. Hundred-million-degree gas detected by NASA's Chandra X-ray Observatory is shown as a purple haze. The long arcs in the optical image are caused by gravitational lensing of background galaxies by matter in the galaxy cluster, the largest system of such arcs ever found.

This galaxy is shaped like a pinwheel. The center has a high concentration of stars, making it appear like there is a yellow-white orb at the source. The sweeping arms of the galaxy are dotted with blue and pink stars. This is an optical and infrared image from E S O's Very Large Telescope.

This optical image is filled with clouds of different shapes and illumination levels. This is a colorful region of space in shades of reds, blues, and browns, as huge stars light up nearby nebula regions.

This supernova remnant resembles a pink soap bubble filled with gases in hues of green and blue. The outer edge of the bubble is more defined than the rest of the bubble. This definition is the outer blast wave. It was created during the destruction of the white dwarf star. The remnant is surrounded by a field of stars, both in the foreground and background of the image.

This is an optical image of the Crab Nebula from Hubble. It shows a whirlpool-like structure nestled in clouds of greens and golds. About halfway through the right side of the whirlpool structure, a faint streak bisects the image in the shape of an arc from lower left to upper right. The streak is the trail of an asteroid. The streak is labeled with arrows pointing toward it.

This optical image from Hubble contains a face-on spiral galaxy on the right and an irregular galaxy on the left connected by a bridge of stars and other material. Dark dust lanes are present in both galaxies. Further to the left is a galaxy in the background that is not part of the interaction.

This is a composite image of an indigo beam of matter and antimatter cutting through red clouds of gas, as well as a close-up of the pulsar from which it originates. 

In the primary image, the long indigo beam begins at our upper left and exits the image at our lower right. This is approximately one third of the beam's actual length. The beam appears thin and consists of many distinct dots, like a string of indigo beads. It travels through brick orange clouds of gas past many specks of orange, red, white, and purple light. 

At the upper left is the source of the beam, the pulsar known as J2030. In the primary image, it resembles a stout, white, vertical line with a purple aura. In the close-up, the spinning pulsar resembles a snowman made with glowing indigo rings. The bottom ring is largest and darkest. The middle ring is slightly smaller and lighter in color. The top section is a solid white oval white oval with an indigo blue aura.

This composite image of N49 shows X-rays from Chandra in blue, infrared light from Spitzer in red, and optical light from Hubble in white & yellow. The remnant is wispy and asymmetrical. Its shape is similar to a chocolate drop candy that has been slightly warped by heat.

In this composite image of NGC 3115, Chandra data are shown in blue and optical data are colored gold. Many point sources in the center of the galaxy are mostly binary stars containing gas that is being pulled from a star to a stellar-mass black hole or a neutron star. An inset features the central portion of the Chandra image, with the black hole located in the middle. No point source is seen at the position of the black hole, but instead a plateau of X-ray emission coming from both hot gas and the combined X-ray emission from unresolved binary stars is found.

A nebula filled with stars of different sizes. Loops of materials arch upward from a bright concentration of stars and X-ray light. Diffuse X-ray data detected by Chandra are blue and optical data from ESO are shown in orange and yellow.

An illustration of a vertically-oriented, oval debris field with a swirling disk at its core, and blue arcs hovering above and below at either end. This is an artist's conception of the aftermath of a "kilonova", a powerful event that happens when two neutron stars merge. 

The swirling disk at the core of the illustration has a glowing white light at its center. This represents gas falling onto a black hole that formed after two neutron stars merged. This merger is called GW170817. The disk sits at the core of the oval debris field like a small yoke floating inside an egg. As the neutron stars merge, the debris generates visible and infrared light from the decay of radioactive elements. In the artist's conception, this debris field glows like a mottled, electric, orange and red marble.

Hovering above and below the ends of the oval debris field are glowing blue arcs. (See release for full visual description.)

This mulitwavelength image has many background galaxies present. In the foreground are two radio structures in blue. The radio structure on the left provides an example of "pareidolia," a psychological phenomenon where familiar shapes and patterns are seen in otherwise random data. In Abell 1033, the structures in the data create an uncanny resemblance to many of the depictions of the fictional Starship Enterprise from Star Trek.

This nebula resembles a fluffy marshmallow wrapped in translucent, icy blue leaves, backed by the head of a pale blue rose. The translucent leaves have feathery edges and are streaked with hot pink ripples. Several bright stars dot the black sky in the background. The image contains X-ray light from Chandra and optical light from Hubble.

A wide-field image of the region around supernova remnant G306.3-0.9. The remnant appears as a small object in the lower left-hand corner of the image. The image is about 1 degree across, which corresponds to about 450 light years at the remnant's estimated distance.
A colorful cloud filled with bright knots. X-rays from Chandra are blue, infrared data from Spitzer is red, and radio observations from the Australia Telescope Compact Array are pinkish-purple.

This image of the supernova Cassiopeia A combines some of the first X-ray data collected by NASA's Imaging X-ray Polarimetry Explorer, shown in magenta, with high-energy X-ray data from NASA's Chandra X-ray Observatory, in blue. The saturation of the magenta color corresponds to the intensity of X-ray light observed by IXPE. It overlays high energy X-ray data, shown in blue, from NASA’s Chandra X-ray Observatory. Chandra and IXPE, with different kinds of detectors, capture different levels of angular resolution, or sharpness.

A pixelated neon pink stream extends toward our upper right like a vapor trail from an airplane. At the front of the stream, near our middle left, is a bright white dot. All around are pale blue clouds and blue and white specks of light. The white dot is a pulsar, and the pink stream is a jet captured by Chandra. Also originating from the pulsar is a faint blue shape observed in optical light. Pointing toward our lower right, the distinctive guitar shape is somewhat hidden in the surrounding blue clouds. This is a nebula with a long thin neck and a curvy, widening body, which rightly earns it the nickname the "Guitar Nebula".
A star with elongated refraction spikes glows just above the middle of the image and just above spiral galaxy UGC 3855.
This image of Abell 2744 contains thousands of galaxies. Cloud-like structures of red and blue are concentrated toward the center of the image.

Each member of this interacting pair of spiral galaxies is somewhat distorted. Long tidal tails sweep out from the two galaxies made from gas and stars that were stripped out and torn away from the outer regions of the galaxies. The presence of these tails is the unique signature of an interaction.

NGC 7662: This nebula resembles a tie-dyed blue and purple bean in a mossy green and orange cloud. At the center of the image is a pixilated white dot, the nebula's white dwarf. The bean shape around it is filled with blobs of sky blue and purple with lime green near the outer edges. The mossy green cloud that surrounds the bean shape is marked by smears and flecks of neon orange, as if dabbed with an artist's saturated brush.

R Aquarii: This image resembles a sparse brick-orange cloud in the shape of a cross, with a flash of white light at its core. The white light is ringed by faint concentric circles which resemble ripples from a raindrop in still water. Along the horizontal arms of the cross shape is a wavy string of purple clouds. These connect with the white core at the center. This image depicts R Aquarii, a pair of stars that orbit one another, inside a cloud of gas. The bright light at the core is a white dwarf star with a relatively cool temperature, pulling material from a red giant star. The string of purple clouds is a jet of material shooting from the resulting explosion, observed by Chandra. The brick-orange cloud, observed by the Hubble Space Telescope, is evidence of much older explosions and jets.

The Medusa Nebula: A star present in the core of this nebula shed its outer layers into space and formed a colorful cloud of mostly reds, golds, greens, and blues. The "snakes" referenced in this nebula are serpentine filaments of glowing gas. The red glow from hydrogen and the fainter green emission from oxygen gas extends well beyond this frame, forming a crescent shape in the sky.

M66 has many star-forming regions throughout its spiral arms. The galaxy's bright core is filled with stars and appears to be off-center when compared to the galaxy's arms. This Hubble image shows M66 in optical and infrared wavelengths.

Sharpless 2-106: The outstretched "wings" of the nebula record the contrasting imprint of heat and motion against the backdrop of a colder medium. Twin lobes of super-hot gas, glowing blue in this image, stretch outward from the central star. This hot gas creates the "wing" shapes. A ring of dust and gas orbiting a massive star acts like a belt, cinching the expanding nebula into an hourglass shape.

This wide field image of 47 Tucanae shows a dense concentration of stars toward the middle of the cluster and more widely-dispersed stars out to the edges of the image. Image Credit: Jose Mtanous (CC-BY-3.0)
This close-up Hubble image of 47 Tucanae shows a dense concentration of stars toward the middle of the cluster.

This composite image of Abell 1758 shows the effect of a collision between two small galaxy clusters. Chandra X-ray data (blue) reveals hot gas in the cluster and data from the Giant Metrewave Radio Telescope (GMRT) in India (pink) shows huge "halos" generated by ultra-relativistic particles and magnetic fields over vast scales. Optical data from the Digitized Sky Survey are colored gold.
An artist's illustration of the two black holes at the core of OJ 287.

An infographic showing the sizes of the two black holes at the core of OJ 287 relative to the size of our solar system. For larger versions of this graphic, visit the Spitzer Space Telescope website at: https://bit.ly/33Ca4Kv
Galaxy M94 (Messier 94) is a face-on spiral galaxy. A ring of starbirth encircles dark dust lanes which swirl around the galaxy's bright core.

This nebula resembles a butterfly with ethereal electric teal wings set against a star-packed sky. The wings, which are gas structures expelled by a white dwarf star, extend toward our upper right and lower left. Near the outer edges they are translucent, gauzy, and teal-colored. Near the center the wings appear more solid and white and have a shimmering quality similar to mother of pearl.
A mostly round nebula in shades of green and blue that isolate the light emitted by oxygen atoms. A central star is prominent in the center of the image.

This image of the spiral galaxy NGC 3344 is a composite of Hubble images taken through seven different filters. They cover wavelengths from the ultraviolet to the optical and the near-infrared. This spiral galaxy is viewed face-on, showcasing the galaxy's arms and bright core.

An image of the front and back covers of the Chandra 2022 wall calendar. On the left, the front cover is an image of the center of our Milky Way Galaxy in X-ray and radio light, along with the superimposed text, NASA's Chandra X-ray Observatory 2022." On the right side of the graphic are the 12 monthly images shown in the calendar. Larger image versions and captions are available at the link in this post.

This is an optical image of a galaxy group inset with an X-ray close-up of a dwarf galaxy, all backed by black space dotted with specks of light. The center of the galaxy group HCG068 appears on our left side of this horizontal graphic near several bright stars. The most prominent members are four distinct, labeled galaxies. NGC 5355 is a glowing silver speck. 5350 is a silver galaxy with spiralling radial arms. And 5353 and 5354 are two galaxies in a golden haze, which together resemble an apostrophe or comma. At our lower right is a glowing white dot labeled Mrk 462. This is the dwarf galaxy. Above it is an X-ray enlargement, presented in an outlined square. Here, Mrk 462 resembles a large, hazy neon pink circle. The X-rays emitted by this relatively small galaxy reveal the presence of a supermassive black hole about 200,000 times the mass of our Sun.

Newborn stars, hidden behind thick dust, appear as pink and red specks toward the center of this infrared image. The stars appear to have formed in regularly spaced intervals along linear structures in a configuration that resembles the spokes of a wheel or the pattern of a snowflake.

This infographic shows the electromagnetic spectrum, spanning a broad spectrum from very long radio waves to very short gamma rays. The graphic depicts the different types of waves, the wavelengths of light, as well as what types of light can pass through Earth's atmosphere. For more information, including a larger version of this graphic, visit: https://science.nasa.gov/ems/01_intro

This is a composite image of X-ray and optical light with dark matter (derived mass) mapped out in blue. Because dark matter doesn't emit any radiation, astronomers instead precisely measure how its gravity warps the images of far background galaxies like a funhouse mirror. This allows them to come up with a mass estimate for the cluster. Chandra's X-ray data are shown in pink and these have been overlaid on optical data from Hubble that shows the individual galaxies in the cluster as well as stars in the field of view.

Stars in blue, red, and yellow are present throughout a wispy nebula that contains a few huge cavities. X-rays from NASA's Chandra X-ray Observatory (blue) show hot regions created by winds and shocks, while infrared data from NASA's Spitzer Space Telescope (red) outline where the dust and cooler gas are found. The optical light from the 2.2m Max-Planck-ESO telescope (yellow) in Chile shows where ultraviolet radiation from hot, young stars is causing gas in the nebula to glow.

A mostly round reddish cloud with a cluster of other colors in the lower, right-hand quadrant. Chandra data (yellow, green and bright red) show multimillion-degree gas and Hubble optical data show cooler gas in the system, near the outer border of the remnant in red.
A mostly spherical supernova remnant filled with knots of material.  Low, medium, and higher-energy X-rays are colored red, green, and blue respectively in this X-ray image from Chandra.

Two images of the same galaxy cluster, RBS 797, presented side-by-side. Left is an optical image from NASA’s Hubble Space Telescope. Right is an X-ray image from the Chandra X-ray Observatory. The optical image on features short streaks of golden light and golden stars of varying sizes set against a black background. While many of the stars resemble small roundish specks, others feature shafts of light bursting from brilliant, round cores. At the center of the image is a small fuzzy oval, surrounded by a glowing ring and a patch of golden haze. This is the large galaxy in the center of RBS 797. The X-ray image does not show the clustered galaxies, rather the hot gas that envelopes them. The image is royal blue in color, and somewhat mottled or cloudy. At the center is a pair of irregular black ovals, ringed with white and pale blue. These side-by-side shapes are X-ray cavities, thought to be a byproduct of eruptions from a giant black hole at the center of the cluster.

This image contains 3 separate images of the galaxy taken on January 6th, January 12th, and February 10th, 2008. In the first image, no supernova is present. In the second image, a white dot-like source (the supernova) is present in the top, right-hand side of the galaxy. In the 3rd image, the white dot-like source appears to have grown in size and is more orange in coloration.
Wispy clouds of gas and dust in shades of purple and dark pink surround the bluish star AE Aurigae. Many other stars are also present in the image.
This X-ray and optical image of galaxy cluster JKCS041 show the distant group bathed in a halo of blue X-ray light. Several other galaxies are present in the image foreground.

A collection of images of six planetary nebulas. The shapes and colors of each nebula are all different from each other. These composite images have been arranged in a grid, three across and two down, to create the primary visual of this release.  

These composite images have been arranged in a grid, three across and two down, to create the primary visual of this release.  

At our upper left of the grid is NGC 6302. This nebula resembles a butterfly with ethereal electric teal wings set against a star-packed sky. The wings, which are gas structures expelled by a white dwarf star, extend toward our upper right and lower left. Near the outer edges they are translucent, gauzy, and teal-colored. Near the center the wings appear more solid and white and have a shimmering quality similar to mother of pearl.

Further description at: https://chandra.si.edu/photo/2021/pne/pne_description.txt
Mz3 is composed of a bright core and four distinct high-velocity outflows called lobes. It is often referred to as the Ant Nebula because it resembles the head and thorax of an ant.

The greenish nebula is roughly circular with a faint internal structure of three concentric shells. The owl-like appearance of the nebula is the result of an inner shell that look like owl eyes/face to some.
A simple drawing of the nebula by William Parsons, Ireland's 3rd Earl of Rosse, that shows the nebula's face-like structure.
This image of the Chandra Deep Field-South contains thousands of "dots" in shades of red, green, and blue. Most of the sources in this image are black holes.

Two galactic cores in shades of browns and tans are located in the center of the image and they are surrounded by a ring of blue stars. Interactions have pulled and stretched the galaxies' disks of gas, dust, and stars outward. This action formed the ring of intense star formation around the galaxies.

An X-ray inset within an illustration. The artist's illustration shows a white dwarf as the blue-white sphere near the center. The object in orbit around the white dwarf — either a very low mass star or a planet — is depicted in the illustration by a brown and red object on the right-hand side. The white dwarf pulls the material from the companion into a disk around itself, which the artist shows in orange, before it slams into its north and south poles.

A multiwavelength image of the Helix Nebula with its white dwarf star present in the center of the image. X-rays are purple; Ultraviolet is light blue; Optical is red, green, and blue; Infrared is aqua and red.

This nebula is roughly spherical in shape with an inner ring of X-ray light (blue) surrounded by an outer ring shown in optical/IR in reddish-orange. The dying star is slightly to the right of center in this image, located in the blue region.

Multimillion-degree gas detected in X-rays (blue) by the Chandra X-ray Observatory comes from shock fronts — similar to sonic booms — formed by stellar winds and by supernova explosions. This hot gas carves out gigantic bubbles in the surrounding cooler gas and dust shown here in infrared emission from the Spitzer Space Telescope (orange/red).

Hundreds to thousands of galaxies are present in this composite image of cluster A1795. Chandra X-ray Observatory data is in blue and optical data from the Canada-France-Hawaii Telescope is in red, green and blue.
A wispy cloud in shades of dark browns and grays amidst a field of stars. The orange star, T Tauri, brightly illuminates part of the nebula nearby.

The jet of outflowing material, pointing from the middle to the upper left, is generated by the black hole at the galaxy's center. This high-energy snapshot of Centaurus A also highlights a dust lane that wraps around the waist of the galaxy.

An eye-catching spiral galaxy in the image shows a very pronounced, curling tail. The companion galaxy, located to the bottom-right of the image, displays an intricate structure, including a number of trails that extend quite far out from its core. A large, bright star appears between the two galaxies.
This wide-field optical view of IC 443 shows a spectacular filamentary structure in a nebula of golds, greens, and browns.

A composite of X-ray data from Chandra revealing hot gas in the cluster in purple and optical data from the Hubble Space Telescope showing many galaxies in yellow. The cluster is very bright in X-rays implying that it is extremely massive.

NGC 922 was formed by the collision between two galaxies. One of these galaxies is shown in this composite image with X-rays from Chandra (red) and optical data from Hubble (appearing as pink, blue, and yellow). The galaxy is dotted with bright sources throughout.

The left panel of this graphic shows M51 in X-rays from Chandra (purple and blue) and optical light from NASA's Hubble Space Telescope (red, green, and blue). A box marks the location of the possible planet candidate, an X-ray binary known as M51-ULS-1. An artist's illustration in the right panel depicts the X-ray binary and possible planet. Material from the companion star (white and blue in illustration) is pulled onto the neutron star or black hole, forming a disk around the dense object (illustrated as red and orange). The material near the dense object becomes superheated, causing it to glow in X-ray light (white). The planet is shown beginning to pass in front of this source of X-rays.
A roughly apple-shaped nebula in shades of mostly green, red, and yellow filed with knots of gas & dust.
A dark cloud of gas & dust illuminated in the center in shades of blue by starlight.

NGC 3081 is nearly face-on in this combination of ultraviolet, optical, and infrared light. The center of the galaxy is a well-defined oval shape with a prominent bar. Moving outward there is an area of mostly dust lanes which are surrounded farther out by a ring thick with stars.

This composite image of the barred spiral Andromeda Galaxy (M31) shows Chandra X-ray data in gold, optical data from the Digitized Sky Survey in light blue and infrared data from the Spitzer Space Telescope in red.
A small nebula inside a larger circular nebula in shades of primarily purple and orange. The central star illuminates a bright region in the center of the image.
This intermediate spiral galaxy stretches from the lower left to upper right of the image. Spiral dust lanes are prominent along with clusters of thousands of red and blue stars.
This composite image shows the mostly-round supernova remnant G344.7-0.1 through the eyes of different telescopes. X-rays are in blue, infrared data are yellow and green, and radio data are in red.
A wispy nebula is shown with many background & foreground stars. X-rays are shown in blue, radio data are shown in pink, and visible light data are shown in yellow.

NGC 7027 is a rectangular-shaped nebula with an elliptical region of ionized gas within. A central white dwarf star is present in the middle of the nebula. This composite image shows X-ray light in blue and optical light in red and green.

Galaxy NGC 7424 is multi-armed galaxy seen almost directly face-on in this image. A prominent bar in the middle is reddish in color, indicating an older population of stars. The bright blue color of the loose arms indicates the presence of clusters of young and massive stars.

This labeled illustration shows our Milky Way Galaxy in relation to two of the larger galaxies in the Local Group of galaxies — Triangulum Galaxy and Andromeda Galaxy. Smaller unlabeled galaxies are also illustrated.

The pulsar is shown in X-rays by Chandra and XMM-Newton as well as in radio data and appears as the brightest white source in the image. A large red circle-like area shows radio emission from the blast wave. The image also contains infrared data from the 2MASS survey that show the stars in the field.
An image of a hand-like structure in gold (X-ray light), surrounded by a cloud-like structure in shades of red, blue, and purple (infrared light).

The Lindsay-Shapley Ring galaxy has a sparkling blue ring of stars (horizontal oval shaped) around the yellowish nucleus of what was once another galaxy. Some have said the object resembles the appearance of a fried egg, complete with yolk.
A spiral galaxy with wispy arms that has many regions of star formation in shades of pink and red.
This image shows NGC 7009 in pinks, blues, and greens. The complex nebula features a halo, jet-like streams, multiple shells, ansae ("handles"), filaments, and knots.

This image of the "Pillars of Creation" combines X-ray data from NASA's Chandra X-ray Observatory and Hubble Space Telescope optical data. The optical image, taken with filters to emphasize the interstellar gas and dust, shows dusty brown nebulae immersed in a blue-green haze, and a few stars that appear as pink dots in the image. The Chandra data reveal X-rays from hot outer atmospheres from stars. In this image, low, medium, and high-energy X-rays detected by Chandra have been colored red, green, and blue.

This is an X-ray and optical image of SNR E0519-69.0. The remnant is slightly out of round, mostly on the right hand side of the orb. Multimillion degree gas is seen in X-rays from Chandra (blue). The outer edge of the explosion (red) and stars in the field of view are seen in visible light from Hubble.

This image of Markarian 573 shows two cones of emission streaming away from the supermassive black hole at its center. The composite image shows overlap between X-rays from Chandra (blue), radio emission from the VLA (purple), and optical data from Hubble (gold).
This image is a wide-field view of the Puppis A supernova remnant.
This image is a wide-field view of the Puppis A supernova remnant along with an arrow and label pointing to the neutron star: RX J0822-4300.

This is an image of galaxy NGC 6118. It is a disk-shaped galaxy with several rather loosely wound spiral arms that spiral out directly from the nucleus. These arms show large numbers of active star-forming regions.

An artist's illustration in the main part of this graphic shows how the paths of light from distant objects are bent and amplified by a galaxy along the line of sight between Earth and the objects. The X-ray light from one of the objects on the left (purple) has been warped by the gravity of the intervening galaxy to produce two beams and X-ray sources ("A" and "B" in the labeled version) detected in the Chandra image, which is represented by the dashed square on the right. The X-ray light from the fainter object (blue) produces an X-ray source ("C") that has been amplified by the galaxy to be as much as 300 times brighter than it would have been without the lensing. The Chandra image is shown in the inset.
An image of supernova remnant G292.0+1.8 in X-ray light. The image is somewhat spherical and contains different colors (chemical elements) woven throughout the object.

This multiwavelength image of galaxy 4C+29.30 contains X-ray data from NASA's Chandra X-ray Observatory (blue), optical light obtained with the Hubble Space Telescope (gold) and radio waves from the NSF's Very Large Array (pink).

Pluto nearly fills the frame in this image from the Long Range Reconnaissance Imager (LORRI) aboard NASA's New Horizons spacecraft, taken on July 13, 2015 when the spacecraft was 476,000 miles (768,000 kilometers) from the surface. This view is dominated by the large, bright feature informally named the "heart," which measures approximately 1,000 miles (1,600 kilometers) across. The heart borders darker equatorial terrains, and the mottled terrain to its east (right) are complex. However, even at this resolution, much of the heart's interior appears remarkably featureless.

An X-ray and optical image of a group of galaxies called NGC 5813 showing distinct cavities in the hot gas (shown in purple) surrounding a central, supermassive black hole which is too small to be identified in this image.
This image is the same as the first image in this post with the addition of yellow labels identifying six cavities.
A radio image of the Pinwheel Galaxy, M33. The rainbow of colors shown in this image is due to the rotation of the galaxy, which Doppler-shifts the radio light.
Image of N49 in X-ray and optical light. The bullet-shaped object seen in X-rays in the lower right of the image is traveling away from a bright point source in the upper left part of N49.
Puppis A is seen as a red dusty cloud that resembles the shape of a rose in this image from NASA's Wide-field Infrared Survey Explorer, or WISE. Puppis A is the remnant of a supernova explosion.
This image of the Sun in shades of blue was taken in ultraviolet light by the Extreme-ultraviolet Imaging Telescope (EIT) on board the Solar and Heliospheric Observatory (SOHO) spacecraft.

An image of the slightly oblong planetary nebula NGC 3132. This Hubble image shows two stars near the center of the nebula, a bright white one, and an adjacent, fainter companion to its upper right. (A third, unrelated star lies near the edge of the nebula.) The faint partner is actually the star that has ejected the nebula. Colors represent the temperature of the gases. Blue represents the hottest gas, which is confined to the inner region of the nebula. Red represents the coolest gas, at the outer edge.

This composite image of DEM L316 contains X-ray data in blue, optical data in red, and radio data in green. This cat-shaped image is produced by the remnants of two exploded stars in the Large Magellanic Cloud.

The image shows NGC 6826 in X-ray and optical light. The nebula has a white dwarf at its center that's surrounded by an oblong orb of gas and dust. A fainter cloud of material surrounds the orb and that cloud is flanked on both sides by bursts of orange-red gas called FLIERS, or fast low-ionization emission regions.

This composite image features a series of incomplete concentric rings in a black field dotted with gleaming white, yellow, and golden stars.
 
Here, the X-rays are rendered as hazy neon blue rings. The smallest, near the center, is the brightest and the most substantial. The remaining concentric rings are somewhat wispier, but are much larger, and extend beyond the edges of the image. These rings are not clearly defined like the clean ridges on a record album. Instead, they appear vague and blurred, resembling curving tire marks left in wet snow. 

The rings are incomplete, with gaps at our upper right, and upper left. A string of gaps appear in a horizontal line across the middle of the image, as if portions of the neon blue X-ray rings were removed with a straight swipe of an eraser. These gaps show the edges of Chandra's field of view during the observations, or the sections of the field Chandra did not observe.

This image of Chandra Deep Field-South contains many dots of color scattered on a the mostly black background of space. The colors in this image represent different levels of X-ray energy detected by Chandra. The lowest-energy X-rays are red, the medium band is green, and the highest-energy X-rays observed by Chandra are blue. Roughly 70% of the colored dots in this image are supermassive black holes.
An image of face-on spiral galaxy NGC 6814. The galaxy has a bright nucleus and its sweeping arms are rippled with an intricate pattern of dark dust in this Hubble Space Telescope image.

This image of M81 is a composite of X-ray (purple), optical (cyan / gold), and infrared (red) data. The galaxy's spiral arms wind all the way down into its bright nucleus and the galaxy is thick with stars throughout.

Stars and dust lanes are revealed in this Hubble Space Telescope image of NGC 2841. A bright cusp of starlight marks the galaxy's center. Spiraling outward are dust lanes that are silhouetted against the population of whitish middle-aged stars. Much younger blue stars trace the spiral arms.

An image of NGC 1313 showing the galaxy's a barred spiral shape, with arms emanating outwards in a loose twist from the ends of the bar. Patches of young clusters of stars are present in the arms and to a lesser extent between the arms of the galaxy.
An image of galaxy M82 in X-ray and optical light; X-rays from NuSTAR (purple) and Chandra (blue) that have been combined with optical data from the NOAO 2.1 meter telescope (gold).
Zoom-in: Closer field of view than image #1 showing the core of galaxy M82
Zoom-in: Even closer field of view than image #2 with M82 X-2 and M82 X-1 sources labeled

A cluster of stars almost completely surrounded by a colorful and detail-filled nebula. In this composite image the Chandra data is shown in purple, optical data from Hubble is shown in red, green and blue and infrared data from Spitzer is shown in red.

This composite image of NGC 6338 contains X-ray data from Chandra (displayed in red) that shows hot gas as well as cooler gas detected with Chandra and XMM-Newton (shown in blue) that also emits X-rays. The Chandra data have been combined with optical data from the Sloan Digital Sky Survey, showing the galaxies and stars in white.

Jupiter is shown with several important components of its magnetosphere in this artist's representation. The planet's magnetic field is represented by soft purple lines that connect its north and south magnetic poles. Jupiter's brilliant auroras glow at the poles, while the bright areas to the left and right of the planet's equator represent the regions of most intense charged particle radiation — Jupiter's inner radiation belts.

The primary image of this release features a small galaxy cluster plowing through a larger one, leaving behind a wake of hot gas. 

The large galaxy cluster resembles a round cloud of neon blue squiggles, more dense on our left than on our right. Just below the center of this cloud is a light blue shape packed with blurry squiggles. It resembles a mushroom cap on its side, with a thin horizontal stem shaped like an umbrella handle sticking out the bottom, pointing to our left. The mushroom cap is hot gas in the smaller galaxy cluster. The umbrella handle is the wake of hot gas. Although, it's important to remember that small is a relative term. Galaxy clusters are the largest structures in the Universe held together by gravity, containing hundreds or even thousands of individual galaxies.

A red line that resembles a vapor trail left by an airplane cuts through the cloud. It extends from the bottom of the mushroom cap to the upper left of the large blue cloud-like galaxy cluster. This
A bright central source surrounded by a cloud of gas (blue) with two distinct cavities in the gas at the top and bottom. Jets extend from the central source into and through the cavities (pink).
A barred spiral galaxy oriented almost face-on with other galaxies present in the background

These two images contain some of the thousands of stars from a new survey by NASA's Chandra X-ray Observatory.

The Lagoon Nebula (left) is an area about 4,400 light years from Earth in the Milky Way galaxy where stars are actively forming. This field-of-view shows the southern portion of a large bubble of hydrogen gas, plus a cluster of young stars. The Chandra data (purple) have been combined with infrared data (blue, gold, and white) from the Spitzer Space Telescope in this composite image.

The image on the right shows the star-forming region called RCW 120, which is also in the Milky Way, but slightly farther away at a distance of about 5,500 light years. This view of RCW 120, which has the same wavelengths and colors as the Lagoon composite, contains an expanding bubble of hydrogen gas, about 13 light years across.

This is an image depicting the amounts of chemical elements present in the human body and the cosmological process that created them. The amounts that make up the human body (by mass) are: Nitrogen 3%, Hydrogen 10%, Carbon 18%, Oxygen 65%, Other 4%. The human body is made of material produced by: Exploding White Dwarfs 1%, Big Bang Fusion 9.5%, Dying Low Mass Stars 16.5%, Exploding Massive Stars 73%.

This vertical panoramic image depicts an area about the center of Milky Way, with the field of view large extending 700 light years above and below the galaxy. The image resembles colorful gas clouds streaked with fine threads, dotted with a handful of brilliant white shapes. Throughout the image are tiny orange and purple dots set against a black backdrop. This rendering was made using a giant mosaic of data from NASA’s Chandra X-ray Observatory and the MeerKAT radio telescope in South Africa. In this release, the image is presented both labeled and unlabeled.

 

Across the center of the image is a horizontal, bright purple cloud with a glowing white core. This is the plane of the Milky Way – the disk where most of the Galaxy’s stars reside. The labeled image indicates that within the glowing white core are several star clusters, clouds of gas and dust, and the supermassive black hole Sagittarius A*. Also in this translucent cloud are thin, wispy streaks of gray that resemble fine ha
A wide field infrared image from NASA's WISE mission that includes a comparatively small box drawn around young star cluster NGC 6231.
A close-up Chandra X-ray image of NGC 6231 showing hundreds of stars.
Image of Sera smiling in front of book shelves and seated at a table.
Image of Daryl in the snow-covered mountains, being licked by a white and black spaniel-type dog. A boy has his arm around the dog and there is a mountain vista behind them.
Black Hole Week logo and an announcement of the question and answer event asking those who want to participate to reply to this thread with questions.

This composite image features the ringed planet Uranus set against the blackness of space. The planet is depicted in blues and pinks, encircled by a near vertical white ring. The blue and white colors represent optical data obtained by the Keck-1 Telescope, and the pink represents X-ray data gathered by NASA's Chandra X-ray Observatory. The blues, which appear as blended, near vertical stripes, range from midnight blue at our right, to teal and even neon sky blue at our left. Across the right half of the planet is a teardrop-shaped patch of neon pink which is more solid near the bottom and somewhat less defined near the top. Several pale blue dots mark the surface of the planet, though none appear in the hot pink patch. The near vertical ring, which is slightly tipped toward our upper-right, is quite thin. It appears white when set against the black background, and pink when it passes in front of the planet's pink patch. Upon closer inspection, other faint, concentric rings can be spot

An infographic about the electromagnetic spectrum. For a larger version of this image, visit: https://bit.ly/3fnNHvV and to learn more through NASA's "Tour of the Electromagnetic Spectrum" materials, visit: https://go.nasa.gov/39q1ZIn
The colorful globe of Saturn's largest moon, Titan, passes in front of the planet and its rings in this true color snapshot from NASA's Cassini spacecraft.

A wide view of space that shows the Andromeda Galaxy from about 11 o'clock to 5 o'clock in the image. NGC 205 is shown to the right of Andromeda's central galactic bulge. NGC 205 is considerably smaller than Andromeda — less than the size of Andromeda's bulge. Both galaxies are labeled.
NGC 1559 is a barred spiral galaxy that has massive spiral arms filled with bundles of stars.

M82 is seen nearly edge-on with its disk crossing from about 1 o'clock to about 7 o'clock in this image from Chandra (where low, medium, and high-energy X-rays are colored red, green, and blue respectively.) Among the 104 point-like X-ray sources in the image, eight so far have been observed to be very bright in X-rays and undergo clear changes in brightness over periods of weeks and years. This means they are excellent candidates to be black holes pulling material from companion stars that are much more massive than the Sun.
